<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Leary     09-16 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Leary,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>'60s Drug Guru Timothy Leary to Have Head Frozen After Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixties drug guru Timothy Leary said he's
signed up to have his head removed and frozen after he dies for
possible resurrection, but he admits the technology is ``a long
shot.''
   ``I don't want to just go belly-up when my Blue Cross runs
out,'' said the 67-year-old former Harvard psychology professor who
once advised the youth of America to ``tune in, turn on and drop
out'' with mind-altering drugs.
   Leary said Thursday he's formalizing a $35,000 agreement to have
his head preserved for posterity in so-called ``cryonic
suspension'' by the Alcor Life Extension Foundation in Riverside.
   ``It's the second dumbest idea in the world,'' Leary said of
cryonics, the practice of freezing the recently dead. ``The first
is that you go to the worms. It's a long shot but it's worth a
try.''
   Alcor is best known for a long-running battle with authorities
about whether an elderly woman client was actually dead when her
head was surgically severed and immersed in liquid nitrogen. A
judge backed Alcor in its refusal to turn in the head for tests,
and the matter remains at a standoff.
   Leary, who recently has been appearing at colleges and
nightclubs after years of relative obscurity, said he has followed
developments in cryonics since 1976, when he wrote a paper on 22
alternatives to ``involuntary, irreversible death.''
   ``He's been interested the last 30 years in any cutting edge
technology,'' explained his agent, Eric Gardner. ``And this, if
you'll pardon the expression, is cutting edge technology.''
   For his $35,000, Leary, who says he is perfecly healthy, would
become a member of the non-profit Alcor foundation. That gives him
the right to have his head surgically removed after death and
immersed in liquid nitrogen at minus 320 degrees Fahrenheit.
   Alcor also freezes entire bodies, but Leary said he couldn't
afford the $100,000 price.
   Mainstream scientists scoff at cryonics, but adherents believe
the essence of a person's mental or spiritual being resides
physically in the brain. That essence could someday be transferred
to a mechanically produced or biologically cloned body, said
Alcor's president, Carlos Mondragon.
   ``There's about as good a chance that they'll be able to bring
you back in 50 years than there is that we'll get a good president
of the United States, or that they'll find a cure for the common
cold,'' Leary said.
   Leary doesn't think his much-publicized drug use ruined his
brain for revival, but is prepared: ``I'd be very happy, if they
don't bring me back, to have it turned over to the neurologists.''
   Alcor has six heads and two complete bodies frozen in concrete
vats of liquid nitrogen, Mondragon said. He said 109 members signed
up to be suspended after they die. The controversy over the head of
85-year-old Dora Kent boosted interest in membership and Leary's
endorsement may do the same, said Mondragon. ``A lot of people may
have negative reactions to Dr. Leary, but people without open minds
don't generally come to us anyway,'' said Mondragon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
