<1ST_LINE>u w AM-PollutionSettlement     09-16 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pollution Settlement,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Allis-Chalmers Agrees to Pay $4.5 Million Penalty For Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Allis-Chalmers Corp. has agreed to pay the
federal government $4.5 million to clean up 13 hazardous waste
sites in seven states, the Justice Department announced Friday.
   The payment agreement was filed in New York City, where
Allis-Chalmers, a Milwaukee-based farm equipment manufacturer, is
reorganizing under Chapter 11 of the Bankruptcy Code in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in New York. The $4.5 million payment is subject
to approval by the federal court.
   The agreement was the result of the Justice Department's program
to make sure certain environmental cleanup issues are addressed
when companies reorganize under federal bankruptcy law, said
Assistant Attorney General Roger J. Marzulla of the Land and
Natural Resources Division.
   Marzulla said the firm pledged to pay the government regardless
of other obligations under the reorganization proceedings.
   The $4.5 million will be distributed to the following sites:
Maxey Flats Nuclear Disposal Site, Morehead, Ky., $325,000; Bluff
Road Landfill, Columbia, S.C., $15,000; Peak Oil, Tampa, Fla.,
$25,000; Conservation Chemical Co. landfill site, Gary Ind.,
$40,000; Northside Sanitary landfill-Envirochem, Zionsville, Ind.,
$30,000; Schmalz Dump Site, Harrison, Wis., $2 million; Ninth
Avenue Dump Site, Gary, Ind., $625,000; Muskego Sanitary Landfill,
Muskego, Wis., $375,000; Brookfield Sanitary landfill (Loth
Disposal Site), Brookfield, Wis., $125,000; Lenz Oil, Lemont, Ill.,
$295,000; U.S. Scrap, Chicago, $625,000; Interstate Transformer,
Ellwood, Pa., $10,000; and Lee's Lane Landfill, Louisville, Ky,
$10,000.
</TEXT>
