<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FetalTissue Bjt   09-16 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fetal Tissue, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Asks Anti-Abortionists If They Can Accept Fetal Tissue
Research</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Committee not expected to arrive at recommendations before
midafternoon EDT; may stand for PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Near the end of two days of scholarly talk
about the ramifications of allowing intentionally aborted fetuses
to be used for medical research, a National Institutes of Health
advisory committee member sharpened the issue with a simple
question:
   Will there ever be a medical benefit ``great enough'' for
anti-abortionists to drop their opposition to using tissue from
induced abortions?
   ``No,'' Kay James, public affairs director of the National Right
to Life Committee, told Joseph B. Martin, chief of neurology at
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston.
   `No,'' said Judi Brown of Stafford, Va., president of the
American Life League.
   A few minutes earlier, Robin Chandler Duke, co-chairwoman of the
Population Crisis Committee based in New York City, had
acknowledged the strong opposition of anti-abortionists and said
she wished there was some way to reach accommodation over the
transplant issue.
   ``But to hold a nation hostage to a minority group who are
opposed to abortion is a tragedy,'' she said. ``They must know that
even if it (abortion) became illegal, it would still be done. It's
just not going to go away. It has been with us since the written
word.''
   Another member of the panel of witnesses, Sam Gorovitz, dean of
the college of arts and sciences at Syracuse University, told
Martin he empathized with his effort to find common ground but
suggested the ``intractable polarity'' of positions just outlined
by his fellow panelists showed that would be impossible.
   In the end, Gorovitz predicted, the special advisory committee
will simply have to settle on ``the position for which the
arguments are best,'' with the realization that one group or the
other will be unhappy.
   ``There is no way out of that,'' Gorovitz said.
   Retired federal appeals court judge Arlin M. Adams of
Philadelphia, the advisory committee chairman, broke the 21-member
committee into smaller groups for informal discussions Thursday
night and again today.
   He planned to bring them together late today in hopes they could
reach consensus on whether to recommend federal approval of using
fetal tissue from induced abortions for research and, if so, what
guidelines to recommend to guard against abuses.
   Adams said he hoped the committee could agree enough by the end
of the day to allow a rough draft of a document that would be
circulated for further discussion with an eye toward having a
formal recommendation ready in time for presentation Dec. 1 to a
standing NIH committee.
   Father Don McCarthy, a Roman Catholic church leader from
Cincinnati, drew a clear distinction between induced abortions and
natural abortions in expressing his opposition to using tissue from
the former.
   ``One might say that the American public becomes accomplices
after the fact for these induced abortions'' if its institutions
embrace policies that could tend to give a medical value to having
an abortion, he said.
   Several committee members used the term ``custom pregnancy'' as
a short way of raising the concern that some woman might become
pregnant just to produce an aborted fetus for research _ either for
financial gain or in an effort to help a sick relative.
   ``I don't think people are as callous about abortion as that
premise suggests,'' said Thomas H. Murray, director of the Center
for Biomedical Ethics at Case Western Reserve University. ``If we
get to that point, I'm deeply worried.''
   Murray said he was convinced that guidelines could be drawn to
ensure that a woman's decision to have an abortion would be kept
totally separate from the decision to allow the remains to be used
for research.
   Robert J. Levine of the Yale University School of Medicine told
the committee his institution has drawn its own guidelines that
would exclude transplanting the tissue of a fetus into a relative
of the mother.
   He said that was done out of safety considerations _ that
whatever caused the disease in the relative might somehow be
present in the offspring's genes _ but coincidentally also serves
to negate concern about ``custom pregnancies.''
</TEXT>
