<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Palau-Shooting     09-16 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palau-Shooting,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President's Shooting Death Ruled Suicide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0822 to fix category code; Friday is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KOROR, Palau (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gunshot that killed Palau President
Lazarus E. Salii on Aug. 20 was self-inflicted, the government said
Friday.
   ``The inescapable conclusion is that the cause and manner of
death was instantaneous by self-inflicted perforating gunshot wound
of the head,'' said the report issued by the offices of Palau's
attorney general and director of the Bureau of Public Safety.
   The report cited ballistic tests conducted at the FBI laboratory
in Washington, D.C., an autopsy report from forensic pathlogist Dr.
Hee-Yong Park on Guam and statements from witnesses.
   Salii, 51, was the second elected president of the tiny island
republic in the Western Pacific. He was elected in August 1985 to
succeed Haruo I. Remeliik, who was assassinated two months earlier.
Three Palau men convicted at trial in connection with Remeliik's
death were acquitted on appeal.
   Salii's wife found his body slumped in his chair in a small
sitting room in their house, the report said.
   A .357-caliber Magnum revolver that Salii had borrowed from a
police officer about four months earlier was found on the floor by
his feet, it said.
   The autopsy report said Salii placed the gun muzzle at his left
temple and fired. The bullet passed through his head.
   Palau, about 4,500 miles southwest of Hawaii and 600 miles east
of the Philippines, has been beset by economic and political
problems, including a lengthy legal dispute over its future
political status with the United States.
   Palau, with a population of 15,000, is the last political entity
of the Trust Territory of the Pacific Islands and has yet to
conclude an agreement on a proposed Compact of Free Association
with the United States.
</TEXT>
