<HEAD>American Tourists Robbed Of Jewelry Bought On European Holiday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four U.S. tourists lost $173,000 worth of
jewelry purchased during a two-month European tour when their car
was broken into and their luggage stolen, police said.
   The two retired couples from Palm City, Florida, had left their
valuables in a car Wednesday while sight-seeing in Bath, the
ancient Roman spa city 100 miles west of London, said Inspector
Graham Cawley of the Avon and Somerset police.
   The couples were at the end of a two-month tour of Europe during
which they had bought several pieces of second-hand jewelry,
including bracelets, rings and brooches, most of it gold, Cawley
said.
   Cawley would not release the tourists' names. He said he did not
know whether the jewelry was purchased for personal use or for
resale in the United States.
