<DOCNO> AP880916-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0457EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-APArts:JapanTV     09-16 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP Arts: Japan TV,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vintage American TV Shows Ride Nostalgia Boom In Japan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Captain James T. Kirk of the starship Enterprise
looks skyward from a lonely, wind-blown planet and says:
``Entapuraizu, riku kara tenso shite kure.''
   For those listening to the English version of ``Star Trek,''
Captain Kirk would have said ``Enterprise, beam me up.''
   Dubbed in Japanese, ``Star Trek'' is just one of many vintage
American TV programs boldly exploring the late-night Tokyo airwaves.
   During a typical week, insomnia-stricken viewers in the Tokyo
area can watch ``Burke's Law,'' the 1960s adventure show starring
Gene Barry as a debonair Los Angeles police chief; Rod Serling's
``The Twilight Zone,'' the acclaimed science fiction series;
``Bonanza,'' one of television's longest running Westerns, starring
Lorne Greene; ``The Beverly Hillbillies,'' the antics of a
backwoods family in Los Angeles' elitist neighborhood; ``Mission:
Impossible,'' the acclaimed Bruce Geller adventure series; and
``The Addams Family,'' a sitcom based on Charles Addams' bizarre
magazine cartoon characters.
   ``I don't have any statistics on this,'' said Yoshihiro Mishima
of the TV Tokyo network, ``but we think the people who stay up to
watch these programs are looking for a bit of the good old days,
when they might have been too young to watch the original
broadcasts.''
   Mishima said the viewers are mainly college students or adults
in their 30s. ``It's part of the `retro boom,''' he said, referring
to a recent trend among some Japanese to seek out things from the
past.
   But American TV shows are nothing new to the Japanese audience.
``There have been American programs on Japanese TV for decades,
going back to `Ben Casey' and `Rawhide,''' Mishima said. ``They've
lost popularity to domestic programing, but people still watch them
to get a look at America.''
   Yuji Tagami, an editor with TV Station magazine, added, ``They
can develop devoted fans, but ratings for late-night American
programs in general are not very high.''
   Limited viewership did not stop the Tokyo Broadcasting System
from putting the ``Nostalgic American TV'' series on its schedule
last October. Since March, the series has included: ``Surfside 6,''
a '60s detective series set in Miami Beach, starring Troy Donahue
and Van Williams; ``Combat!'' the longest of the World War II
adventures, starring the late Vic Morrow; and ``Superman,''
starring George Reeves.
   ``Ratings aren't a good way to judge late-night television
shows' popularity. In that time slot, viewership is small and more
personal. Viewers are more attached to what they watch,'' said
Masato Ueda, TBS producer of the series.
   To young viewers, the appeal of the rejuvenated old programs is
in their ``newness,'' Ueda said.
   ``We decided to go with the series when we went on the 24-hour
broadcasting schedule, and though the `retro boom' was a part of
the decision, we wanted to give young people something completely
new, which to them these programs are.''
   Many of the American programs also feature bilingual broadcasts,
with the original English-language dialogue simultaneously aired on
a subchannel available on specially equipped TV sets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ReaganSetsAgenda Bjt   09-16 0661</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan Sets Agenda, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Dukakis Lines Up With Reagan _ Sort Of</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When President Reagan switched the other day
and decided to release overdue payments to the United Nations, it
was another sign that as far as U.S. foreign policy is concerned
his views have undergone extensive alteration since he entered the
White House nearly eight years ago.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater explained the surprising
switch on the dues as based on a determination by Reagan that the
United Nations had ``reformed its operation.''
   That doesn't alter the fact, however, that one of the tenets of
the political philosophy that nurtured Reagan and gave identity to
his pursuit of the presidency was severe skepticism of the United
Nations.
   Conservatives always have complained that the United States paid
a disproportionate share of the U.N. bills while serving as a
convenient target of the Soviet bloc and the so-called non-aligned
countries.
   But Reagan told the State Department to ante up, and another
corner was turned. In his twilight months in the White House only
his commitment to guerrillas trying to overthrow the Sandinista
government in Nicaragua remains uncolored by the pragmatic fact
that the Contras are not making much headway.
   On arms control, after campaigning in 1980 against all major
accords with the Soviet Union and putting negotiations on a back
burner for months, Reagan gradually adopted a stance that even
diehard opponents grudgingly acknowledged was far friendlier to
arms control than they had expected.
   They still are worried he may try to unravel the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty before heading home to California,
but the new 1987 accord to ban intermediate-range nuclear missiles
is safely on the books.
   It stands as the only U.S.-Soviet agreement to eliminate an
entire category of nuclear weapons, and it was negotiated on
Reagan's watch.
   Meanwhile, four summit meetings with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev have produced a conciliatory stance in the White House
that is in striking contrast to early Reagan rhetorical flourishes
that included castigating Moscow as an ``evil empire.''
   Until November 1985, he was the first American president since
Herbert Hoover not to have met with a Soviet leader. Now he has
held more one-on-one superpower summits than any of them.
   Ironically, Reagan has moderated his arms control policy to such
an extent that Michael Dukakis, who is a liberal Democrat,
suggested this week in outlining a nuclear missile strategy agenda
that his views were not that far from the president's.
   The biggest difference is over Reagan's Strategic Defense
Initiative. Dukakis said he would ``stop pouring billions and
billions of dollars'' into the pursuit of a space-based defense
against Soviet ballistic missiles. But he said he would continue a
modest research program into possible missile defenses.
   The Republican candidate, Vice President George Bush, who
projected himself in 1980 as a moderate alternative to Reagan's
deep conservatism, is working overtime, meanwhile, to align himself
with Reagan's foreign policy initiatives. His pitch essentially is
that he would continue along the same course if he is elected.
   Having been part of the administration, Bush's job in lining up
with Reagan policies is hardly as difficult as the task confronting
Dukakis.
   But the Democratic candidate's agenda on weapons moved him
closer to Reagan.
   Dukakis has voiced concerns about the costs of the B-1 bomber
and the Midgetman missile, but he endorsed production of the
Trident II submarine-launched missile and four other weapons.
   More significant, perhaps, was his vow that ``We'll use force
when it's necessary to protect our territory, our citizens or our
vital interests; to meet our treaty commitments; and to deter or to
respond to terrorist attacks.''
   The words were Dukakis's but if you close your eyes and let your
mind drift back to 1980 they might just as well have been Ronald
Reagan's.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid has covered diplomacy for The
Associated Press since 1973.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
