<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     09-16 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A New Edition of `Forbidden Broadway' Opens Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ladies and gentlemen, sharpen your scalpels. The
show that dares to comment on Patti LuPone's diction, Madonna's
acting ability, Nell Carter's figure and Sarah Brightman's overbite
has returned with malice and entertainment for all.
   ``Forbidden Broadway 1988,'' which arrived Thursday at
off-Broadway's Theater East, is the latest edition of Gerard
Alessandrini's vest-pocket musical revues that mercilessly spoof
the Broadway theater. And it's the best version of the show yet.
   In more than 25 musical sketches, a hard-working company of
four, plus pianist Philip Fortenberry, takes aim at some of
Broadway's biggest hits including ``Les Miserables,'' ``The Phantom
of the Opera,'' ``M. Butterfly,'' ``Speed-the-Plow,'' ``Anything
Goes'' and ``Into the Woods.'' They score a bull's-eye nearly every
time.
   Alessandrini, who devised the show and supplied the new lyrics
as well as the direction, is a master at deflating bombast.
Consider his blitz of ``Les Miserables'' _ a mock mini-musical that
deflates the big Broadway blockbuster. It's not easy simulating
Trevor Nunn's turntable staging, but Alessandrini comes up with
credible and hilaroius copy of it here. But then he also supplies a
chandelier for something called ``The Phantom of the Musical,'' a
duet for a masked Andrew Lloyd Webber and a buck-toothed Miss
Brightman.
   The author is equally effective at lancing big-time
personalities. There's a narcissistic Miss LuPone mushmouthing a
Cole Porter-style ditty called ``I Get a Kick Out of Me.'' Or an
exasperated David Mamet, author of ``Speed-the-Plow,'' singing, to
the tune of ``The Rain in Spain,'' ``We strain in vain to train
Madonna's brain.''
   The performers, particularly the two women, are superb mimics.
Toni DiBuono does a terrific LuPone, and a powerhouse Ethel Merman
who battles it out on stage in a duet with a relentlessly perky
Mary Martin, played by Roxie Lucas. Miss Lucas also lacerates
Elaine Stritch, parodying her ``Ladies Who Lunch'' number in
``Company'' with a song called ``Ladies Who Screech.''
   The evening reaches the height of demented lunacy when Miss
DiBuono and Michael McGrath take on Kiri Te Kanawa and Jose
Carreras and the practice of using opera stars to record famous
Broadway scores. Here Alessandrini has them singing a song from the
rock musical ``Grease.'' Equally effective is McGrath's explanation
of the bizarre plot of ``M. Butterfly,'' done to the strains of
``Poor Butterfly.''
   David B. McDonald lends his booming voice to an effective sendup
of Joseph Papp, called ``Papp the Knife,'' and Papp's practice of
butchering the classics. He also leads the audience in a Sondheim
sing-along called ``Into the Words.''
   ``Forbidden Broadway'' seems to renew itself every season with
the influx of new shows. Right now, you can imagine Alessandrini
looking forward with glee to ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway'' and Peter
Allen in ``Legs Diamond,'' both big musicals scheduled to open this
season. They should provide particularly good material for his
special brand of merry meyhem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
