<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sweden-Immigration     09-16 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Immigration,0934</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farming Town Resists Immigrants, Raising Questions Of Racism</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SJOBO, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's heartland is challenging
Sweden's generous refugee policy, raising fears that latent racism
may be bubbling to the surface.
   It's happening in Sjobo, a small southern farming town where the
tallest building is three stories high, downtown is one street, and
everyone knows just about everybody else.
   The 15,000 citizens of the town and the surrounding district are
holding a referendum Sunday on whether to accept about 30 refugees.
   It is a local issue, but the question is drawing national
attention and is dominating the final weeks of the campaign for the
parliamentary election on the same day.
   Government figures say that from 1983 to 1987, 62,600 people
sought political asylum in Sweden, a country of 8.4 million people,
making it the highest per capita rate in Europe.
   Last year 245 of Sweden's 284 municipal districts took in 18,000
newcomers as the government tried to spread them outside Stockholm
and other cities where housing is scarce.
   When the request came to Sjobo, the town council balked. It
voted last autumn by 25-24 to put the question to a popular vote.
   Residents say the issue has split families, friends and even the
town's only church. Distrust and anger stop people from talking
about it any more, and a sullenness has fallen on the town.
   ``A lot of people are very ashamed. It's terrible,'' said
Madeleine Ramel, head of the local Social Welfare Board. ``The town
has changed.''
   Mrs. Ramel said the fight in Sjobo may spread to other
communities that have been reluctant to take in refugees but that
have been too afraid of public scorn to refuse.
   ``It is dangerous to ignore signals, and what is happening in
Sjobo is one of the signals,'' said Mrs. Ramel.
   The immigration department has said Sjobo could have a say in
which immigrants would be sent. The decision has been postponed
until after the referendum.
   An influx of immigrants from Iran, Lebanon and South America has
spawned a right-wing backlash in France, Denmark and other European
countries, but that has not happened in Sweden.
   ``A lot of Swedes have a negative attitude toward immigrants. It
is normally surpressed, but having a referendum is bringing it to
the surface,'' said Anders Sonnerstedt, a political scientist at
nearby Lund University.
   ``Swedish people are afraid to speak about the refugee question
today, because anyone who speaks out is called a racist,'' said
Per-Ingvar Magnusson, a fertilizer dealer who favors keeping the
immigrants out.
   Magnusson, chairman of the Sjobo branch of the Center Party,
denied he is motivated by racism. He said the town lacks housing
and jobs for its own young people who are moving away, and he
professed astonishment at the attention the town has received.
   ``They make us out to be stupid, fools, farmers who live in
isolation,'' he said in an interview. The town simply wants to take
care of its own first, he said.
   Mrs. Ramel, whose welfare board would handle the immigrants if
they came, dismissed Magnusson's argument. ``It's a silly question.
Why can't 15,000 people take care of 30 more people. I think they
(the opponents) just don't want foreigners here.''
   The nay-sayers in Sjobo have been roundly condemned by national
leaders, the media and the public. One waitress complained that a
customer passing through asked rudely if the restaurant ``has
racism on the menu.''
   Magnusson said he gets hundreds of letters of support from other
Swedes. Many of them ``don't even dare to sign their names'' for
fear of being branded as a racist.
   Sweden's few openly racist groups are dismissed as an
insignificant fringe. But the fight in Sjobo involves farmers who
represent Sweden's roots, and a political party with long and
illustrious history.
   The issue was an embarrassment to the national Center Party
during its election campaign, and party leader Olof Johansson
threatened to expel the Sjobo members. ``They have made their last
mistake in the Center Party,'' he said in a television interview.
   The center-right party governs the local council in a coalition
with the Conservative Party. On the national level, it is in the
opposition against the governing Social Democratic party.
   Set serenely among woodlands and wheatfields, Sjobo seems hardly
the scene for a national confrontation. The town of 4,000 is laid
out in neat rows of single-story homes with well-trimmed gardens.
   The Immigration Department has said the state would pay for
housing and educating the immigrants.
   But Magnusson said the problem goes deeper. He said the
government must curb an unchecked flood of immigrants.
   Magnusson cited police reports that more than half the refugees
seeking to live in Sweden destroy their passports on their way here
to make it difficult to deport them.
   Police say as many as 25,000 people may be in Sweden under false
identities and that as many as 15 wanted terrorists move here every
year.
   Among them were a Palestinian who was killed by a car bomb in
Athens, Greece in July, and a wanted terrorist from the Irish
Republican Army who was arrested in August by Dutch police while
traveling through the Netherlands.
   ``There are terrorists, drug dealers and criminals coming in,''
said Magnusson. ``If the government had more control of handling
refugees, there would be no need for a vote in Sjobo.''
</TEXT>
