<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Harvard-Mideast     09-16 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Harvard-Mideast,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvard Creates Institute Designed To Foster Mideast Cooperation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harvard University's John F. Kennedy
School of Government has announced an institute designed to foster
regional cooperation in the Middle East on health, welfare and
economic development.
   Kennedy School Dean Graham T. Allison said Thursday the
Institute for Social and Economic Policy in the Mideast will bring
six to 10 Arab and Israeli public managers to the school's
mid-career program for public officials.
   The institute also will develop field projects in the Middle
East in areas such as child health care and economic development in
the Gaza Strip, he said.
   Fomer Health, Education and Welfare Secretary Joseph Califano
will head the institute's board of advisers. Cardinal John
O'Connor, the archbishop of New York; former Secretary of State
Alexander M. Haig Jr.; and Dallas investor Leo Fields will serve as
vice chairmen.
</TEXT>
