<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hurricane-Mexico-Tourists     09-16 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Mexico-Tourists,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Tourist Rides Out Storm In Rental Car, Reading Horror
Story</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Bowden of London came to this
Caribbean resort to get a tan. He ended up spending a dark day in a
rented car, reading a horror story as he rode out Hurricane
Gilbert, the worst storm on record.
   ``There was a lot of corrugated material flying about all over
the place,'' said Bowden, 35. ``It was like being in an aircraft in
turbulence. You felt the wind was going to lift you away.''
   Other tourists crammed into Cancun's hotels and shelters were
becoming impatient by Thursday, the day after Gilbert blasted the
Yucatan Peninsula with 160-mph winds and driving rain.
   Food was in short supply, power was still out, the airport was
closed and roads out of the city nearly impassable.
   ``Hysterical,'' one hotel receptionist said of the stranded
vacationers.
   About 6,000 tourists were trapped in Cancun when this normally
idyllic resort of sandy beaches and warm, clear waters turned into
a fury of waves and wind in the predawn hours Wednesday.
   Bowden drove into Cancun Tuesday, only hours before the storm
hit.
   By then, tourists at the beachfront resorts were being moved
into shelters and hotels in the old part of the city, about six
miles away.
   As the hurricane neared, Bowden also sought refuge in the city,
but was turned away by hotels already jammed with guests from the
luxury resorts.
   As Gilbert roared into Cancun, Bowden said he curled up in his
car with a book, a horror story involving a magic carpet.
   ``I got sick of it. If I'd had some postcards I would have
written them to send to people, but I did not have any,'' he said.
   Bowden said he watched as airborne debris zipped past his car.
But even worse was the sound of two support lines of a radio
transmission tower twanging ``like a badly tuned guitar'' in the
wind.
   Shortly after dawn, the storm still raging, he said left the
car, looking for some place to get a cup of coffee. Unsuccessful,
he returned to the vehicle.
   About 150 tourists who were given refuge at city hall had
nothing but milk and cookies to eat.
   ``I think everyone's nerves are starting to get shot now,'' said
Joseph Camuccio of Philadelphia, who had arrived in Cancun Sunday.
   ``Everyone is going to the same bathroom,'' he said. ``There is
no water or electricity. They (the toilets) don't flush or
anything. Everybody wants to get out.''
   Some tourists said they were given virtually no warning that a
dangerous storm was on the way.
   Maggie Frederick of Petaluma, Calif., said she had just gotten
dressed to go out for the evening Tuesday when there was a knock
her hotel room door and a voice said: ``You're being evacuated.''
   ``I started laughing thinking they were joking,'' she said.
   Tom Long of Effingham, Ill., who speaks no Spanish, said the
language barrier added to the confusion. He and his wife, Jackie,
were in Cancun to celebrate their fifth wedding anniversary.
   Nabil Nachawati, of Arlington, Texas, said his two children,
ages 3 and 5, took the storm well. When the sky began to darken,
the two children curled up and went to sleep.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
