<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0323EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DingoBaby     09-16 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dingo Baby,0804</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Clears Lindy Chamberlain After Sensational Murder Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said a wild dog snatched
and ate her newborn child has been found innocent of murder.
   The court decision closes the book on an 8-year-old case that
divided Australia and captured headlines worldwide.
   The Northern Territory Court of Criminal Appeal in Darwin on
Thursday overturned Lindy Chamberlain's sentence of life
imprisonment with hard labor. She spent about four years in jail.
   It also quashed the conviction of her husband, Michael, a pastor
for the Seventh Day Adventist Church, on charges of being an
accessory to murder.
   Mrs. Chamberlain, who was born in New Zealand, became a
household name in 1980 when she said a dingo, or native Australian
dog, carried off her 6-week-old daughter Azaria while the family
camped in the Outback near Ayers Rock, a sacred aboriginal site.
   Replete with rumors of black magic and a suicide that led to a
break in the case, the Chamberlain story made Page 1 in newspapers
across Australia and elsewhere. All Australians seem to have an
opinion on the woman's story.
   In 1987, she was pardoned but her conviction was not overturned.
Thursday's innocent verdict finally sealed the case shut.
   Gasps filled the courtroom when the decision was announced.
Michael Chamberlain clasped his hands to his head and wept. His
wife, who had been staring at the judges, slumped in her seat.
   ``The law of the land holds the Chamberlains to be innocent,''
said the ruling.
   The Chamberlains' defense attorney had accused the Northern
Territory government, which originally prosecuted the pair, of
waging a ``modern-day witchunt.''
   The lawyer, Stuart Tipple, said the Chamberlains were waiting to
see whether the government would pay the couple compensation before
deciding on any civil action. Earlier, he said the couple was
seeking about $750,000.
   After the verdict, Mrs. Chamberlain, a tiny woman in high-heeled
red shoes, was thronged by curious onlookers as she strode with
straightened shoulders from the courthouse.
   The crowd clamored for a closer look as the couple made their
way through the large crowd to their car. Construction workers
nearby downed tools and whistled while others jeered.
   The Chamberlain drama began on a cold night in August 1980 when
Mrs. Chamberlain cried out at the family camp side at Ayers Rock,
central Australia, ``A dingo's got my baby!''
   At first, the Chamberlains' story was believed. But when the
couple went to court, Mrs. Chamberlain was accused of slitting her
baby's throat.
   The baby's body was never found, but bloodstains were found in
the couple's tent.
   On Oct. 29, 1982, the Chamberlains were found guilty and Mrs.
Chamberlain was sentenced to life in prison, where she to gave
birth to a second daughter, Kahlia. Her husband was sentenced to a
suspended 18-month sentence.
   The couple has two other sons, Aiden and Reagan. Although the
prosecution never alleged black magic as a motive, many Australians
have linked the death of baby Azaria to witchcraft and satanic
rites, believing the children have mystical names.
   The family denied rumors that the name Azaria meant ``sacrifice
in the wilderness.'' Many Australians also thought it significant
that the death occurred at Ayers Rock, sacred to aborigines in one
of the most remote parts of Australia.
   In February 1986, a remarkable breakthrough in the case came
when a British tourist jumped off the huge monolith to his death.
   Aboriginal trackers investigating the suicide found the tattered
remains of Azaria's jacket, which Mrs. Chamberlain swore the baby
was wearing the night she vanished.
   The discovery of the jacket proved that Mrs. Chamberlain had not
been lying about at least one aspect of her baby's death and
prompted officials to reopen the case.
   Five days after the jacket was found, Mrs. Chamberlain was
released from prison. On June 2, 1987, a federal judge pardoned her
and said Mrs. Chamberlain may have told the truth when she said the
dingo snatched and ate the baby.
   ``Indeed, the evidence affords the view that a dingo may have
taken her,'' federal Judge Trevor Morling wrote in his opinion.
   But under Australian law, the pardon was as far as Trevor could
go and the Chamberlains returned to court to overturn the
conviction.
   ``There is no satisfaction, no joy, knowing they still believe
you are guilty,'' Mrs. Chamberlain said at the time.
   Although the court case is over, the Chamberlain story will
continue.
   American movie star Meryl Streep recently finished filming a
movie on the case based on a book titled ``Evil Angels.'' The
American release is provisionally called ``A Cry In The Darkness.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0152EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Peru-Inflation     09-16 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Inflation,0800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peruvians Buy Hard Goods as Currency Loses Value</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT SEAVEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With their currency losing ground rapidly in a
spiraling inflation, Peruvians are buying up refrigerators and
other durable goods not likely to lose value as fast as their paper
money, the inti.
   After two years of prosperity, Peruvians are seeing an economic
turnaround that is fueling the fastest increase in consumer prices
ever seen here.
   Independent economists conservatively estimate that inflation
will pass 500 percent this year. Two years ago inflation was 63
percent.
   ``The country is shipwrecked in a sea of paper money,'' said
Sen. Enrique Chirinos, an independent. ``This is a horrifying
perspective and never known before in our history.''
   Consumer prices shot up 30.9 percent in July alone.
   Peruvians are trying to adjust. They say they eat less, work
more and worry a lot.
   ``Now I have to buy less chicken. I use it first for broth and
then stew. It's the only way,'' said housewife Carmen Alegre, while
shopping in Lima's working-class La Aurora market.
   Nearby, tennis shoes costing 500 intis early last year were
selling for 3,000 intis, equivalent to about $25 or half the
minimum monthly wage.
   Cigarettes, often sold singly because many Peruvians cannot
afford entire packs, cost 10 intis each or seven times the January
price.
   Analysts are now concerned that Peru's inflation could boil into
four-digit figures next year.
   The middle class has begun renting spare rooms, tutoring,
knitting and sewing piece work and selling home-cooked food such as
meat-filled ``empanadas'' in streetside stands to make ends meet.
   But Peru's poor, the vast majority of the population, have been
affected the hardest.
   ``The poorest paid people in Peru are earning less money than at
any time since records have been kept,'' The Andean Report, an
economic monthly, said in July.
   An old man begging in the shadow of Lima's downtown government
palace complained recently that inflation was making him poorer.
   ``This fills up fast but the intis are worth nothing,'' he said,
jiggling the dirty plastic cup he waves to passers-by.
   Antonio Reyes, manager of an appliance store, said he telephones
wholesalers every day to get revised prices for the television
sets, stoves and toasters he sells.
   But business has been good, Reyes said, noting customers have
pulled cash from bank accounts where the annual interest is frozen
at 130 percent to buy durable goods, whose value very well could
rise in an inflation.
   ``The only option a saver has with his money is spend it,'' said
the news magazine Caretas. ``Those who do not have the ability to
save will simply have to seek a second job.''
   Guillermo Fernandez, 42, a married accountant with three
children, said he recently began moonlighting as a curbside money
trader on ``Wall Street,'' the name given by Peruvians to Jiron
Ocona, a narrow downtown street where thousands of people every day
now buy dollars as a hedge against inflation.
   He said many of his competitors are also professionals seeking
to supplement inflation-pinched incomes with the small but quick
profits offered by the dollar trade.
   Analysts say Jiron Ocona is also a financial barometer, and the
recent stampede for dollars reflects Peruvians' waning confidence
in the government's ability to improve economic conditions.
   In a recent survey, Peruvians rated the economy as the No. 1
problem, replacing a vicious leftist insurgency that was ranked
first a year ago.
   President Alan Garcia imposed a ceiling on foreign debt payments
on taking office three years ago and then used the money owed
creditors abroad to finance a consumption-based economic
reactivation that pulled Peru from its worst depression of the
century.
   But heavy government spending with an expected deficit of at
least 12 percent and a growing shortage of dollar reserves to
subsidize imports have plunged the nation into recession this year.
   Manufacturing has fallen sharply, while speculation in consumer
and industrial goods is rampant.
   Prosperity reflected by well-stocked stores two years ago has
now been replaced with repeated and prolonged shortages of
medicines, auto parts and basic foods, such as milk and sugar.
   Garcia, a populist whose term ends in 1990, recently installed a
``war economy,'' aimed at holding down wage increases while
allowing prices to rise.
   But economists maintain the measures are not sufficent and
predict inflation will continue to soar.
   ``When inflation hits 500 percent, it could very easily get out
of hand,'' said one leading independent economist, Alejandro Toledo.
   ``This is my biggest concern. There will be a very high social
cost and Peru is not a stable country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
