<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Paul Simon has donated $375,000 from his
appearance on ``Live at the Hard Rock'' to the mobile medical unit
he founded to give free medical treatment to homeless children.
   Before agreeing to do the show, Simon got its sponsor,
Coca-Cola, to agree to give the children's medical service a
minimum donation of $250,000 for his performance with John Cougar
Mellencamp in Los Angeles.
   That, coupled with his $125,000 salary, makes the New York
Children's Health Project $375,000 richer, Dan Klores, a spokesman
for the project, said recently.
   Simon founded the New York Children's Health Project, which
gives free health care to more than 12,000 homeless children in the
city, last November. The mobile medical vans are run by doctors
from the New York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether on crutches or in a wheelchair,
Steve Sanders of the Oak Ridge Boys will go on with the show
despite having broken a bone in his right foot while playing touch
football, a spokeswoman said.
   Sanders, lead singer on the Nashville group's new single,
``Gonna Take a Lot of River,'' broke his right foot while playing
with other band members and their road crew Wednesday night in
Puyallup, Wash., publicist Kathy Gangwisch said Thursday.
   Sanders will stay with the band during its tour to promote the
album ``Monongahela,'' Ms. Gangwisch said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pat Benatar, releasing her first album in
three years, says she's still uncomfortable in the world of stardom.
   ``(The media) are like little piranhas,'' she said recently.
``It's like the worst time of your life, and they find it and
publicize it. It's like finding a scraped knee and rubbing a luffa
on it.''
   Benatar, 35, has avoided the spotlight since her relationship
with her husband, Neil Geraldo, was scrutinized in the press early
in her career.
   Her new album, ``Wide Awake In Dreamland,'' deals with child
abuse and other emotional subjects.
   ``When you have a child, it only cements it further in your mind
what a supreme act of cowardice child abuse is,'' said Benatar, who
has a 3-year-old daughter, Haley.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the tangled breach-of-contract case
between actress Valerie Harper and Lorimar appear close to a
verdict, a judge told lawyers.
   Superior Court Judge William Hogoboom on Thursday ordered
attorneys to return to court today on the likelihood that jurors
will reach a verdict after four days of deliberations.
   The panelists must decide numerous questions centering on which
of the parties was responsible for Ms. Harper's departure from the
TV series, ``Valerie.''
   Lorimar sued her, claiming she was a temperamental star who
breached her contract by quitting the show. But in a countersuit,
Ms. Harper contended she was wrongfully fired and that it was
Lorimar that breached the contract.
