<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Tom Berenger says he enjoys bringing out
the human side of the bad-guy roles he's played, including a
sadistic sergeant in the Oscar-winning ``Platoon'' and a racist in
his new movie, ``Betrayed.''
   The exception, he says, was the maniacal slasher he portrayed in
``Looking for Mr. Goodbar.''
   ``It was such a slimy character with no redeeming qualities,''
Berenger told US magazine in its Oct. 3 issue. ``To me it was like
playing Charles Manson. I had nightmares after I finished shooting.
I felt dirty.''
   Yet when working on a role, Berenger said, he doesn't think
about his character's bad nature. ``You can't think that you're
playing a villain or you'll end up with a cartoon.''
   Berenger recently completed a script about an Irish rebellion
and included a part in it for him: ``the bad guy. Or, at least, the
insensitive one.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert stole the show
from Frank Sinatra, Liza Minnelli and Sammy Davis Jr. in Texas this
weekend, and the trio announced they will begin their national
concert tour in Arizona instead.
   The three had been scheduled to open Saturday at Houston's
Summit Arena but uncertainty over the storm's direction forced them
to shift to a show Sunday at Arizona State University in Tempe,
spokeswoman Susan Reynolds said Thursday. The Houston appearance
was rescheduled.
   Sinatra has performed with Miss Minnelli and Davis, but all
three have never performed together, Ms. Reynolds said.
   The trio have been rehearsing at Davis' California home for
several days.
   ``They're having a lot of fun together,'' she said.
   The tour, dubbed ``Frank, Liza & Sammy _ the Ultimate Event,''
has stops in Atlanta, Miami, Tampa, Fla.; Philadelphia, East
Rutherford, N.J., Uniondale, N.Y., Worcester, Mass., Los Angeles
and Detroit.
