<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former tennis champion Arthur Ashe was released
from a hospital after taking antibiotics to relieve pressure from a
``severe bacterial infection'' in his head, his agent said.
   The infection put pressure on nerves, causing numbness in the
arm of the 45-year-old former Wimbledon and U.S. Open champion,
according to Ted Ewanciw, a spokesman for ProServ, Ashe's agent.
Antibiotics ``relieved the pressure considerably,'' Ewanciw said.
   Myrna Manners, a spokeswoman for New York Hospital, said Ashe
was released Thursday after a weeklong stay during which his
condition was satisfactory throughout.
   Ashe retired from professional tennis in 1980, the year after he
underwent quadruple bypass surgery following a heart attack. He had
a heart attack and double bypass surgery four years later.
   In a telephone interview from his hospital room Monday, he said
the tests he was undergoing were unrelated to his earlier heart
problems.
