<2ND_LINE>BC-Carnegie Hall,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carnegie Hall Stage Adding Acoustic Screens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Movable panels of sound-absorbing material
should improve the sound of music from the stage of Carnegie Hall,
say officials of the famous concert hall.
   The beige, cloth-covered fiberglass panels were unveiled at a
news conference Thursday as a response to complaints from some
critics and musicians about acoustics since the hall's major
renovation two years ago.
   The panels, in nine sections that can be carried on or off stage
by stagehands, cost a total of $30,000, officials said.
   Isaac Stern, president of Carnegie Hall, said the panels are
designed to absorb mid-to-high-range sound.
   ``The result is that you can feel the wood quality of a great
violin and of a piano and woodwinds,'' Stern said, adding he thinks
orchestral blend also will be improved by the panels.
   ``The challenge was to provide a modest amount of absorption
that would absorb only in a certain frequency range,'' said
Lawrence P. Goldman, Carnegie Hall vice president and director of
real estate planning and development.
