<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Les Black isn't one to shirk his
responsibilites, but then he also didn't count on them entailing
any heavy lifting.
   The lawyer, who earned the job of field driver by dint of being
the town's most recently married man, refused to round up a stray
800-pound bull calf when called to perform his task.
   ``I said I was off duty,'' he joked Thursday. ``I consider the
position of field driver to be a desk job.''
   Black was married May 7, a few weeks before he was appointed to
the post at Town Meeting according to a 200-year-old tradition in
this central Massachusetts town of 600 people.
   ``I suppose 200 years ago, when everybody knew something about
cows and bulls, it made more sense,'' he said.
   He was called to the job Monday for the first time, when a calf
was discovered in a back yard.
   ``I don't know one end of a cow from another,'' he said. ``I was
very lucky there was someone there who did.''
   David Young, the selectmen's chairman, and employees of Young's
lumber company corralled the calf.
   Black said he was called only as a courtesy.
   ``Nobody really calls the field driver and expects him to chase
a bull,'' he said. ``A couple of chickens I could handle, but
that's it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Bill Cosby may show up on his TV
show this season wearing a Navy football practice jersey.
   As part of a wager with the Naval Academy superintendent, Cosby
will don the jersey if the Midshipmen defeat Temple in football
Saturday at Navy-Marine Corps Memorial Stadium.
   But if Temple wins, Rear Adm. Virgil L. Hill Jr. will proclaim
Cosby, a Temple alumnus, to be an honorary chief petty officer in
the Navy.
   Navy goes into the game undefeated, with victories over James
Madison and Delaware. Temple is winless against much tougher
competition, Syracuse and Alabama.
</TEXT>
