<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Yellowstone-Ecologists     09-16 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yellowstone-Ecologists,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ecologists Say `Let It Burn' Policy Is Sound</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You don't preserve a forest by putting out all
fires, ecologists observe in defending the ``let it burn'' policy
of the National Park Service.
   The forest will keep changing as plant and animal species kept
down by periodic natural fires establish themselves, and, ``You're
going to culminate in a few species that can out-compete the
others,'' said Jonathan Roughgarden, professor of biological
sciences at Stanford University.
   ``It must be understood that nothing is preserved by stopping
burning,'' said Roughgarden, who was a member of a panel for
reporters organized by the American Association for the Advancement
of Science on Thursday.
   The panel was trying to call attention to ecology, the science
that studies the relationships of organisms with their
environments. Today's issue of Science, the weekly scientific
journal of the association, has a special section on the subject.
   The word ``ecology'' is not properly a synonym for
``environment,'' Roughgarden observed at one point: ``It is not
something you should be for or against. It is simply there.''
   Others on the panel _ who were quick to point out they were not
specialists in fire ecology _ said government agencies should not
return to the days of trying to put out all fires and the Forest
Service was widely using its anti-fire cartoon symbol of Smoky the
Bear.
   However, they said revisions in the ``let it burn'' policy might
be desirable in light of the burning of half of Yellowstone
National Park this summer.
   ``A backlash returning us to Smoky the Bear would be a larger
disaster than the fires,'' said Henry Wilbur, professor of zoology
at Duke University.
   ``The worst possible thing that could happen would be to go back
to a total fire-suppression policy,'' said Robert V. O'Neill, a
research ecologist at Oak Ridge National Laboratory in Tennessee.
   Fire suppression brings ``reduced landscape diversity, which can
cause the transmission of disturbances such as fire, or a pest,''
said O'Neill. The loss of diversity is ``a brand-new problem ... a
new area of research.''
   ``There remains a good ecological basis for the plan of
controlled burning'' that government agencies follow, said
Roughgarden. ``Without fire you simply obtain an entirely different
vegetation type.''
   Though the National Park Service has been using controlled
burning in some parks, it had not been used in Yellowstone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0039 </DOCNO>
