<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TextileBill     09-16 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Textile Bill,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textile Bill Supporters Worried Over Times Squeeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile-state lawmakers, racing to gain
approval of their embattled import-limiting bill before Congress
adjourns, confess anxiety over fresh delays being threatened in the
House.
   ``They could outdistance us, we just don't have that much time
in this Congress,'' Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., said Thursday
after the Senate approved the bill 59-36 in a rerun of action it
took last week.
   Designed to protect American industry from foreign competition,
the bill won approval last week only to remain bottled up in the
Senate when opponents seized on a technicality to delay it.
   Thursday's vote freed the bill from that snarl and sent it to
the House.
   The bill would freeze textile and apparel imports at 1987 levels
and limit growth to 1 percent annually starting next year. It would
hold nonrubber footwear imports to 1987 levels and ban further
increases in foreign producers' share of the U.S. market.
   Congress has been fighting over new import curbs for three
years, with sponsors saying they are needed to save both American
jobs and an industry that is vital to the nation's defense. Critics
concede apparel companies have problems but say the textile
industry is flourishing.
   Indeed, opponents credit stepped up competition from overseas
with prodding the textile industry to modernize. They attribute a
wave of layoffs since the early 1980s to increased automation.
President Reagan vetoed an earlier version of the bill in 1985,
saying it would narrow consumer choices and cost more jobs than it
would save.
   The current version is moving slowly forward amid threats of
another presidential veto.
   ``The president's going to veto it, fortunately, and I hope that
we have the votes to sustain the veto,'' Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore.,
told the Senate. ``America cannot turn its back on the world. It's
going to be part of it, and, frankly, I'd rather participate in
it.''
   Textile forces had hoped that the House would give swift
approval to the four changes that the Senate made since the House
passed the bill a year ago.
   But the House Ways and Means Committee voted Wednesday to
negotiate the differences in a House-Senate conference committee.
   ``A conference just delays the time,'' Hollings complained to
reporters Thursday after the Senate's action.
   The Ways and Means action Wednesday appeared to dash textile
supporters' hopes that the Senate changes would get a stamp of
approval and a quick trip to the White House. But House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas, said it was not certain the measure would go to a
conference committee.
   The president can prevent a bill from becoming law when Congress
is not in session merely by not signing it. This is called a pocket
veto. Textile forces are trying to avoid one, saying it would lower
the political price paid by the administration with elections
coming by keeping the spotlight off the issue.
   The House and Senate have set an adjournment target date of Oct.
5.
   Avoiding a pocket veto and forcing Reagan to actually use his
veto pen also just could give textile forces a chance to try for an
override and pass the measure into law over the president's
objections.
   The bill has not demonstrated that it can gain the two-thirds
support needed for an override, but Hollings said that he could
produce enough votes in the Senate if it came to a showdown.
   There are only four differences between the House and Senate
versions.
   _The House bill would freeze imports at 1986 levels and textile
forces already have said they are prepared to change that to the
1987 levels specified in the Senate version.
   _A provision of the House bill would set up a one-year pilot
program under which the government would auction off import
licenses to U.S. importing firms.
   _To muster farm support, the Senate attached a provision that
would guarantee textile-exporting nations greater quotas in the
U.S. market if they increased their purchases of American farm
goods.
   _The Senate bill would establish a special quota for imported
silk neckties; the House version has no such provision.
</TEXT>
