<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cavazos     09-16 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cavazos,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Recommends Confirmation Of Cavazos As Education Secretary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laruo Cavazos, president of Texas Tech
University, is just one step away from becoming the nation's top
educator and the first Hispanic member of a president's Cabinet.
   The Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee on Thursday
unanimously recommended that Cavazos be confirmed as the next
education secretary. A vote by the full Senate is expected next
week.
   ``I would be very surprised if anybody voted against Larry,''
said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
   Cavazos, the 61-year-old son of a south Texas cattleman and a
registered Democrat, would serve until the next president takes
office in January, although Gramm said he believed Cavazos would
stay on if George Bush wins the November election.
   President Reagan nominated Cavazos last month to succeed
outgoing Education Secretary William Bennett.
   Cavazos testified before the Senate committee last week that he
would push for increased education spending.
   ``It is vital we have a Department of Education that speaks up
for every citizen in the area of education. There is not a problem
in the United States that could not be solved with education,''
Cavazos said.
   Cavazos is the first Hispanic to serve as president of Texas
Tech, and is also the school's first graduate to hold the post. He
is president of the Texas Tech medical school, although he is not a
medical doctor.
</TEXT>
