<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Credit     09-16 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Credit,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Credit-Repair Clinics Draw More Attention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Credit-repair companies, little known before
the 1980s, have increasingly become the target of law enforcement
agencies because of their deceptive practices, say federal
officials.
   The companies promise to help remove derogatory information from
individuals' credit files, and charge as much as $2,000 for the
service.
   Ms. L. Jean Noonan, an official in the Federal Trade
Commission's bureau of consumer protection, told a House
subcommittee Thursday ``it appears that a substantial segment of
the industry engages in deceptive advertising and sales practices.''
   Kenneth P. Walton, inspector-deputy assistant director of the
FBI's criminal investiative division, told the panel of a recent
case involving Credit-Rite Inc of Palmyra, N.J., which defrauded at
least 9,000 consumers of $2.3 million in a credit-repair scheme in
15 states and the District of Columbia.
   The investigation resulted in three convictions with the
founder-president, James T. Gray, being sentenced to seven years in
prison, Jeffrey Roberts, former director of franchising, receiving
a prison sentence of 15 months, and David Gray, credit-repair
manager, receiving three years probation.
   The clinics take advantage of the law that gives consumers the
right to challenge the information about them that credit bureaus
have on file. This provision requires a credit bureau to verify the
information upon request, generally within 30 days. If verification
is not completed on time, the disputed data must be deleted.
   Under the law, individuals who feel their credit records have
inaccuracies can go directly to a local credit bureau and ask that
they be corrected. However, accurate derogatory information can
remain as part of an individual's credit history for seven years
or, in the case of a bankruptcy, for 10 years.
   Walter R. Kurth, president of Associated Credit Bureaus Inc., a
trade association representing over 1,200 consumer credit bureaus,
said, ``The wrong being committed by credit clinics is the promise
held out to intimidated consumers, that by some magic a credit
clinic can accomplish things that the consumer cannot accomplish
and that false promises, rooted in half truths, will cost the
consumer several hundred dollars or more.
   ``The illness of a poor credit history can only be cured by time
and careful reconstruction of a consumer's payment history with
creditors in the future,'' Kurth told the House Banking consumer
affairs subcommittee.
   The subcommittee is considering legislation, introduced by
Chairman Frank Annunzio, D-Ill., which would restrict the practices
of credit-repair clinics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
