<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SmithCroquet     09-16 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Smith Croquet,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Dedicates Nation's First Collegiate Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHAMPTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's first college croquet
court will be dedicated next week to the professor who raised
$16,000 to build it, despite what he described as Smith College's
embarrassment by the playing field.
   ``My level of enthusiasm (for the dedication ceremony) is not
particularly high by this time,'' said Richard B. Young, a
literature professor emeritus. ``The playing court has been around
for months.''
   The 105-by-84-foot manicured lawn is the first regulation
croquet court on an American college campus. It was built last year
with donations from alumnae and friends.
   College President Mary Maples Dunn will shoot the first wicket
at the Sept. 24 ceremony naming the court after Young. Smith's team
will give a demonstration of the sport, which evokes images of
gentry in white dress.
   The field's first tournament opened to little fanfare last April
at the 2,000-student school, and Young said at the time that the
school was embarrassed by the court.
   ``I'm told that this court promotes the idea that Smith is
elitist,'' he said. ``If it weren't, they'd be out of business.''
   The dedication ceremony planned for that tournament was
postponed because Dunn was out of town, college spokeswoman Debra
Bradley said.
   She said Thursday that the ceremony was rescheduled for
September because Dunn ``wanted the dedication to coincide with a
tournament so people could see the field being used.'' The ceremony
kicks off a weekend tournament involving New England Collegiate
Croquet Association teams.
   The college has denied that the dedication delay had any
connection to a survey that found many students and staff consider
the school elitist.
   Young, 66, who lost one leg and suffered a crippling injury to
his other foot during World War II, had given up on sports until he
discovered croquet and founded the Smith team.
   He said he was ``of course extremely pleased by the naming of
the field,'' but added: ``The timing doesn't galvanize me.''
</TEXT>
