<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EnvironmentRegs     09-16 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Environment Regs,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Chief Pledges No Last-Minute Rules Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the Environmental Protection
Agency said he won't issue any last-minute ``midnight regulations''
as the Reagan administration comes to a close.
   EPA Administrator Lee M. Thomas, in remarks to reporters
Thursday, named only four major regulations he would try to
complete before leaving office in January.
   Thomas said he also would try to nail down arrangements for an
international conference in the next administration to strengthen a
treaty limiting chlorofluorocarbon emissions.
   ``I'm trying to make decisions that are logical and natural, not
speeding it up or slowing it down,'' Thomas said.
   The four major regulations he said he would press for are:
   _New controls on gasoline volatility.
   _Requiring larger gasoline vapor recovery systems on cars.
   _Eventually banning the manufacture or import of asbestos and
asbestos products.
   _Revising the major regulation governing the ``Superfund'' toxic
waste cleanup program.
   Thomas said he was hoping to see the approval of several pieces
of legislation, including a revision of the Clean Air Act setting
new deadlines for cities to comply with federal clean air standards.
   He also held out hope for these other legislative actions:
   _A revision of federal pesticide laws setting deadlines for the
agency to review old chemicals and abolishing the requirement that
the agency pay for inventories of banned products
   _A bill providing $10 million to aid state programs dealing with
radon pollution in the home.
   _A bill clarifying the agency's authority over medical waste.
   ``These are the natural kinds of things for me to complete,''
Thomas said.
   In 1981, the incoming Reagan administration accused Douglas
Costle, EPA administrator for President Carter, as well as heads of
other agencies of hastily putting out regulations and making other
decisions to pre-empt what the new administration could do.
Reagan's appointees revoked several of those actions.
   ``We're not going to wield the signature machine all night long
on Jan. 19,'' Thomas said.
</TEXT>
