<DOCNO> AP880916-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen Bjt   09-16 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen, Bjt,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Looking to Bentsen to Court Reagan Democrats in
the South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As vice presidential candidate Lloyd Bentsen took
the stage carrying Michael Dukakis' message for the South, the
event resembled a reunion for Democrats who once worked together
and won the White House.
   The Texas senator was flanked by Tennessee's top elected
officials _ Gov. Ned Ray McWherter and Sens. Albert Gore and James
Sasser. The audience was filled with cheering local sheriffs,
school board members and party activists.
   ``I know what's happened the last two presidential elections,''
Bentsen told the Shelby County Democratic Party fund-raiser
Thursday night. ``You've seen some of our Democratic friends go
into that voting booth, pull that curtain, and vote for Ronald
Reagan.
   ``Now, we understand that, and we respect that,'' he said,
pausing before the punch line: ``But now we're saying, `Democrats
who voted for Reagan, welcome home, welcome back to our party.'''
   The crowd roared.
   The Dukakis campaign knows that Bentsen can repeat that scene in
the South and Southwest, and it can only hope that the effort will
help score a win on Nov. 8 for the Democratic ticket.
   Tad Devine, who watches the polls and directs the vice
presidential campaign from Dukakis-Bentsen headquarters in Boston,
says Bentsen is ``an effective tool'' for convincing conservative
Democrats they can vote for the Massachusetts governor.
   ``I expect that he'll continue to sort of `credential' Governor
Dukakis before these audiences,'' Devine said in a telephone
interview. ``Everywhere he's been so far, he's been very well
received in terms of the political impact,'' including extensive
coverage and interviews with the local press.
   But there are doubts outside the campaign.
   ```Credentialing' is an academic approach to saying the fella
can't stand on his own two feet,'' said Claibourne Darden, an
Atlanta-based pollster and consultant whose clients include Sen.
Sam Nunn, D-Ga. ``It's like getting a Ph.D. because you can't get a
job.''
   While it's smart for Bentsen to focus on the South and Southwest
_ ``You fish where the fish bite,'' he said _ the vice presidential
candidate can only open the door for the presidential candidate to
walk through.
   ``The question is, how capable is Michael Dukakis at walking
through these doors in the South? The answer so far is not so
good,'' Darden said in a telephone interview.
   Larry Harrington, the Dukakis-Bentsen campaign's Southern
regional director, said the evidence was to the contrary. In the
Memphis hotel ballroom, he pointed out local officials who wouldn't
be caught near the two previous Democratic tickets.
   ``They call them leaders, but really they tend to follow the
voters,'' he said. ``They're still moving toward the ticket.
They're with the ticket.''
   But Harrington acknowledged that Bentsen's easy popularity with
Southern Democrats who voted for Reagan wasn't enough.
   ``You're definitely going to see Dukakis follow up'' with more
Southern trips himself, he said, citing the governor's previous
Southern swings. ``I don't think he (Bentsen) closes the deal.''
   Harrington declined to say which Southern states the Democrats
believe they are capable of winning but Bentsen's schedule this
week follows the scenario the campaign acknowledges privately.
   Besides his native Texas, which is a neck-and-neck battle,
Bentsen was hunting for votes in Louisiana, Tennessee, North
Carolina and Florida. He was in Southern California just last
weekend.
   Lance Tarrance, a Houston-based political consultant for the
GOP, said Oklahoma, Arkansas and Louisiana also were states where
Bentsen helps the Democratic ticket.
   ``But let's be frank _ it's California and Texas,'' with their
47 and 29 electoral votes, the Democrats were after, Tarrance said.
   And although Bentsen had a lot of pride tied up in the Texas
race, ``California is the one that really hurts the Republicans if
it goes to the Democrats,'' he said. Bentsen helped in Southern
California in areas where Dukakis was weak, he said.
   The deep South, especially states such as Alabama, South
Carolina and Mississippi, was very unlikely to produce a win for
the Democrats.
   ``The South because of the Reagan presidency is very strong for
Bush,'' Tarrance said, and Bentsen's strength was more to the West
in oil-producing areas.
   Harrington said it was too early to write off any state,
although he said obviously some were tougher for the Democrats than
others.
   For cautious Southerners, Bush's choice for his running mate,
Dan Quayle, presented problems for the GOP and an opening for
Bentsen and Dukakis, he said.
   ``You can say `President Quayle' in a room full of people and
you get a combination of laughter and look of fear,'' he said.
``Every so often, the vice president tragically has to take that
office.''
   Darden said that while Quayle was unquestionably not as
palatable a vice presidential candidate to Southerners as Bentsen,
he doubted the Texan's presence was having a major impact. He said
people also tended to overestimate the impact of having
locally-elected officials back the ticket.
   ``A lot of people overplay the importance of the
establishment,'' he said. Bentsen ``appeals to that upper middle
class Southern white, and it's hard to peel off that vote from a
Republican.''
   Devine said he expected Bentsen to continue to focus on Texas
and the South and Southwest.
   ``He's not going to just campaign in the South, however,'' he
said. Trips elsewhere ``reinforce his standing as a national
candidate'' and that plays well in Texas and elsewhere, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
