<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0728EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Picnic 1stLd-Writethru a0470 09-16 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Picnic, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Hosts `Simple, 14-Course Supper' For Lawmakers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd, 24 grafs to correct punctuation</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Tom Foley said, it was just ``a simple,
14-course picnic supper'' as President Reagan played host for a
congressional barbecue laced with tart lyrics by a troupe of former
Capitol Hill aides.
   Foley, the Democrat from Washington state who is House majority
leader, traded pleasantries with Reagan at the conclusion of the
annual event on the White House lawn Thursday, which will be the
last for the president and first lady Nancy Reagan.
   As lawmakers and administration officials dined on food from
four tents _ giving them their choice of seafood, Cajun, Western or
Mexican cuisine _ entertainnment was provided by the Capitol Steps,
a group formed six years ago at a Capitol Christmas party.
   The Reagans joined in the applause as the Steps aimed their
satire both at the Reagan administration and Vice President George
Bush.
   The president laughed heartily, for instance, as a member of the
troupe impersonating the Republican presidential nominee, who has
been charting an increasingly independent course, sang:
   ``I sorta ... kinda ... remotely ...
   ``Distantly wanna be like you.''
   In another skit, a singer representing Bush sang to the tune of
``September Song'':
   ``Try to remember
   ``That date in September
   ``The day Japan
   ``Attacked Pearl Harbor.''
   The audience erupted in laughter at the reference to Bush's
speech at an American Legion convention in Louisville on Sept. 7,
in which he said that that day, instead of Dec. 7, was the
anniversary of the attack that plunged the United States into World
War II.
   Democratic nominee Michael S. Dukakis did not get off scot free,
either, as the singers hymned a presidential campaign pitting the
``Duke of Dullness'' against ``Sir George of Kennebunkport.''
   Reagan even burst into laughter at what was probably the
harshest satire of the evening, one in which he was represented as
musing upon his place in history and intoning:
   ``Well ...
   ``Don't know much about history
   ``Don't know much about geography
   ``Don't know much about World War II
   ``Don't know much about who fought who
   ``But I know it followed World War I
   ``If we only fought in the wars we won
   ``What a wonderful world this would be.''
   In his concluding remarks, the president said, ``I want to thank
the Capitol Steps for showing such _ mercy. Now you're all under
arrest.''
   Noting that it would be the last such affair he would host, the
president said, ``After 6 o'clock, we all take off the cleats and
come together as friends and colleagues.''
   Foley told the president, ``Unanimously, we wish you and Mrs.
Reagan thanks, first of all for your many courtesies, and secondly,
as you go in, not to a retirement but a different part of your life
in which I know you'll be concerned as you have been for the future
of this country and for its role in the world, the best of every
happiness, success and satisfaction.''
</TEXT>
