<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Hurricane-Aid     09-16 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Aid,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Planners Step Up Preparations For Gilbert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal emergency planners say they've moved
into high gear in preparing to help remedy whatever damage is
inflicted on south Texas by Hurricane Gilbert.
   Trucks, equipment and personnel were readied Thursday for quick
dispatch to Texas as Gilbert, with maximum sustained winds of 120
mph, marched on across the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``We are bringing every resource we have up to maximum
operational capability in preparedness of relocating and mitigating
this problem,'' said Grant C. Peterson, in charge of the natural
disaster program at the Federal Emergency Management Agency.
   The Pentagon said aircraft at naval air stations all along the
Texas coastline were dispatched to a civilian airport in Midland,
Sheppard Air Force Base and Biggs Army Airfield, all in Texas.
   Navy personnel and dependents were sent to Lackland Air Force
Base, 130 miles inland.
   Naval ships in the Gulf of Mexico were sent out to sea to avoid
the storm.
   Army Maj. Gen. J.D. Smith said procedures were streamlined to
ensure ``this is not a bureaucratic slow-moving turtle.''
   The Pentagon agreed to dispatch active duty military personnel
to back up the Texas National Guard if necessary.
   ``I think it is fair to say that we recognize that we face the
greatest weather threat that we have ever faced in our part of the
country. We want to be certain our preparation is up to the
challenge,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
   Peterson and Gramm said paperwork had already been prepared to
allow President Reagan to almost immediately issue a disaster
declaration and set relief efforts in motion, cutting through the
five to seven days usually needed.
   Peterson said federal agencies would dispatch Spanish-speaking
personnel and Spanish-language forms and pamphlets to help
communication with the sizeable Hispanic population along the coast.
   The American Red Cross said it also had begun sending emergency
supplies to four hurricane ``watch'' districts at several Texas
cities.
   The Red Cross said thousands of blankets, cots, comfort kits and
cleanup kits were on their way to Corpus Christi, Harlingen,
Houston and Beaumont, Texas. In addition, volunteers and staff
members were sent to San Antonio, Texas, and Birmingham, Ala.,
staging areas for deployment after the storm hits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-IntelligenceBill     09-16 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Intelligence Bill,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Expected To Sign Spy Satellite Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is expected to sign a bill to
modernize the nation's spy satellite network as part of
intelligence agency activities over the coming year,.
   Precise provisions of the measure, which was approved by
Congress on Thursday, have not been revealed.
   The Senate approved by voice vote a compromise measure which the
House had passed a day earlier.
   The Senate Intelligence Committee initiated the major
modernization program for electronic spying after concluding that
U.S. photo and eavesdropping satellites are growing outmoded. The
nation's spy capabilities in space have not been substantially
updated in a decade.
   In reviewing how well the United States could verify Soviet
compliance with the new Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces, or INF,
treaty, the panel found that monitoring technology would be
inadequate if the superpowers reach later agreement on deep cuts in
long-range nuclear weapons.
   A compromise was reached with the Reagan administration on the
amount of money needed for the program, but it was uncertain
whether Congress will appropriate the funds.
   That issue is tied up in a dispute over a separate Pentagon
appropriations bill.
   The House Appropriations Committee opposes the initiative,
saying it has been too hastily conceived and would not
substantially enhance U.S. treaty-monitoring ability.
   The exact amounts for the spy satellite program and the overall
intelligence budget are secret, but total spending on U.S.
intelligence programs reportedly is approximately $25 billion.
Nearly all of the money is hidden in the Pentagon's budget.
   Among other provisions in the intelligence bill:
   _Stronger language prohibiting the government from aiding
Nicaragua's Contra rebels unless specifically authorized by
Congress. The issue became controversial during the Iran-Contra
affair when the Reagan administration insisted prohibitions on
intelligence agencies aiding the rebels did not extend to the
president's National Security Council staff. The new legislation
bars any ``entity'' of the government from unauthoried aid to the
Contras, which would include the NSC.
   _A requirement that the Central Intelligence Agency report to
Congress about the activities of the agency's internal inspector
general, who investigates allegations of wrongdoing. The provision
also would require the CIA director to tell congressional overseers
any time he bars the inspector general from undertaking a specific
investigation.
   The only dollar amounts mentioned in the unclassified version of
the intelligence bill were a $23.7 million authorization for the
244-member intelligence community staff, which serves the CIA
director in his role of coordinator of all government intelligence
activities; $15.1 million for FBI counterintelligence activities in
keeping tabs on Soviet inspectors at U.S. weapons sites under the
INF treaty; and $144.5 million for the CIA's retirement and
disability fund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
