<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hurricane-Shelters     09-16 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane-Shelters,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Evacuees Asked To Bring Food, Leave Beer, Firearms Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were told to bring their own
food, drinks and blankets, but warned to leave their pets, booze
and guns at home. And they did.
   As Hurricane Gilbert, perhaps the most-feared storm of its kind,
approached the Texas coast, residents fled their homes, taking
bedrolls and food supplies to Red Cross shelters on higher ground.
   In this southernmost Texas city, where the eye of Gilbert was
predicted to pass sometime this evening, 750 people filled the
civic auditorium to its capacity within four hours, while hundreds
of others crowded into schools.
   For some, their flight to the shelters was reminiscent of
Hurricane Beulah, which struck Brownsville in 1980 and Hurricane
Allen, which landed north of Brownsville the same year.
   ``We brought food, water, some milk, but my husband forgot the
stereo and all our medicine, but I think we will be all right,''
said 77-year-old Maria Cardenas, a diabetic in a wheelchair.
   Families staked out perimeters on the floor of the civic center,
placing blankets, sheets and pillows on the floor next to bags of
food and ice chests filled with meats and soft drinks.
   Some children brought their plastic toys and some brought their
teddy bears while others turned on their small radios and tuned in
to news of the storm.
   ``Most of the people who come here or to other shelters in the
(Rio Grande) Valley are those who don't have transportation to go
north,'' said Ersel Lantz, head of the Red Cross effort at the
civic center.
   ``We have all kinds of people here, from those that need
Pampers, to those that need wheelchairs,'' he said.
   Frank Sanchez, 19, said he boarded up the home of mother and
grandparents in nearby Olmito and drove them to the civic center.
   ``We just decided this was the best place to be because of all
the predictions of damage it could cause,'' Sanchez said.
   Maria Elena Silva, 34, brought her children to the shelter
because she feared staying in her second-story apartment.
   ``We know that there might be an emergency and we don't have a
car and we knew we could come here where there are a lot of people
and if something happened, we knew we could get something if we
needed it,'' Ms. Silva said.
   Ricky Saldierna, 7, said would rather be at home.
   ``I think this hurricane is very bad because it could hurt
somebody, especially some kids like me,'' he said. ``I wish we were
in school now and I wish we were back in our own house.''
</TEXT>
