<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WarholCache     09-16 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Warhol Cache,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Warhol Jewel Cache Discovered in Hidden File Drawers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year-and-a-half after his death, Andy Warhol
has sprung another surprise: hundreds of diamonds, sapphires and
other jewelry worth $1.2 million and found hidden in a file cabinet.
   Curators uncovered the secret cache at the artist's Manhattan
townhouse, Sotheby's announced Thursday.
   The value of the jewelry was put at $1.2 million. But as last
spring's auction proved, anything associated with Warhol is likely
to sell for far more than its book value.
   Sotheby's said two curators were moving file cabinets at the
townhouse in June when they discovered the jewels stashed in
false-bottom drawers.
   The find included hundreds of diamonds, dozens of sapphires and
a 300-carat emerald, Sotheby's said. There also were 96 watches by
such makers as Patek Philippe, Rolex and Cartier.
   The jewelry will be auctioned Dec. 4, with proceeds going to the
Andy Warhol Foundation.
   At the earlier auction, jewelry that had been valued at
approximately $500,000 brought in $1.9 million as a frenzy of
Warholmania sent prices of his art and belongings soaring.
   The flat file cabinets with the jewels had been used by Warhol
to store unframed drawings and prints. They had been examined
before last spring's auction, but no one noticed the hollow
bottoms, Sotheby's spokesman Matthew Weigman said.
   The curators discovered the false bottoms only after they
removed the bottom drawers to lighten the cabinets before moving
them, he said.
   Warhol died in February 1987 at age 58.
</TEXT>
