<DOCNO> AP880916-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0416EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HurricaneBriefs     09-16 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane Briefs,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Hurricane Gilbert, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,500 animals at the Gladys
Porter Zoo were included in the preparations for Hurricane Gilbert.
   ``All the animals will have some kind of shelter. Tender birds
or those capable of flight in high wind are locked up first,''
General Curator Jerry Stones said Thursday.
   ``We try to wait until the last minute to do this because it
puts a lot of stress on the birds and we don't want to have them in
there too long or longer than we have to.''
   Workers also will place extra hay and feed in zoo buildings,
check generators and secure equipment from high winds.
   The zoo was already prepared for a hurricane, with a year-round
cache of supplies, including flashlights, batteries, boots, lumber,
food, water and generators, said Stones.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert has similarities to Allen,
which had winds up to 200 mph but diminished before it reached the
Texas coastline in 1980, meteorologists say.
   Allen caused heavy flooding and two deaths, but its assault on
Texas in August 1980 was far less serious than had been feared.
   Allen _ one of the most powerful hurricanes then on record _
slammed across the Caribbean with lethal force and built to
Category 5 strength.
   Gilbert also built to the same strength before weakening as it
passed over Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula.
   Allen, with a diameter of more than 600 miles, rapidly built in
intensity and crossed the gulf on Aug. 7 with winds near 200 mph.
   It sent hundreds of thousands of people on an exodus from the
coast but its rush toward land suddenly stalled as a high-pressure
ridge fended it off.
   By the time Allen crashed into the coast early Aug. 10, its
winds had diminished to around 100 mph and it was classified as a
Category 3 hurricane.
   At least 67 people were reported killed in Haiti after Allen
raced over the Caribbean island of Hispaniola.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA's Johnson Space Center employees were sent
home for the weekend to secure their homes, get supplies or leave
the area as Hurricane Gilbert approached the coast.
   Normally, the space center is closed to visitors only on
Christmas Day. But it shut down at noon Thursday and employees were
told they didn't have to return until normal work times Monday,
spokesman James Hartsfield said.
   At the space center, about 25 miles from the coast, there are
3,382 civil employees and 5,665 workers from companies contracting
with the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
   A core group will remain throughout the weekend at Mission
Control, the strongest building at the center and the place where
shuttle flights are controlled, Hartsfield said. Mission Control
has concrete walls and no windows.
   ``If the storm hurts that (Mission Control), we're really in
trouble,'' he said.
   If the space center withstands substantial damage, Hartsfield
said the expected launch of the first post-Challenger flight at
Cape Canaveral, Fla., wouldn't be affected.
   But NASA officials on Wednesday decided not to set an exact date
for the long-waited launch of Discovery because of the storm.
</TEXT>
