<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-16 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Up In Tokyo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged up against the Japanese yen, while
share prices rose moderately on the Tokyo Stock Exchange at the
close of trading here Friday.
   The dollar closed at 133.76 yen, up 0.31 yen from Wednesday's
finish of 133.45 yen. The currency was traded in a range between
133.58-133.80 yen, after opening at 133.65 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which closed at
27,866.38 points, gained 60.71 points or 0.22 percent from
Wednesday's close. The market's most widely used index rose in the
afternoon after a moderate fall in midmorning trading.
   A foreign exchange dealer with Mitsubishi Bank said the
dollar-yen rate was hardly moving after Thursday's national holiday
and ahead of the weekend.
   Investors in Tokyo traded currencies after observing the dollar
seesaw between 133 yen and 135 yen in New York following
Wednesday's release of the U.S. trade figure for July, which
indicated the U.S. trade deficit narrowed to a four-year low of
$9.5 billion for the month.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 11.51-point
winner Wednesday, ended the morning session up 0.67 points at
27,806.34. The index climbed to 27.871.80 shortly after trading
began but declined moderately in mid-morning activity.
   Despite a lower Dow Jones index overnight on Wall Street, the
Tokyo market was stable throughout the morning session, said a
Nomura Securities analyst.
   ``Steels attracted investors and made their trading very active.
That's the way the market should be,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
