<2ND_LINE>PM-Wedding Deaths,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Convicted For Deaths of Newlywed Couple, Best Man in Collision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of criminally negligent
homicide for smashing his car into a limousine during a drag race,
killing a newlywed couple and the best man, but the victims'
families found slim solace in the verdict.
   ``I just want him to pay for my pain,'' 22-year-old Debra
Zagorski said Thursday after the Nassau County jury convicted
21-year-old Vincent Laezza.
   Miss Zagorski was the maid of honor for her sister, 24-year-old
Carol Zagorski-Phillips, who died after 18 days in a coma. The
April 1987 crash left Miss Zagorski with a permanent limp.
   ``My body is scarred and I want him to be scarred for the rest
of his life,'' she said, tears running down her face outside the
courthouse.
   Laezza, who was free on $75,000 bail, was handcuffed and
remanded as his parents looked on with tears in their eyes. He
could be sentenced to a maximum 19 years in prison. Sentencing is
scheduled for Oct. 14.
   Police said Laezza was apparently drag racing at speeds up to
100 mph when his car crashed broadside into the limousine as it was
turning into a catering hall parking lot for the wedding reception.
   Killed instantly was the groom, Peter Phillips, 27, and his
brother and best man, 29-year-old John Phillips.
   Laezza was convicted of criminally negligent homicide but
acquitted of the more serious charge of manslaughter. He also was
convicted of one count of assault for seriously injuring Miss
Zagorski and was acquitted of assault in connection with the
limousine driver's injuries.
   ``This is really nothing but a terrible, terrible auto
accident,'' said Laezza's attorney, Eugene Schaffer. ``It was not a
crime.''
   Laezza, a carpenter from the Long Island community of Selden,
testified during the two-week trial that he did not remember the
accident: His only recollection was stopping for a red light and
waking up three days later in a hospital.
   The defense blamed the limousine driver, who suffered minor
injuries in the accident, charging he caused the accident by
cutting across Laezza's lane.
   The verdict was returned on what would have been the groom's
29th birthday.
   ``No matter what they do to (Laezza) it is not going to bring
those kids back,'' said the groom's father, John Phillips. ``I've
been waiting 17 months to see him led away in handcuffs.''
</TEXT>
