<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines     09-16 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Hails Formation of Pro-Government Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino today hailed
the formation of a new political party organized by her supporters
but said the move must not divide democratic forces into
``permanent hostile camps.''
   Formation of the new party is the latest step in a realignment
of forces which ousted leader Ferdinand Marcos in February 1986 and
swept Mrs. Aquino into power.
   Mrs. Aquino made her remarks in a speech to the opening session
of the first national convention of the new party, the ``Struggle
of the Democratic Filipino.''
   Rep. Ramon Mitra, speaker of the House of Representatives, was
elected president of the party, which organizers hope will bring
together pro-government forces under a single banner and serve as
the president's own party.
   But some pro-Aquino politicians have attacked the new party as a
bid by the president's relatives and others to consolidate their
own power in advance of the 1992 presidential election.
   Mrs. Aquino, who has vowed not to seek re-election, told the
5,093 delegates she hoped the new party was founded ``not only for
the 1992 elections but to help our people face and overcome their
problems.''
   Mrs. Aquino acknowledged the country must reinforce its newly
won democracy by establishing disciplined national parties. Parties
here have traditionally formed around personalities of their
leaders rather than ideology.
   ``Without the organization of political beliefs and programs
into disciplined parties, we would have only a riot of conflicting
opinions but no effective action,'' Mrs. Aquino said.
   She said political factionalism enabled her ousted predecessor,
Ferdinand Marcos, to impose eight years of martial law in 1972.
   Mrs. Aquino said the current political realignment was creating
disenchantment among the Filipino public, who fear a return to the
old-style politics of bickering and infighting that led to martial
rule.
   Delegates to the inaugural convention included 108 of the 202
members of the House of Representatives, six of the 23 senators, 42
provincial governors and more than 1,170 city and town mayors.
   Sen. Neptali Gonzalez, convention chairman, said he was not
disappointed by Mrs. Aquino's reluctance to give the party a
ringing endorsement or to join its ranks.
   ``You don't expect the president to say, `this is my party,''
Gonzalez said. ``I think her presence here is enough inspiration to
add membership to the party.''
   Mitra said Mrs. Aquino avoided a clearcut endorsement of the
party as the principal administration party because ``she might be
accused of playing politics.''
   He told reporters the party was organized to consolidate
political support for the government and establish a grass-roots,
mass movement behind Mrs. Aquino.
   ``But there are others who do not believe in this thinking,''
Mitra said. He was referring to the refusal of 18 Liberal Party
members in the House to join the new party.
   The Liberals, led by Senate President Jovito Salonga, are among
six parties united in the government coalition. But the Liberals
have disagreed with other pro-government parties and with some of
the president's politically influential relatives.
   Last month, Vice President Salvador Laurel and opposition Sen.
Juan Ponce Enrile announced formation of a new opposition party.
Mrs. Aquino ran under Laurel's United Nationalist Democratic
Organization in the 1986 presidential election, but the two fell
out over differences in philosophy and personal rivalry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
