<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Moving Toward Final Ban on Hairspray Propellant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration is close to
banning a chemical that once was used widely as a propellant in
hairsprays, according to the agency's director.
   ``We feel all the evidence indicates it is a hazardous
substance,'' said Dr. Frank E. Young at a hearing of the House
Small Business Committee's regulation subcommittee on Thursday.
   ``Just the introduction of this for just a few seconds in the
air in the bathroom every morning'' is a risk, Young told the
lawmakers.
   The cosmetics industry has conceded that the chemical is
hazardous for cosmeticians who might use it several times a day,
but has argued that it is safe for consumers.
   The FDA proposed banning use of methylene chloride in 1985
because the agency believes it is causes cancer.
   The agency should announce its final decision on the substance
by the end of the year. Other government agencies also would have
to consider the proposal before it becomes official.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Judges Plan Videotape Experiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Judicial Conference has announced an
experiment that could eliminate court stenographers.
   The Judicial Conference, a 28-judge board which sets policy for
the nation's federal courts, announced Thursday that it has
approved a two-year experiment for some federal courts to videotape
their proceedings.
   The experiment marks a radical departure for the federal
judiciary because, unlike many of their state counterparts, the
federal courts ban all electronic coverage of courtroom proceedings.
   The experiment, to be conducted in six trial courts and two
appeals courts which have not been identified, is designed to find
out whether videotapes should replace written documents as official
records of trial and appellate court proceedings.
   Public access to the videotapes is ``something that has not been
determined yet,'' said conference spokesman David Sellers.
   The experiment, which will be supplemented by stenographic
record, will be monitored by a committee led by U.S. District Judge
Richard M. Bilby of Tucson, Ariz.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Votes To Acquire Site Near Civil War Battlefield</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel has voted to give the federal
government authority to seize a development site adjacent to a
Civil War battlefield in suburban Virginia.
   The Energy and Natural Resources Committee on Thursday voted
11-8 to approve a measure that would authorize Congress to acquire
the 542-acre William Center Development tract near the Manassas
National Battlefield Park.
   The measure, introduced by Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark., is
identical to a bill that passed the House last month and allows for
purchase of the land and up to $30 million in construction of new
roads around the park.
   The panel rejected a compromise measure offered by Sen. John
Warner, R-Va., under which only part of the parcel would be
acquired.
   ``If we don't act to preserve that property, you can go down
there three weeks from now, and it will be gone, for all intents
and purposes,'' Bumpers said, maintaining the entire tract was
historically significant. ``It'll be a shopping mall.''
   Committee chairman Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., said he
hoped the bill would reach the Senate floor by next week. President
Reagan has threatened to veto any legislation similar to the
Bumpers bill.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Count Of Inactive Waste Sites At Nuclear Facilities Doubles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy has more than doubled
its count of inactive waste sites at nuclear weapons production
facilities across the country, according to the General Accounting
Office.
   The inactive waste site figure went from 1,447 to 3,276,
according GAO reports released by Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, chairman
of the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee.
   ``DOE's disarray in counting and assessing its inactive waste
sites is further evidence of this and earlier administrations'
willingness to place the public's health and safety at risk in
their rush to produce nuclear weapons,'' Glenn said.
   ``The fact that DOE doesn't know how many inactive waste sites
it has, or how hazardous they are, suggests that this cost estimate
is low,'' Glenn said, noting that DOE previously had estimated it
would cost $60 billion to clean up the waste sites.
   Glenn said that ``if we add all these costs up, the bill will be
at least $175 billion over the next half century.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>House Committee Approves Expanded Territorial Limit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Merchant Marine and Fisheries
Committee has approved legislation that would extend the U.S.
territorial limit to 12 nautical miles.
   Thursday's voice vote approving the measure would make the first
change in the three-mile protection zone along the U.S. coast since
1793 when President Thomas Jefferson instituted it.
   The panel also approved legislation that would require that
foreign fishing vessels stow their gear when passing through the
200-mile U.S. economic zone and carry transponders so satellites
could track their location.
   Those proposals were attached to a new U.S.-Soviet fishing
treaty and were sought by Washington state lawmakers after seven
Japanese trawlers were videotaped fishing in American waters off
Alaska in January.
   The expansion of the territorial limit will allow the United
States to exercise complete control over a broader area that would
``enhance our nation's ability to intercept and board vessels which
may be carrying contraband or drugs off our coast,'' and ``the
ability of Soviet ships to monitor and detect the movement of U.S.
submarines is lessened,'' said Rep. Mike Lowry, D-Wash., sponsor of
the bill.
</TEXT>
