<HEAD>Dollar Holds Ground Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held its ground against the Japanese yen
today, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately.
   The dollar closed 0.31 yen higher at 133.76 yen. It opened at
133.65 yen and fluctuated in a narrow range of 133.58-133.80 yen.
Spot volume was estimated at $4 billion amid directionless trading.
   ``Because the Tokyo market opened at almost the same level as it
closed before the release of U.S. trade figures and a Japanese
national holiday Thursday, it was difficult for investors to figure
out whether they should sell or buy the dollar,'' said a dealer at
the Bank of Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Monthly trade data released in Washington Wednesday showed the
U.S. trade deficit in July shrank to $9.53 billion from $13.22
billion in June, the biggest monthly improvement in almost six
years.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues closed higher at 27,866.38 points, up 60.71 points or 0.22
percent from Wednesday's close of 27,805.67. Volume on the first
section was a heavy 1.1 billion shares.
   ``Steels initiated the trading today, and trading was active all
day,'' said a stock dealer with Daiwa Securities. Electronic and
high-tech issues also advanced.
   The better-than-expected U.S. trade deficit as well as a stable
yen-dollar rate were boosting the stock market's performance, he
added.
