<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0553EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Caron     09-16 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Caron,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Moonlighting' Executive Producer Reported Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Glenn Gordon Caron, the producer whose
creative genius powered the comic eccentricities of the ABC-TV
series ``Moonlighting'' has left the show, the Hollywood newspaper
Daily Variety reported.
   Jay Daniels, who had been working as co-executive producer on
the Emmy-award winning show during the past two seasons will take
over as executive producer, the trade publication reported Thursday.
   The newspaper attributed Caron's departure to the network.
   Variety said reports were circulating that Caron had told ABC
network officials they would have to decide whether they wanted him
or actress Cybill Shepherd to return to the show, but ABC denied
this.
   Miss Shepherd, who co-stars with actor Bruce Willis, plays
Maddie Hayes, a financially devastated glamour queen who returns to
run a detective agency she had purchased as a tax-shelter.
   ``Moonlighting'' satirized the TV detective genre, often turning
the conventional end-of-the-show chase scene into a campy
free-for-all. The show also broke ground by deliberately mocking
its own television format.
   The show was energized by the hot-and-cold relationship between
Miss Shepherd's sensual princess and Willis' irreverent,
street-wise character, David Addison.
   Their banter sometimes evolved into witty dual monologues, with
each character talking without listening to the other.
   Caron, a reputed perfectionist, often worked on the scripts
himself and frequently pushed beyond deadlines for the show.
   He also directed ``Clean and Sober,'' the critically acclaimed
Michael Keaton film currently in release.
</TEXT>
