<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0625EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Heroes     09-16 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heroes,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>20 Named Carnegie Heroes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MATTIACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hotel bellhop honored for saving a
handicapped man from his burning apartment after a fireman had
given up says he doesn't want to be recognized as a hero, ``Thank
you was more than enough.''
   Nonetheless, Thomas J. Cathcart was among 20 Americans and
Canadians honored Thursday for their heroism by the Carnegie Hero
Fund Commission. Two of the heroes died in the performance of their
deeds.
   Cathcart, who works at a Catskill mountains hotel, said he was
walking home in Ellenville, N.Y., on July 22, 1987, when he heard a
woman screaming that her handicapped brother was trapped in a
burning apartment.
   ``I thought to myself, `Someone do something,''' Cathcart
recalled in a telephone interview Thursday. ``A volunteer fireman
said he couldn't make it. Instead of getting all riled up, I tried
to figure out what to do.''
   Cathcart picked up a dirty towel from the ground, put it over
his mouth, and went to the fiery second floor for Dennis DeJesus,
33.
   ``He was trying to get himself up with his crutches. I put him
up on my shoulders and ran down the steps. A lot of things were
going to my mind, but I wasn't thinking of my own health,''
Cathcart recalled.
   ``I didn't want to be recognized as a hero. Myself, I just felt
good inside for helping another man. Thank you was more than
enough. I know I'll always have a friend.''
   Heroes receive $2,500 and a medal from the Carnegie Hero Fund
Commission, which was established by industrialist Andrew Carnegie
in 1904 to recognize heroism by civilians in the United States and
Canada. It has honored 77 people this year and 7,258 people since
1904.
   Others recognized Thursday were:
   _Jeffrey G. Chipley, 17, of Estevan, Saskatchewan, who died
helping in the rescue of a 16-year-old boy in an abandoned mine on
Nov. 11, 1987.
   _James Michael Paradis, 28, of Chelsea, Mass., who died of stab
wounds after saving a woman from an assailant who had broken into
her apartment in Lynn, Mass., on Oct. 26, 1987.
   _Fred A. Thomas Jr., 18, of Wilkes-Barre, who saved a 3-year-old
boy from his burning apartment on Oct. 26, 1987.
   _Bruce Dobbs, 46, of Fairfax Station, Va., who saved a man from
drowning in the Potomac River on Dec. 22, 1987.
   _Todd Allen Brill, 24, of Elkhart, Ind., who saved two women
from drowning in their car, which had plunged into the St. Joseph
River on Oct. 21, 1987.
   _John E. Conner, 45, of Trenton, N.J., who saved a girl from a
burning car in Columbus, N.J., on Sept. 26, 1987.
   _Thomas William Luzak, 42, of Walton, Ky., who saved a woman
from drowning in her car, which had plunged into a lake at
Richwood, Ky., on Dec. 4, 1987.
   _Arthur H.C. Ham, 32, of Arnprior, Ontario, who saved a man from
exposure in a river near Galetta, Ontario, on April 11, 1987.
   _Guy A. Keally, 36, of Johnson City, Tenn., who saved a woman
from a burning car on Oct. 16, 1987.
   _Larry B. Pulai, 26, of Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, who saved a
20-month-old girl from being struck by a train on May 20, 1987.
   _Donna Marie Bell, 21, of Ingleside, Ill., who saved an
11-month-old girl from her burning home in Mundelein, Ill., on
March 7.
   _Hsien-li Chang, 70, of San Francisco, who saved a 71-year-old
man from his burning apartment on Jan. 11.
   _Michael Allen, 26, of Conroe, Texas, who saved a woman from
being struck by a train on July 18, 1987.
   _Connie Sue Gries, 36, of Evansville, Ind., who saved a man from
