<1ST_LINE>u i PM-OlympicProtests     09-16 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Olympic Protests,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radicals Mount Anti-Olympic Protests On Eve Of Games</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students shouting
``Yankee go home!'' mounted protests against the Olympics today on
the eve of Games and burned an effigy of President Reagan.
   Students staged protests at three schools in Seoul to demand the
Olympics be shared with communist North Korea and to denounce the
government of President Roh Tae-woo. The Olympics start Saturday.
   ``Oppose dictator's Olympics!'' and ``Crush military
aggression!'' students yelled.
   About 300 protesters armed with firebombs and clubs marched out
of Kookmin University to fight riot police after burning effigies
of Reagan and Roh, as well as a U.S. flag. But riot police watched
from a distance and did not intervene as the protesters repeatedly
blocked traffic.
   Students, one of whom hurled a single firebomb at a passing
police truck and missed, tired of taunting police and dispersed.
   About 500 students took part in a similar protest at Seoul
National University in the south of the capital. They marched to
the gate and burned an effigy of Roh.
   Riot police in green combat fatigues and black, visored helmets
watched but did not intervene. The students made no move to attack
the police.
   The protesters then marched to a gym on the campus where Olympic
table tennis events are to be held and yelled anti-Olympic slogans
outside the building before dispersing.
   A small anti-Olympic protest was also held at Yonsei University
with less than 100 students taking part.
   Anti-Olympic protests have been small by Korean standards, and
the radicals have failed to attract support. Violent clashes with
riot police have dropped sharply in recent days as the number of
students taking part has dwindled.
   A few onlookers even shouted abuse at protesters at Kookmin,
accusing them of trying to wreck the Olympics. ``Go home. You are
shaming our nation,'' screamed an angry old man.
   The radicals are demanding the Olympics be shared with North
Korea to promote reunification of the Korean Peninsula, divided
since 1945.
   Radicals also contend the Roh government is a front for military
rule and is using the Olympics to cement its rule with aid from the
United States.
   The great majority of Koreans, including most students, want the
Olympics to be a major success. ``Students know the people are
against these demonstrations,'' a student leader said today.
   North Korea is boycotting the Olympics because its demand to be
a co-host of the Games was rejected. The International Olympic
Committee said the Games are awarded to a single city and cannot be
shared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
