<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0642EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WPPSSTrial     09-16 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Trial,0596</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Debacle Encompassed All, Says Attorney For Engineers
^By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Accusations against 19 defendants in the
fraud trial over the Washington Public Power Supply System's
default on $2.25 billion in bonds amounts to ``fraud by
hindsight,'' a defense lawyer says.
   ``There is no evidence to support charges of conspiracy,'' Peter
Nickles, representing the engineering firm of Ebasco, said in
opening statements Thursday.
   Jurors were told by other defense attorneys that utility
officials who sat on the system's board of directors were part-time
public servants who relied on experts and had nothing to gain by
misleading investors who bought bonds in the two nuclear plants.
   ``These people always acted in good faith,'' said Al Malanca,
who represents 12 of the 16 public utilities that are among
defendants. ``They had no motive to do wrong.''
   Malanca opened the defendants' case by disputing plaintiff
attorneys' arguments that utility members of the WPPSS board
controlled the supply system and plotted to defraud bond buyers.
   Defendants, including another engineering firm and a financial
adviser to WPPSS, are accused of making misrepresentations and
withholding crucial information from investors who bought bonds to
finance construction of two nuclear power plants.
   Plaintiffs include more than 24,000 bond buyers in the case,
which resulted from the 1983 default by WPPSS on the $2.25 billion
in bonds. It was the biggest default in the history of the
municipal bond market.
   The trial began last week. The judge excused jurors until
Monday, when opening arguments by defense attorneys were to resume.
   Nickles said what happened to the WPPSS projects was happening
to the entire nuclear industry by the late 1970s.
   He said plant-construction prices dramatically escalated because
of inflation and required changes to make nuclear plants safer. And
the 1979 Three Mile Island accident, he said, ``wrecked the nuclear
industry.''
   Malanca told jurors that the plaintiffs would have them believe
the 16 utility defendants had the power to control federal and
state agencies, and were able to induce major engineering and
financial firms to knowingly make false claims on official bond
statements.
   But the utilities were relatively small, and were far down on
the pecking order among the energy powers in the Northwest, he
said. The federal Bonneville Power Administration, he said,
dominated the region.
   While WPPSS in the 1970s, with five nuclear plants under
construction, was also a major player in the energy scene, said
Malanca, the utility officials that directed it were part-time
participants.
   He said they considered their appointments to the board a matter
of civic duty, went to meetings only periodically, hired the best
experts they could find, and generally followed directions of those
experts and WPPSS.
   The supply system staff had more power in directing WPPSS and
board members were not even to speak to the media as
representatives of WPPSS, he said.
   ``If they did anything wrong, they were acting as board members
of the supply system, not of the utilities,'' he said.
   He stressed that public utility officials are not paid,
receiving only per diem allowances for their work.
   Dennis Bromley, another defense lawyer, said utilities from the
23-member WPPSS board sent one representative each to the supply
system.
   But, he said, the utilities had no control at all over how that
representative voted and didn't stand a chance of controlling the
supply system.
   The supply system was created in 1957 to build and operate major
power-generating facilities in the Northwest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
