<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain, Wind, Tides Herald Gilbert's Approach in Texas; Rain in
Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy rain, gusty winds and high tides heralded the approach of
Hurricane Gilbert along Texas' southern Gulf Coast today while
unrelated showers and thunderstorms soaked parts of the Plains.
   Showers and scattered thunderstorms also extended to the lower
Mississippi Valley, the central Gulf Coast and Florida.
   Hurricane warnings were in effect along the southern Texas coast
from Port O'Conner to Brownsville and south along the Mexican coast
to Tampico. A hurricane watch was in effect eastward from Port
O'Conner to Port Arthur, Texas, near Louisiana.
   The first major rains from Gilbert hit Brownsville late
Thursday, accompanied by wind gusts up to 40 mph, and Corpus
Christi reported tides 3 to 4 feet above normal.
   Out in the gulf today, the hurricane packed maximum sustained
winds of 120 mph and 10- to 15-inch rainfall. Tides were expected
to run 7 to 11 feet above normal when Gilbert makes landfall.
   A band of thunderstorms lashed the area from north Texas to
northwest Missouri with heavy rains, strong winds and hail
Thursday. Power lines were downed, and golf ball-size hail pelted
Ponca City, Okla. By early today, the storms had dropped 1 to 2
inches of rain in several locations.
   Showers also dampened Iowa, Minnesota and the eastern parts of
South Dakota and Nebraska. Cloudy skies covered the Pacific
Northwest, but it was clear in most other parts of the country.
   Early morning temperatures dipped into the 30s and 40s in the
northern Atlantic Coast, with frost warnings in effect for Vermont
and eastern New York state.
   Today's forecast called for numerous showers and thunderstorms
from Hurricane Gilbert over southern Louisiana and Texas, with
strong gusty winds in southern Texas and the northern Rockies;
showers and a few thunderstorms from South Carolina to the Gulf
Coast states, from the Tennessee, lower Ohio and Mississippi
valleys to the eastern Plains, and over northern Michigan, northern
Wisconsin and eastern Minnesota; and widely scattered showers from
the Pacific Northwest to northwest Montana.
   Highs were forecast in the 70s and 80s over most of the nation;
in the upper 50s and 60s in New England, the northern Appalachians,
from northern Michigan to eastern Minnesota, and from northwest
Montana to the Pacific Northwest and down part of the California
coast; in the lower 90s in Florida, Mississippi and parts of the
southern Plains; and up to 105 degrees in the desert Southwest.
   At 3 a.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 34 degrees at Watertown,
N.Y., to 84 degrees at Homestead, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 72 foggy; Boston 49 fair; Buffalo 44 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 74 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 60 fair; Cleveland 51
fair; Detroit 54 fair; Miami 83 partly cloudy; New York 54 fair;
Philadelphia 52 fair; Pittsburgh 51 fair; Portland, Me. 43 fair;
Washington 57 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 53 foggy; Chicago 61 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
77 fair; Denver 51 fair; Des Moines 66 rain; Indianapolis 62 fair;
Kansas City 65 thunderstorms; Minneapolis-St. Paul 58 rain;
Nashville 72 partly cloudy; New Orleans 79 foggy; St. Louis 72
partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 58 fair; Anchorage 53 cloudy; Las Vegas 72
fair; Los Angeles 62 hazy; Phoenix 83 fair; Salt Lake City 62 fair;
San Diego 65 cloudy; San Francisco 53 fair; Seattle 55 foggy.
   _Canada: Montreal 45 fair; Toronto 45 fair.
</TEXT>
