<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady in Thin Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was trading steadily in thin
late-morning trading in Europe today, with players saying they
expected the dollar to stay in a narrow range throughout the
session.
   Gold prices moved lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers in Italy said that volume was limited
and that there were few commercial orders as activity wound down
for the weekend.
   They said that the market remained bullish about the dollar due
to the narrower-than-expected U.S. July trade deficit reported
Wednesday. But they cautioned that the general opinion was that the
world's major central banks appeared content with the dollar's
present levels, and that any attempt to push it much higher would
invite intervention.
   ``I see the dollar gaining ground, but nobody wants to be the
first the try stepping over 1.88 (West German) marks,'' said a
trader in Milan with a major Italian commercial bank. He predicted
that the dollar would trade within a range of between 1.87 marks
and 1.88 marks today.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.31 yen to a closing 133.76 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 134.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8741 West German marks, down from 1.8775
   _1.5810 Swiss francs, down from 1.5820
   _6.3735 French francs, down from 6.3790
   _2.1133 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1160
   _1,397.25 Italian lire, down from 1,398.87
   _1.2235 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2225
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6755, compared with
$1.6675 Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $417 a troy ounce, down
from $417.75 bid late Thursday. At mid-morning Friday, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $417.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $417.20, down from $417.50 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.61 to close at a bid
$419.84. Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.46
a troy ounce, up from Thursday's $6.44.
