<HEAD>Protesters Smash Store Windows In Protest Against Austerity
Measures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Peru-Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators against government austerity
measures smashed store windows with rocks, looted shops and clashed
with riot police. Officials said leftist guerrillas infiltrated the
downtown protest.
   Thousands of pedestrians trying to escape the riots Thursday ran
through streets filled with tear gas fired by police. Most were
unable to find shelter because stores and restaurants closed their
doors when the violence started.
   The government gave no report on the number of injured, but two
protesters were seen bleeding from the head. Police made 30 arrests.
   Small groups of demonstrators blocked traffic Thursday afternoon
and shouted insults against harsh anti-inflation austerity measures
announced last week by the center-left government of President Alan
Garcia.
   The measures included price increases of as much as 300 percent
for food staples and gasoline to eliminate costly government
subsidies that were contributing to inflation expected to top 900
percent this year.
   In addition to the protests against the steep price increases,
about 300 striking civilian workers from a navy shipyard clashed
with police troopers who fired tear gas grenades to keep the
strikers from reaching the government palace.
   Police said members of the Maoist-inspired Shining Path
guerrilla movement infiltrated the demonstrators and urged them on
to violence. Men in hoods were seen among the protesters.
   Police said the protesters smashed store windows and looted a
book shop and a clothing store only two blocks from the government
palace.
   Riot police regained control in the downtown area after several
hours.
   In other violence Thursday, police said an assassination team of
Maoist rebels fired on a navy captain as he was driving his young
daughter to school in an upper-class neighborhood, wounding him
twice in the stomach and twice in the left leg.
   Police said the daughter, whose age was not available, was not
hurt in the attack.
   Four suspected members of the Shining Path armed with three
revolvers and sticks of dynamite were arrested as they tried to
escape on foot, police said.
