<2ND_LINE>PM-NY Primary,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Biaggi Loses Last Election; 2 Others Tainted by Corruption Win</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mario Biaggi, whose congressional career ended
last month after he was convicted of racketeering, saw his
electoral career end with a defeat in the Democratic primary he
said he did not want to win.
   New York voters Thursday gave two other prominent politicians
tainted by political scandal the chance to remain in office as they
seek to clear their names.
   State Senate Minority Leader Manfred Ohrenstein and Rep. Robert
Garcia both survived Democratic primary challenges in districts
where winning the primary is tantamount to election.
   Biaggi, who had quit his seat after his conviction in the
Wedtech scandal, was still given a good chance because of his
popularity. But the voters turned instead to state Assemblyman
Eliot Engel.
   With 97 percent of the vote counted, Engel had 12,831 votes, or
50 percent, to 6,538, or 25 percent, for former state Assemblyman
Vincent Marchiselli and 6,405, or 25 percent, for Biaggi.
   Though Biaggi will be on the November ballot as the Republican
candidate, Engel is expected to be the easy winner.
   Garcia's name has come up in testimony in the Wedtech case, but
he has not been charged with any wrongdoing. He said Thursday night
that the questions about his connections to Wedtech made his
primary victory sweeter.
   ``After 22 years in public with never as much as a bad word
against me, this hit me like a ton of bricks,'' said Garcia. ``I
feel the people of my district said, `OK, Bob, we're in this
together, let's go.'''
   With all the returns in, Garcia had 16,517 votes, or 60 percent,
to 7,515, or 27 percent, for Pedro Espada, a community health
center director, and 3,471, or 13 percent, for Ismael Betancourt,
who had lost two earlier primaries to Garcia.
   Ohrenstein, a 28-year veteran of the state Legislature, narrowly
beat back a challenge from Joseph Rose, 29, the son of a wealthy
developer.
   Rose spent more than $500,000, most of it family money, trying
to make sure every potential voter in the district knew that
Ohrenstein has been indicted for putting campaign workers on the
Senate payroll during the 1986 elections. Ohrenstein has denied any
wrongdoing.
   In suburban Westchester County, former state official Nita Lowey
defeated Hamilton Fish III and businessman Dennis Mehiel in a
Democratic primary for the right to oppose Republican Rep. Joseph
DioGuardi in November.
   The Fish family has been active in state GOP circles since the
party was founded and Fish's father, Hamilton Fish Jr., represents
a neighboring district in Congress that had previously been
represented by another Hamilton Fish, the young Fish's grandfather.
</TEXT>
