<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-MentalHealth     09-16 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Mental Health,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rural Areas Need More Services To Address Mental Health Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 drought has increased the need for
more mental health services in rural areas, says a former Cabinet
official.
   ``The drought this summer has made a bad situation worse for
many,'' said Bob Bergland, the ex-secretary of agriculture who
headed a special commission on rural mental health problems.
   Citing research conducted before the drought, the National
Mental Health Association's commission on rural mental health
issued a study Thursday recommending the creation of a federal
office of rural mental health and increased funds for alcohol, drug
abuse and mental health programs.
   The study, ``Rural Mental Health: The Time for Action Is Now,''
also recommends a broader crisis counseling network for farmers.
   ``We're fighting a myth that rural America is a healthier place
to live. If that was ever true, it's not true today,'' said Dr.
Peter G. Beeson, director of planning for the Nebraska Department
of Public Institutions.
   Bergland said much of the stress on rural residents is triggered
by economic problems.
   Besides the economy, other parts of the rural environment have
changed, the study said. The traditional image of a closely-knit
rural community revolving around church and family activities no
longer fits, the report said.
   Consequently, psychological distress becomes more common, and
rural residents' problems often aren't treated promptly because
rural areas frequently lack mental health services, Bergland said.
   ``The biggest problem isn't that we're sicker in rural places.
The problem is we don't have resources,'' said Bergland during a
news conference to unveil the study.
</TEXT>
