<DOCNO> AP880916-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-O-Rings-Sabotage     09-16 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-O-Rings-Sabotage,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Says Suspect Identified, Arrest Likely In O-Ring Sabotage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities expect to file charges soon in
the apparent sabotage of O-rings made for space shuttle booster
rockets, an FBI agent says.
   HydraPak, which manufactures the O-rings in West Jordan, a Salt
Lake suburb, discovered in June that a small number of the
rubber-like seals had been deliberately cut.
   Officials notified booster maker Morton Thiokol, the FBI and
NASA. The federal agencies began a joint investigation.
   ``We do have suspects and the case will be prosecutable,'' FBI
Special Agent Cal Clegg said Thursday. ``Right from the inception,
we have been discussing the case with the U.S. Attorney's office,
and we feel that arrests or indictments will be imminent.''
   Clegg said charges could be filed within a month.
   Clegg said he did not know whether more than one person was
suspected, but the number ``could expand. ... It depends on the
evidence that is gathered.''
   James Dockstader, HydraPak vice president of production, said
earlier that none of the damaged seals had been shipped to Morton
Thiokol, which manufactures the rockets at its northern Utah plant.
   He said Thursday he could not comment on the FBI probe. However,
he said HydraPak's internal investigation had determined that
allegations of lax security, shipment of substandard O-rings and a
company cover-up were without foundation.
   Dockstader said the internal investigation, completed Monday,
found no ``irregularities in manufacturing, shipment or inspection
processes'' or in the security procedures at the plant about 20
miles south of Salt Lake City.
   He said steps had been taken to increase security, but would not
give details.
   The O-rings are used as seals between segments of the booster
rocket to prevent leakage of superhot gases from burning propellant.
   After the 1986 Challenger explosion, a presidential commission
found that an O-ring allowed a plume of fiery gas to escape and
ignite the shuttle's main liquid fuel tank, triggering the blast
that killed the shuttle's seven astronauts.
   Improvements to the booster joint have been the focus of Morton
Thiokol's effort to redesign the rocket. Last month the company
conducted a final test-firing of the shuttle Discovery, the first
flight planned since the Challenger disaster.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration has scheduled
the launch for late this month or early October.
</TEXT>
