<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Wedtech-Ramirez     09-16 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wedtech-Ramirez,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Navy Official to Plead in Wedtech Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former civilian Navy official agreed to plead
guilty to taking a $60,000 bribe from Wedtech and related charges
involving the scandal-plagued former defense contractor and another
company.
   Richard D. Ramirez, once head of the Navy's small business
program, will plead guilty to four criminal counts charging him
with conspiracy to receive bribes and filing false income tax
returns, U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday.
   According to the charges, Ramirez, 40, of Clifton, Va.,
conspired to take a $60,000 bribe from Wedtech _ a now-defunct
contractor _ for his help in obtaining $135 million in no-bid Navy
contracts to build floating docks. The docks were designed to move
supplies from ship to shore for the U.S. Rapid Deployment Force.
   At the time, Ramirez was director of the Navy's Office of Small
and Disadvantaged Business Utilization, and was responsible for
assisting minority-owned and minority-operated businesses obtain
contracts without competitive bidding under a special Small
Business Administration Program, said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Baruch Weiss.
   Former Wedtech officials have admitted committing fraud to keep
the company in the program even though it was neither
minority-owned nor controlled.
   One of those officials, former executive vice president Mario
Moreno, testified at the racketeering trial of ex-Rep. Mario Biaggi
earlier this year that Ramirez was ``a mole'' who supplied Wedtech
with inside information from the office of then-Navy Secretary John
F. Lehman.
   Biaggi, a Bronx Democrat, and five others were convicted of
various corruption charges in August. They are awaiting sentencing.
   Ramirez also was charged with plotting to take $120,000 in
bribes from United Chem Con Corp. of Lancaster, Pa., for help in
obtaining no-bid contracts worth $54 million to supply the Navy
with other equipment.
   In addition, Ramirez was charged with failing to include the
money he got from Wedtech and United Chem Con on his 1982 and 1983
tax returns.
   He faces up to five years in prison and a $10,000 fine on each
of the conspiracy counts and three years imprisonment and $250,000
in fines on each tax count, said Weiss.
</TEXT>
