<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugBust     09-16 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Bust,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nearly 2,500 Pounds Of Cocaine Seized In Philly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Customs agents realized something was fishy
when anchovy importer Andes Trading Co. listed a bogus address in
New York City.
   Inside a 1,000-carton shipment of anchovies, investigators found
137 cartons holding 2,745 pounds of cocaine, federal officials said
at a news conference Thursday.
   Roberto Alcaino, 51, of Chile, listed as the consignee on the
manifest, was arrested in New York about Thursday shortly after he
accepted the load, minus all but one carton of cocaine.
   Customs agents intercepted the shipment from Argentina Sept. 6
aboard a German-flagged cargo ship at the Holt Marine Terminal in
Camden, N.J., and seized a container supposedly holding 1,000
cartons of anchovies.
   In each of 137 boxes, agents found two large anchovy tins
containing seven or eight 2{-pound bricks of cocaine, officials
said.
   U.S. Customs agent David Warren said the drug traffickers added
lead weights and sand to the tins holding cocaine to approximate
the weight of anchovies, but were off by about 5 pounds.
   Sam Billbrough, head of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration's Philadelphia office, called Alcaino a high-level
trafficker.
   Alcaino was charged with possession with intent to distribute
cocaine and faces charges in Philadelphia of importing cocaine.
   If convicted, he would face a minimum 10 years in prison on each
charge, said acting U.S. Attorney Thomas H. Lee.
