<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-PhilippinesBases 1stLd-Writethru a0445 09-16 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Philippines Bases, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0445,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Site Possible Removal Of Bases From Philippines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, Other officials, to UPDATE
with Gorbachev statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top U.S. officials are for the first time
talking seriously about removing military bases from the
Philippines, and the chief Philippines negotiator says the country
is preparing for such a possibility but still negotiating.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Thursday the United
States wants to keep giant Clark Air Base and Subic Navy Base and
other installations in the Philippines but ``there are alternatives
which we are having now to examine.''
   Shultz said talks in Manila on bases compensation and other
issues ``basically aren't going well.''
   On Wednesday, Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci told visiting
Philippine Foreign Minister Raul Manglapus, in what one official
described as blunt terms, that the United States is prepared to
pull out of the bases if the Philippines insists on too much
compensation.
   Other officials have suggested they might be relocated to Guam
or elsewhere in the Pacific, with estimates of the cost of such a
move ranging over $10 billion. Defense officials have said in the
past that the bases are vital to security of a vast area stretching
from Southeast Asia into the Persian Gulf.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said in a speech today that
the Kremlin is ready to give up its base at Cam Ranh Bay, Vietnam,
if U.S. forces leave the Philippines.
   U.S. officials have said this would not be a balanced exchange.
Cam Ranh Bay is the Soviets' major naval deployment base abroad,
while Clark and Subic are the United States's largest foreign bases.
   Manglapus, in an interview Thursday, said the two sides in the
negotiations now in recess are not far apart on how much the Reagan
administration should seek from Congress in direct payment for use
of the bases, but several other issues in the talks remain
unresolved.
   ``Both sides agree that the hard component (cash) of our mutual
proposals were not too far apart and that in addition we would be
looking for creative ways of raising the level of the compensation
to that which was proposed by the Philippines,'' Manglapus said.
   He said additional help might come in the form of procurement of
Philippine products and the writing off of some of the nation's $26
billion foreign debt.
   Manglapus did not say how much aid has been offered by the U.S.
panel, but congressional sources have said it is close to $500
million, including a doubling of direct bases-related aid to $360
million for fiscal 1989. Manglapus declined to say how much the
Philippines originally wanted, but Manila news reports have put the
demand as high as $1.2 billion a year.
   Manglapus said he was not surprised by Carlucci's remarks about
pulling out and asserted that the Philippines is preparing for a
loss of the bases.
   He said studies show that conversion of the bases to civilian
use could provide even more benefits, including replacement of the
thousands of jobs that would be lost if the United States pulls out.
   He said that while the bases provide significant economic
benefit, even American analysts agree that their security value to
the Philippines is minimal.
   ``Your own analysts and your own leaders stress the priority
importance of the global strategy that is fulfilled by these
bases,'' he said.
   Manglapus said unresolved issues in the bases talks include the
storage of nuclear weapons on the bases, ownership of improvements
to the bases, procurement policies and the write-off of debts for
military equipment.
   ``We have not gotten anything out of the American panel,'' he
said.
   Manglapus said he is discussing the bases issue with a variety
of U.S. officials but has not moved the negotiations from Manila to
Washington.
   Surveys of Filipinos show only a small percentage of outright
opposition to the bases, he said, but a large number of people say
they would want the bases out if the Americans do not improve the
bases agreement, including additional compensation.
   Manglapus, who lived in U.S. self-exile during the last decade
of ex-President Ferdinand E. Marcos' rule, said he has found
Democrats more responsive on Philippine issues than Republicans,
but he said the views of the two parties on the bases appear to be
the same.
   Manglapus plans to meet Shultz again at the United Nations at
the end of the month.
   The Philippine official also will attend the New York debut of a
musical comedy he wrote during his exile. The play, which deals
with the U.S. takeover of the Philippines between 1898 and 1902, is
called, ``Manifest Destiny: An Evening of Yankee Panky.''
</TEXT>
