<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0816EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AIDS     09-16 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Case Count To Reach 365,000 By '92, CDC Predicts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of AIDS cases in the United States
will jump nearly five-fold by 1992, and about 263,000 people will
have died from the disease by then, the national Centers for
Disease Control predicts.
   As of this week, 72,766 AIDS cases have been reported to the
CDC; 41,064 people, or 56 percent, are dead. By the end of 1992,
the number of cases will hit 365,000, and 72 percent of those
patients will be dead, the CDC says.
   The predictions came Thursday in a report summarizing the CDC's
latest quarterly report on AIDS to the White House's Domestic
Policy Council.
   Actual AIDS reporting has run slightly higher than predicted;
the agency in 1986 predicted 15,800 cases in 1986 and 23,000 in
1987, and the actual totals were 17,100 and 25,200, respectively.
   ``We think they're very close,'' said Dr. Tim Dondero, an AIDS
specialist at the Atlanta-based health agency. ``I think the
message is that, at least for the first couple of years, this ...
method gives some pretty reliable estimates.''
   The CDC in 1986 issued its AIDS predictions for 1991, which
forecast 270,000 cases by the end of that year.
   In the report released Thursday, the agency predicts 80,000
cases of AIDS in 1992 alone, with 66,000 deaths that year. A total
of 172,000 living AIDS patients will require medical care in 1992,
at a cost of $5 billion to $13 billion, the CDC predicts.
   The CDC also said its current estimate of 1 million to 1.5
million Americans currently infected with the virus which causes
AIDS is ``a reasonable working estimate,'' based on mathematical
analysis by experts convened by the CDC in April.
   Thursday's report noted that the national infection estimate has
remained the same since it was devised in 1986. The rate is about
0.4 percent to 0.6 percent.
   ``This does not mean that no new infections have occurred,'' the
CDC said. ``The 1986 estimate was based on preliminary data, and
was probably too high (at the time).''
</TEXT>
