<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarkHofmann     09-16 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mark Hofmann,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confessed Bomber-Forger Critical After Drug Overdose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man who admitted killing two people
with homemade bombs to cover up his forgeries of Mormon documents
was in critical but stable condition today from a drug overdose in
prison, a hospital official said.
   Mark Hofmann, 33, was in a coma when taken by helicopter from
the Utah State Prison to the University of Utah Health Sciences
Center, officials said. He began coming out of the coma shortly
before midnight Thursday.
   Hospital spokesman John Dwan said the overdose was from an
undetermined tricyclic anti-depressant drug, which showed up in lab
tests at toxic levels.
   Hofmann also suffered ``minor to moderate burns'' on his right
forearm and chest, he said. He said the cause of the burns was not
immediately known, but they were not considered serious.
   Hofmann had been prescribed a sleeping medication, but Juan
Benavidez, a state Department of Corrections spokesman, said he did
not know what it was, or the dosage.
   Hofmann is serving a five years to life prison term following
his January 1987 plea agreement, in which he admitted killing two
people in 1985.
   At a hearing before the Board of Pardons in January, Hofmann
said he felt remorse for the families of his victims, but the board
ruled 2-1 that he should spend the rest of his life in prison.
   From 1981 to 1985, Hofmann had virtually set the agenda for
scholars of Mormon history with a string of discoveries of
purported documents relating to early church history. Most later
proved to be his own forgeries, some of which were expertly done
while others were crude.
</TEXT>
