<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Black     09-16 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Black,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shirley Temple Black Angry Over `Shirley T' Soft Drink</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shirley Temple Black is angry about plans to
advertise a new soft drink that borrows her name, but the maker of
Shirley T says she has nothing to complain about.
   Soda Pop Kids, a small regional company that has been selling a
bottled version of the traditional Shirley Temple cocktail for
about a year, is boasting about a new TV ad campaign.
   ``It's an infringement of my rights,'' Ms. Black fumed Thursday.
``They're using my name without my permission.''
   But Brad Weidman, the 26-year-old founder of Soda Pop Kids, says
years of use in bars has made Shirley Temple a generic name for a
non-alcoholic drink concocted of lemon-lime soda and cherry
flavoring.
   He is pressing ahead with plans to expand distribution of
Shirley T, and of his two other flavors, Berryblue and Peachykeen,
in additional Los Angeles area markets. Included in the plans is an
Oct. 1 kickoff of a TV ad campaign.
   ``It's in the good hands of my attorney,'' the former child
actress said when asked what she would do about the ads. Her
lawyer, Richard Ross of Los Angeles, didn't respond to a telephone
request for comment.
   Weidman doesn't mind borrowing others' success: The ads feature
animated dancing fruit reminiscent of the popular California Raisin
commercials.
   ``It's like that,'' Weidman said of his ad, ``but a hundred
times better.''
