<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SlowDown     09-16 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Slow Down,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Arrested After Warning Motorists About Police</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PG1 of Sept. 15</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE DRESSLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who says he's paid $2,000 in traffic
fines held up a sign warning motorists to slow down because police
were ahead _ and was promptly arrested for obstructing traffic.
   ``I stood there for about 20 minutes,'' John Thiry said
Thursday. ``That would have been about a total of $3,000 (in fines)
they would have gotten people for.''
   Thiry, 22, of Pittsburgh, was arrested Wednesday on obstructing
traffic charges after he stood on Schenley Park Plaza with a sign
that read ``Slow down. Police ahead with VASCAR.''
   VASCAR is a device akin to a stop watch that calculates a car's
speed by measuring the time it takes for a car to travel between
two lines painted across the street.
   ``I stopped a lot of people from having a miserable day,'' he
said. ``People were beeping at me. They were waving.''
   Thiry said Pittsburgh police ``make you go 25 (mph) where they
know 25 is an unreasonably slow speed. Try and go the speed limit
and just see what happens. See how many people pass you.''
   Police Chief Ralph Pampena said there are signs posted
throughout the city warning drivers that police use VASCAR devices
to enforce speed limits.
   ``The signs are very clear,'' he said. ``If the signs are posted
as 25 mph, then that's the speed we expect people to go.''
   Thiry said he was upset because he had been issued many tickets,
recently had lost his license for the third time and had to leave a
job as a salesman.
   The tickets included at least five in the past two years from
police using VASCAR devices, plus others for speeding on the
interstate, he said. He estimated he has paid about $2,000 in fines
but said he has never been involved in a traffic accident.
   Police Sgt. Leo McCafferty and officer William O'Rourke said
they noticed motorists suddenly were driving slower and arrested
Thiry after a motorist informed them of the sign.
   Thiry said he will appeal the charge of obstructing traffic,
which carries a fine of $48.50.
   ``I wasn't blocking traffic,'' Thiry said. ``I don't think they
had the right to arrest me because I wanted to warn people. What if
I was just yelling? That's freedom of speech.''
   Edward Patterson, commander of the traffic division, said, ``Any
time you're out in the street, you're obstructing traffic.''
</TEXT>
