<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Huerta-Police     09-16 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Huerta-Police,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Orders Two Investigations Into Alleged Police Beating Of UFW
Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Art Agnos has ordered two
investigations into the alleged police beating of labor leader
Dolores Huerta, who lost her spleen and had three ribs broken
during a political demonstration.
   ``I am deeply concerned and disturbed about this incident,''
Agnos said Thursday after visiting the United Farm Workers
co-founder at her hospital bed.
   Ms. Huerta, 58, was listed in stable condition today at San
Francisco General Hospital. The beating occurred Wednesday during
protests at a campaign appearance by Republican presidential
candidate George Bush.
   Agnos ordered Police Chief Frank Jordan and the director of the
Office of Citizen Complaints to conduct separate investigations
into the incident.
   Ms. Huerta was among demonstrators who gathered on sidewalks in
front of a hotel on Union Square.
   After 20 minutes of warning of protesters to move behind
barricades, police tactical squads began to sweep the crowd, Jordan
said. ``Somewhere in the half-block segment, she apparently was
injured,'' he said.
   Agnos reviewed police tapes for 90 minutes. He said he
identified Ms. Huerta in the crowd but neither he nor Jordan could
see on film whether she was being struck.
   ``We could see she was being very cooperative,'' Agnos said. `We
could even read her lips saying `I am moving.'''
   At a news conference in front of the hospital Thursday, family
and friends of Ms. Huerta's expressed outrage at the alleged police
beating.
   ``I want to condemn the city of San Francisco and the Police
Department for permitting this type of activity to go on,'' said
tearful son Emilio Huerta.
   He said his mother was trying to speak to reporters outside the
St. Francis hotel to respond to Bush's statements against the UFW
grape boycott when she was ``herded'' into an area ``where she was
severely beaten by a member of the San Francisco Police
Department.''
   ``It wasn't a beating over the head or push _ she was speared
and stabbed to where her spleen was shattered,'' he said.
</TEXT>
