<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ToughPrincipal     09-16 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tough Principal,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Principal Joe Clark Runs For Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Principal Joe Clark, whose get-tough
stance on school drop-outs won him acrimony from his school board
but put him on the cover of Time, is running for political office
for the first time.
   Clark said Thursday he will be the Republican candidate in a
special election for Essex County's Third Freeholder District in
November. Clark was asked to run by county Republicans, said Essex
GOP leader John P. Renna.
   ``Nationally, he's hot stuff,'' Renna said.
   Clark, known to roam the halls of Paterson's East Side High
School with a bat and bullhorn, achieved national attention in
December when he clashed with the school board after expelling 61
students.
   His stance drew praise from U.S. Secretary of Education William
Bennett and his story was told in a movie released this summer,
``Lean on Me,'' which was filmed at the school.
   Clark, 50, lives in South Orange, one of four towns in the
heavily Democratic Third District. An interim freeholder has served
the area since Democrat Cardell Cooper left in May to become county
administrator.
   ``I am a great administrator,'' Clark said. ``I'm capable of
bringing situations from shame to fame instantaneously.''
   ``I think they're looking for someone with a name, who can
present a challenge,'' said Democratic Freeholder Sara Bost.
   Clark, who will run against Leroy J. Jones Jr. of East Orange,
admitted that he didn't know who his opponent was.
   ``I could care less,'' he said.
   Jones is chairman of the city's Affirmative Action Review Board
and the East Orange Citizens Advisory Board. A finance manager, he
holds a degree in accounting from Seton Hall University.
</TEXT>
