<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeverlyHighFashion     09-16 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beverly High Fashion,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School District Hopes To Cash In On Trendy Clothing Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beverly Hills school officials have
gone into the fashion business in hopes of cashing in on the
community's trendy image to help pay the bills.
   More than 50 products featuring pastels and geometric designs
with the Beverly Hills High School logo were to be unveiled today
in Los Angeles. Next month, London gets a look at the fashion line.
   School board member Frank Fenton suggested the idea three years
ago. ``Not every child can attend a Beverly Hills school, but I
want to give every child the opportunity to wear our T-shirts,
sweat shirts and our logo,'' he said.
   20th Century Fox is handling licensing and sales. Fox officials
would not quote a price range for the clothes, but the district
will get 60 percent of the profits. The district hopes to make
$250,000 this year.
   The district, with an annual budget of $26 million, is known for
high teacher salaries, small class sizes and a high school
cafeteria where students have the option of ordering a meal a la
carte.
   But falling enrollments, increasing operating expenses and
property tax limits have strained resources.
   The idea hasn't been a hit with all Beverly Hills residents,
however.
   ``This is one more piece of tinsel being added to the city,''
said Betty Harris, a longtime resident and community activist.
``Rodeo Drive is a circus and it has taken over everything.''
</TEXT>
