<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HomelessPossession     09-16 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Homeless Possession,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Los Angeles to Pay Homeless for Possessions Destroyed in Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-one homeless people whose possessions
were destroyed in a police sweep will receive $500 each, according
to terms of a settlement that some recipients said could free them
from life on the street.
   The city admitted no wrongdoing in the agreement, which provides
$20,500 to be divided among those affected in the incident. City
officials confirmed the settlement Thursday but declined to comment.
   The claims resulted from a June police sweep of two homeless
camps in the shadow of City Hall. Authorities said they gave an
estimated 50 people 30 minutes to clear out, but many were away
looking for food or work. They returned to find their possessions _
including medicine, identification papers and clothing _ were gone.
   Although the agreement doesn't guarantee that such sweeps won't
be conducted again, lawyers representing the homeless said it is an
important victory that should discourage officials from similar
seizures.
   ``I believe this has already affected the attitude and practice
of police everywhere in this city,'' said attorney James H. Davis,
who filed the claims on behalf of the homeless men and women.
   Many of the recipients said they would use the $500 to find
permanent shelter.
   ``We're going to get a place and get married,'' said Joseph
Wilson, 27, of his plans for the money.
   ``I'm trying to get ahead, I'm trying to have a future,'' said
Wilson, who added he has been sleeping on the street while studying
word processing at a technical school.
   Joseph Gabriel, 48, said he hopes to ``get a place and get off
the street. The streets are making me old.''
   However, Ted Hayes, an activist for the homeless and one of the
41 to file a claim against the city, warned: ``Five hundred dollars
is not going to get anybody off the street.''
</TEXT>
