<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-25thAmendment 1stLd-Writethru a0418 09-16 0944</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-25th Amendment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0418,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Denies Aides Checked His Mental Fitness</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says there isn't ``an iota of
truth'' to an account that aides questioned whether he was mentally
fit to serve at the height of the Iran-Contra crisis. But a former
aide said today it would have been irresponsible for him not to
raise the issue.
   ``There's no truth to any of this,'' Reagan said Thursday when
asked about the report in a new book that aides weighed whether to
invoke the 25th Amendment, providing for the vice president to take
over if a president is unable to discharge his duties.
   ``It's just ridiculous,'' Reagan said while attending the annual
White House picnic for members of Congress. ``There isn't an iota
of truth in the whole story.''
   As to whether people were considering invoking the 25th
Amendment, the president said, ``I never knew that anyone was. I
don't think anyone was.''
   James Cannon, a former Senate aide to Howard H. Baker Jr. who
was on the transition team when Baker succeeded Donald T. Regan as
White House chief of staff, confirmed most of the account,
attributed to him, in the book ``Landslide'' by reporters Jane
Mayer of the Wall Street Journal and Doyle McManus of the Los
Angeles Times, published by Houghton Mifflin.
   Cannon, in an interview on ``CBS This Morning,'' defended his
decision to raise the issue of the president's mental state and the
possible use of the 25th Amendment to Baker after he had
interviewed several White House staff members as part of the
transition.
   ``I think it would have been irresponsible not to given what I
had been told by senior staff member who had been working with him
(Reagan,)'' Cannon said.
   Cannon said he interviewed White House aides on Feb. 27 and 28,
1987, just after Baker accepted the job, and ``a pattern of
responses evolved that the real problem you have to worry about is
the president. ... They would say he's not paying attention, he's
not reading his memos, he doesn't come to the office, he stays over
in the residence.''
   On March 1, the book says, Cannon wrote a memo to Baker
suggesting that his first priority be to ``consider the possibility
that section four of the 25th Amendment might be applied.''
   After Cannon presented and discussed the memo at a meeting at
Baker's home that night, Baker is quoted in the book as saying,
``Well, it doesn't sound like the Ronald Reagan I just saw, but
we'll see tomorrow.''
   Baker on Thursday said he does not recall ``any serious
consideration ever of invoking the 25th Amendment.''
   He called Reagan ``strong and assertive and perhaps the most
presidential man I ever knew'' and said Reagan was ``fully in
charge, fully capable, and fully presidential.''
   According to the book, Baker and his top aides were prepared,
when they assembled in the West Wing of the White House the morning
after Cannon raised the problem ``to watch the president closely,
to determine whether he appeared mentally fit to serve.''
   The account goes on to say that at a working lunch which Baker
and three aides attended, Reagan seemed relaxed and animated and
Cannon wondered, ``What the hell is going on here? The old fella
looks just dandy.''
   Cannon, in an interview with Cable News Network, said that of
the staffers he talked to ``not all but most said in one way or
another that the president was inattentive, that he had lost
interest in his job.''
   He later said on the CBS Evening News, ``My concern then and
today is that they were more loyal to Don Regan than they were to
Ronald Reagan.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the March 2
luncheon did occur, but ``Senator Baker and Culvahouse and others
don't describe any kind of situation the way Jim Cannon does.''
   ``What you have here is you have Cannon talking to a bunch of
people who for all practical purposes had just been relieved of
their duties. Effectively, every one knew when Regan left they were
all leaving. They all were gone within a week.''
   However, Tom Dawson, who was one of Regan's top aides when he
was chief of staff, said, ``Let's start thinking who those people
might have been. There were not very many of them. I can't even get
up to five. So Cannon has an arithmetic problem.''
   Regan, asked in Portland, Maine, about the book's assertion that
the president was out of touch, said: ``Well, I'm a little doubtful
of that. Of course the White House was in somewhat of disorder. He
was down because he had had an operation in early January, but I
think by that time he had fully recovered from it. ``
   In his book ``For The Record,'' published last spring, Regan
portrayed Reagan as disengaged and indecisive.
   Dawson said Cannon did not talk to him. Fitzwater said he did
not talk to him either. Fitzwater also said that Colin Powell, then
the deputy national security adviser, told him Cannon did not talk
either to him or to his superior, Frank C. Carlucci. Carlucci, who
was succeeded as national security adviser by Powell, is now
secretary of defense.
   Peter Wallison, former White House counsel, who was replaced by
Culvahouse after Baker became chief of staff, said he did talk to
Cannon, but ``he didn't ask me about the question of the
president's mental health, and I didn't tell him anything about the
president's mental health.''
   ``I never saw anything that suggested the president wasn't fully
in charge,'' Wallison said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
