<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-China     09-16 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-China,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Calls for Improved Ties With China, Renews Summit Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gorbachev</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev made another pitch today for
improving Soviet relations with China and renewed a call for a
Sino-Soviet summit.
   ``We stand for the full normalization of relations with the
People's Republic of China, for their development up to the level
adequate to our two countries' responsiblity for peaceful world
policy,'' Gorbachev said in a major speech in the Siberian city of
Krasnoyarsk.
   Gorbachev first proposed a summit with Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping in a speech in the eastern Soviet city of Vladivostok,
near the Chinese border, on July 28, 1986.
   Chinese Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang said last
month the first Sino-Soviet summit since 1960 was possible if
Moscow first urged Vietnam to leave Cambodia.
   Since the Vladivostok speech, Gorbachev has taken several steps
to remove obstacles to improving ties with the Chinese.
   China has listed the impediments as the Soviet intervention in
Afghanistan, Moscow's support of Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia
and Soviet troops stationed along the Soviet border with China.
   The Kremlin has moved to clear some of the obstacles. In May, it
began withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan and has pulled some
of its forces out of Mongolia, which borders China.
   Gorbachev also has offered to accept China's request that the
two countries' border be fixed at the main navigation channel in
the Amur River.
   The Kremlin agreed to its first direct talks with the Chinese
focusing solely on the Cambodia issue. In five-day talks that began
Aug. 29 in Beijing, both sides said they found common ground but
achieved no breakthroughs in resolving the 10-year-old Cambodian
conflict.
   In his speech today, Gorbachev said the Beijing discussions on
Cambodia had ``contributed to improving Soviet-Chinese relations,''
according to the Tass news agency. He also called for direct talks
between China and Vietnam on the issue.
   Since the Vladivostok speech, Soviet and Chinese top envoys have
been meeting regularly to discuss normalization and border issues.
   The Kremlin's ties with Beijing have been strained since the
Communist giants split over ideological and strategic differences
in the early 1960s.
   Gorbachev said the people of the two countries are ready for a
rapprochement.
   ``There is ever more goodwill and trust in relations between the
Soviet and Chinese peoples,'' he said. ``Their profound interest in
one another has been resumed and is being filled with new content.
Mutual attraction is growing.''
</TEXT>
