<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Noriega-Drugs     09-16 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega-Drugs,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Motion Could Influence U.S. Election, Prosecutor Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A motion to dismiss drug-trafficking charges
against Panamanian ruler Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega has been
sealed at the request of a prosecutor, who says it could influence
the U.S. presidential election.
   But Miami attorney Neal Sonnett, Noriega's principal lawyer, on
Thursday denied Noriega was trying to plant a political bombshell,
saying the motion was routine and that prosecutors had an
``overactive imagination.''
   Sonnett's dismissal motion, filed Thursday, was ordered sealed
in advance by presiding U.S. District Court Judge William Hoeveler
at the request of prosecutor Richard Gregorie.
   ``My concern is that Noriega would see this as an opportunity to
put materials in there that could have some bearing on our election
and might use that as some sort of blackmail to cut himself a deal
with the U.S. government,'' Gregorie said Thursday.
   ``I want to be sure that ... this is not being used as some
political tool to attempt to coerce the administration into some
sort of deal,'' he said. ``It doesn't matter to me who's in power.
I'm a prosecutor, not a politician. I just don't want them to play
politics with it.''
   Sonnett has indicated in past hearings that he would argue that
the indictment should be dismissed because the U.S. government has
no legal right to indict the Panamanian leader, and because U.S.
courts have no jurisdiction to try him.
   A 12-count indictment returned by a federal grand jury in Miami
in February accused Noriega of accepting $4.6 million in bribes
from Colombia's violent Medellin drug cartel. A grand jury in Tampa
indicted Noriega the next day on three marijuana importation counts.
   The Reagan administration offered in May to drop criminal
charges against Noriega if he agreed to step down, but protracted
negotiations broke down without agreement.
</TEXT>
