<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PTL     09-16 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PTL,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bakker: `I Don't Intend To Lose' PTL Suit Seeking $52 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BROOKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PTL founder Jim Bakker says he doesn't
have the money to repay his former ministry's $52 million claim
against him and others, but he says that doesn't matter because he
plans to win the case.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Rufus Reynolds halted the trial
Thursday and scheduled it to resume Oct. 17. Reynolds said that
during the interim he will read depositions from Bakker and others,
and defense attorneys will prepare to respond to evidence presented
by PTL.
   Attorneys for the Fort Mill-based ministry want Bakker, his
wife, Tammy, and former aide David Taggart to repay money they say
was lost through mismanagement of PTL accounts and grossly inflated
compensation.
   When asked outside the courthouse Thursday how he would pay if
he lost the suit, Bakker responded: ``You can't get blood from a
turnip. I don't intend to lose.''
   The trial, which is being held without a jury, began Monday.
   Bakker said in court Thursday that PTL attorneys and the IRS
were wrong about the amount of money he received.
   ``I see figures on there (charts presented by PTL attorneys)
that I can't recall at all, like in 1984, that $390,000 bonus, I
can't recall that at all,'' Bakker testified.
   ``Looking at the charts in this room and the figures, and those
in the IRS preliminary report, compared to our research, shows so
much error that proper auditing and examining must be done to
obtain the truth,'' he said.
   He said he believes some financial records were destroyed after
he left the ministry in March 1987 amid a sex and money scandal.
   Last week, Bakker had claimed he had the financing to regain
PTL, which Reynolds has ordered sold. PTL Trustee M.C. ``Red''
Benton had called Bakker the leading bidder with a $172 million
offer until Bakker could not prove he had the money.
   Testifying in the Bankruptcy Court trial this week, Bakker
contradicted testimony that the board of directors never approved
his salaries.
   He said his salary was set by the board, which also approved his
raises. But earlier, former board member Charles H. Cookman
testified that the board ``never ruled on salaries.''
   Peter Bailey, a former accountant and financial director at PTL,
testified that he routinely warned Bakker of the financial troubles
the ministry was having. He said top executives received bonuses in
some cases in anticipation of future donations, when there wasn't
money in the bank to cover the checks.
   But Bakker attorney Ryan Hovis told Reynolds that the continuing
financial crisis PTL experienced under Bakker's leadership was par
for the course.
   ``Every ministry of this type in the nation had the same type of
financial crisis,'' Hovis said. ``It goes with the territory.''
</TEXT>
