<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0524,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curfews in Gaza, Police Question Israeli Who Met Arafat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with deaths in south Lebanon and comments
from Nathan. CORRECTS death toll to 266 in last graf. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGARODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army ordered 180,000 Palestinian refugees
to stay in their homes in the occupied Gaza Strip today in
anticipation of a general strike called by Moslem fundamentalists
and PLO-linked underground leaders.
   In a pre-dawn firefight in south Lebanon, Israeli troops killed
three guerrillas without suffering casualties, the army said.
   Documents found on the bodies showed the guerrillas belonged to
Yasser Arafat's Fatah branch of the PLO, Israel radio said.
   In Gaza, the round-the-clock curfew was imposed indefinitely on
the Shati, Jabaliya, Nusseirat, Bureij, Maghazi and Khan Yunis
camps, the army and Arab reports said.
   It came after a violent clash at the camp Thursday night in
which 20 Palestinians attacked Israeli soldiers with firebombs,
iron chains and clubs, the army said. Troops opened fire, wounding
two Palestinians, the army said.
   Also today, peace crusader Abie Nathan was summoned before
police in the Tel Aviv suburb of Petah Tikva for an investigation
into his meeting with Palestine Liberation Organization chief
Yasser Arafat in Tunis, Tunisia, on Tuesday.
   Nathan faces up to three years in jail for breaking an Israeli
law banning contacts with terrorist groups. Israel views the PLO as
a terrorist group.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said today Nathan didn't
understand who he was dealing with when he met Arafat.
   ``Nathan is a decent and naive man, (but) the naive men don't
understand whom they are dealing with,'' Rabin said on Israel radio.
   Nathan, who returned to Israel Thursday, said he did not carry a
message from Arafat to Israeli leaders but would request a meeting
with Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres to brief them on his talks.
   Nathan presented Arafat with a peace plan calling for mutual
recognition between Israel and the PLO.
   After the interrogation, Nathan said it had gone ``very
smoothly.'' He said he argued he did not violate Israel's
anti-terrorist law since he met with Arafat to promote peace.
   ``I believe I achieved something. I tried to ... show the world
the desire for peace among the people over here,'' he said.
   Also today, the army said it created a special military command
unit to oversee operations in the West Bank.
   The unit is to be headed by Brig. Gen. Gabi Ofir, who vowed in
comments broadcast by Israel Army radio: ``We will not allow the
violence to become a disrupting factor.''
   The Gaza curfew was ordered to prevent violence during a general
strike ordered by underground leaders for Saturday to mark the
anniversary of the 1982 massacre of hundreds of Palestinian
refugees in the Sabra and Chatilla camps in Lebanon, army radio
said.
   In Gaza City, Islamic militants belonging to the underground
group Hamas, or Zeal, painted grafitti calling on merchants to
observe the strike, Arab witnesses said. Among the slogans was one
which read ``Death to the Jews'' in Hebrew and Arabic.
   Thursday was proclaimed a day of reckoning against collaborators
by pro-PLO underground leaders, who ordered Palestinians to kill
Arabs who collaborated with Israel.
   Five alleged collaborators have been slain over the past 11 days
and a total of seven have been killed since the uprising began Dec.
8.
   At least 266 Palestinians have been killed during the
nine-month-old uprising. Six Israelis also have died.
</TEXT>
