<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Blooper 1stLd-Writethru a0462 09-16 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Blooper, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Needled About Blooper on Pearl Harbor Date</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 new grafs after pvs 3rd graf bgng, ``But the big,''
with Bush slip of tongue on anti-Semitism today.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush was teased and
supported about his blooper on the date of the bombing of Pearl
Harbor, and said politicians are fair game for attacks when they
screw up.
   Asked by a boy at Ygnacio Valley High School if he didn't want
to ``deck'' Democratic rival Michael Dukakis for teasing him about
his error, Bush said, ``We'll foul up and he'll jump on me and
he'll make some mistakes and I'll jump on him.
   ``But the big thing is to get the issues out there so the
American people can see them,'' Bush said.
   The vice president had another slip of the tongue today when he
said in Columbus, Ohio, that he favored anti-Semitism.
   Asked about the recent resignations of six members of his
campaign committee on ethnic voters because of past alleged
pro-Nazi or anti-Semitic ties, Bush replied: ``I hope I stand for
anti-bigotry, anti-Semitism, anti-racism. That is what drives me.
It's one of the things that I feel very strongly about.''
   Answering the California students' questions Thursday, Bush said
he expects to receive some flak for his misstatements on the
campaign trial, but is hardly bothered by it.
   ``Once in a while you do get sore, once in a while you might get
a little tense. But you know when you make a mistake like that, I
expect somebody to jump on me. Bob Hope did it. Didn't bother me.
Johnny Carson did it, and that didn't bother me,'' Bush said.
   The subject was first raised in a question-and-answer session at
the school by a girl who shouted ``When was Pearl Harbor?''
   Last week in Louisville, Ky., Bush mistakenly said the
anniversary was Sept. 7, not Dec. 7.
   Replying to the girl, Bush said, ``I'm glad you asked that
question. You ever made a mistake in your life, anybody here? I
know she hasn't.
   ``But has anyone here made a mistake, ever. Come on guys,'' Bush
said.
   ``Now let me tell you how that happens. It's a good question,
fair question. I tell you how it happens. You get a little tired
from time to time. I'm glad to be here in Connecticut,'' he joked.
   ``But, if you really want a serious answer to it, I remember
because I fought for my country in war,'' Bush said, recounting his
service as a naval bomber pilot in World War II and noting that he
was shot down in combat.
   ``So let there be no mistake about it,'' Bush said.``I remember
Pearl Harbor pretty well, firsthand, and I hope we'll never have
another one. ...''
</TEXT>
