<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0442,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walesa Meets with Authorities on Future of Solidarity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland-Dialogue, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with talks beginning, quotes. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and a team
of union activists met with Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszcak today
to set an agenda for talks on the future of the banned trade union.
   The meeting, which included at least 10 Solidarity members or
advisers, marked the first time since the union was banned in 1982
that so many union activists sat down with government officials.
   The third encounter between Walesa and the government began this
afternoon at an undisclosed location outside Warsaw, said Roman
Catholic Church attorney Jacek Ambroziak.
   ``After two meetings of our chairman alone, there is now a
serious delegation,'' said senior Solidarity adviser Bronislaw
Geremek.
   The expansion of the number of participants in the talks ``is a
serious step in the right direction,'' Geremek said. ``A Solidarity
delegation is talking to the authorities at last.''
   At least 23 people, including 11 officials led by Kiszczak and
two priests, were participating in the talks.
   Earlier Walesa said he was optimistic that broader talks with
the government on Solidarity would begin soon.
   The comment came after Walesa met for more than four hours
Thursday with Kiszcak, his second meeting with Polish authorities
in six years.
   The two agreed Thursday to continue working toward an early
start of talks on Poland's future with broader participation.
   They also agreed to expand the group of participants at today's
working meeting and to agree on the topics, composition, as well as
the procedure and work schedule of the later talks, the state-run
news service PAP said Thursday.
   Walesa told reporters after the meeting that ``the atmosphere is
encouraging'' but difficule problems remain.
   The government agreed to the talks and Walesa moved to halt a
wave of strikes last month that posed the most serious threat to
the government since Solidarity was crushed in 1981. It was
declared illegal a year later.
   Today's meeting was to include some leaders of Solidarity
strikes last month as well as at least five members of the official
trade union alliance OPZZ, said Franciszek Ciemny, an OPZZ
spokesman.
   In another development, an official newspaper published an
interview with Walesa for the first time since the imposition of
martial law in December 1981.
   The interview in the September issue of the monthly publication
Konfrontacje, which came out Thursday, seemed to underline Walesa's
return to official respectability and the new emphasis on
considering divergent views.
   The monthly, sponsored by the official national unity
organization PRON, interviewed the Solidarity leader at his home on
Sept. 1, the day a strike at the Gdansk shipyard led by Walesa
ended.
   ``You are the first Polish journalists from the officially
published press to come to me asking for an interview since Dec.
13, 1981,'' Walesa said, referring to the exact date of the martial
law crackdown that suppressed Solidarity, the first independent
trade union movement allowed in the Soviet bloc.
   ``There must be Solidarity,'' the interview quoted Walesa as
saying. But in it he added, ``It certainly does not have to be a
carbon copy of that of 1981.''
</TEXT>
