<1ST_LINE>r w PM-POW-MIARecognition     09-16 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-POW-MIA Recognition,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci: U.S.-Vietnamese Search for MIAs Begins Sept. 25</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Vietnam will begin joint
efforts to find the remains of American sericemen missing in
action, Defense Secretary Franc C. Carlucci said today.
   His announcent came at a National POW-MIA Recognition Day
ceremony on Capitol Hill, where House Minority Leader Robert Michel
urged the administration to ``press for an accounting of each and
every one'' of the 2,393 American troops still unaccounted for
following the Vietnam war.
   ``The Defense Department is committed to doing everything
possible to resolve the POW-MIA issue successfully,'' Carlucci told
a crowd of several hundred gathered on the Capitol steps.
   ``Today, we are encouraged in our quest, but we still await the
results that we know are possible from those who hold the
answers,'' he said. ``Although last month Vietnam temporarily
suspended its offer to conduct joint operations, it recently agreed
to resume cooperation, and I am pleased to announce that joint
activity will begin on Sept. 25.''
   Michel, R-Ill., and Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas
pledged continued congressional support for efforts to uncover the
facts about 79,000 troops missing in action from World War II,
8,000 from the Korean War and those unaccounted for in Southeast
Asia.
   ``We must continue to seek the truth about our POW-MIAs,''
Michel said. ``But the two greatest enemies of truth are rumors and
false hopes.
   ``Nothing could be more cruel to the families of MIAs and POWs
than to lend credence to false rumors, to raise hopes without the
fact to support them, to muddy the waters and confuse the issue.
Nothing could be more detrimental to this cause than to let emotion
cloud our judgment.''
   Meanwhile, wreath laying ceremonies were scheduled today at the
Arlington National Cemetery in memory of POWs and MIAs from the
Korean War.
   An organization dedicated to remembering the families of missing
soldiers, No Greater Love, estimates that there are 8,100 MIAs and
389 POWs still unaccounted for in Korea.
</TEXT>
