<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0561 09-16 0975</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0561,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Spar Over Democrat's Budget Policies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 12 grafs new with Bush defense comments; pick up 11th
graf pvs bgng ``Two days before...; Delete final 3 grafs to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush said today rival Michael Dukakis has
``been made over'' in an effort to win back Democratic voters who
twice put President Reagan in office. Dukakis was striking an
anti-crime note on the West Coast.
   Bush toured a steel plant in Columbus, Ohio, that was once
headed by his grandfather and sought steelworkers' votes by saying
he had more common ground with them than the Democrats.
   Dukakis was campaigning in Southern California, stressing the
fight against drugs and crime with an appearance at a police
academy. The Democratic nominee also was expected to announce plans
to expand the Drug Enforcement Administration, if elected.
   Bush said Dukakis was ``way over in left field'' on some issues
of concern to blue-collar workers. ``These people don't want gun
control. They do favor the death penalty,'' the vice president said.
   Bush referred to Dukakis' brief ride in an M-1 tank earlier this
week and said, ``You cannot fool the Soviet leadership by knocking
America's defense for 10 years and riding around in a tank for 10
minutes. ... You can't fool the American people.''
   The Republican nominee said Dukakis was modifying his positions
on defense to woo back the Reagan Democrats who could decide the
election.
   ``He's gone to states like this, found that his message of ...
cutting unilaterally on these weapons systems is not popular, Bush
said. ``He's coming out with policies quite different, but which
ones do you believe?''
   Running mate Dan Quayle also assailed Dukakis today, turning a
question on his own qualifications into an attack on the Democrat's
lack of foreign policy experience. ``I have 12 years of experience
in Congress. I understand national security measures, which is a
very important requirement,'' the Indiana senator said in Overland
Park, Kan.
   A day earlier, Bush selectively used economic statistics to
charge tha Dukakis had led Massachusetts into a ``budgetary Three
Mile Island.'' The Democratic nominee, initially reluctant to join
the rhetorical fray, defended his state's economy as sound.
   Questioned about Bush's charges, a reticent Dukakis told
reporters joining him on a tour of fire-ravaged Yellowstone
National Park that he would reserve comment until ``sometime next
week.''
   But later, the Democratic nominee chose to respond to the
attacks, and cited his state's low unemployment rate _ 3 percent _
and 10 straight balanced budgets.
   Upon arriving in Los Angeles, Dukakis again, without prompting,
told reporters, ``What Mr. Bush has given us is a mountain of debt,
record deficits, a record trade deficit and an economic future that
does not bode well for the American people.''
   Two days before the Summer Olympics, Bush told a business group
in San Francisco that Dukakis is the ``gold medal winner in the
tax-and-spend competition.''
   The Republican nominee added: ``Under my opponent, Massachusetts
has lost _ lost _ 26,000 jobs since 1983, more than any other state
in the country.''
   Federal figures show that Massachusetts has gained more than
230,000 jobs in the past five years, while losing manufacturing
jobs. The text of the vice president's speech said ``manufacturing
jobs,'' and Bush aides said the campaign stands by that description.
   Bush also said that as governor, Dukakis has tried to raise
taxes five times, including a $180 million jump in business taxes,
sales taxes and personal income taxes this past summer.
   There have been no broad-based tax increases in Dukakis' two
terms as governor beginning in 1983, while there have been numerous
tax cuts. But Bush said correctly that Dukakis pushed through a
major tax increase in 1975 during his first term. That hike was
repealed when taxpayers rebelled.
   ``The fact is the so-called Massachusetts miracle is really the
Massachusetts mirage. And right now that state is approaching a
fiscal fiasco that might best be described as a budgetary Three
Mile Island ... facing a budgetary meltdown,'' the vice president
said.
   In Los Angeles, Dukakis answered the charge, saying, ``Anybody
who'd compare my state's economy with Three Mile Island must be
suffering meltdown.''
   One debate the Democratic nominee refused to get involved in was
the argument over whether the forest fires that have decimated the
West should have been allowed to burn unchecked.
   ``This isn't the time to discuss what might have been or should
be,'' Dukakis said as he toured the park. ``Everbody agrees that
once the fires are out, it'll be a good time to sit down and think
through exactly how we deal with this problem in the future.''
   Bush, at a question-and-answer session with high school students
in Concord, Calif., was drawn into the question of a pardon for
Iran-Contra figure Oliver North.
   ``The question is for me _ pardon imputes guilt, and therefore I
have refused to speculate on this because I want to see this man
have a fair trial. I hope he's found innocent. ...
   ``In my description anybody that shed his blood in Vietnam with
two or three purple hearts is a hero for that,'' Bush said. ``Now
did he make some mistakes? Maybe so. But you're not going to see me
picking on Ollie North.''
   One high school girl teased Bush about his verbal faux pas last
week on the date of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor _ the vice
president mistakenly said the anniversary was Sept. 7, ot Dec. 7.
   ``When was Pearl Harbor?'' she asked.
   Bush joked about being in Connecticut rather than California,
asked the girl if she ever made a mistake and then recalled his
service as a naval bomber pilot in World War II.
   ``I remember Pearl Harbor pretty well, firsthand, and I hope
we'll never have another one ...''
</TEXT>
