<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CanyonSlayings     09-16 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canyon Slayings,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberace's Ex-Lover Reportedly Linked To Canyon Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who claimed to be Liberace's lover gave
evidence leading to new murder charges in a 1981 quadruple slaying
for which pornographic film star John Holmes was acquitted, it was
reported today.
   Scott Thorson, who is awaiting sentencing for a drug-related
armed robbery, linked convicted cocaine dealer Adel Nasrallah to
the bludgeoning attack on five people at a hillside home in
exclusive Laurel Canyon, the Los Angeles Times reported. The story
cited unidentified sources familiar with the case.
   Nasrallah, 59, who goes by the name of Eddie Nash, and his
former bodyguard, Gregory Dewitt Diles, 40, were charged Sept. 8
with four counts of murder and one count of attempted murder in the
case.
   Neither have entered pleas to the charges and both are being
held without bail. If convicted, they could face the death penalty.
   Holmes, king of pornographic films in the 1970s, was
unsuccessfully prosecuted for the murders in 1982. He died of
AIDS-related complications in March at the age of 43.
   Thorson, 29, is being held under tight security at the county
jail while he awaits sentencing after pleading guilty to the armed
robbery.
   When the charges against Nash and Diles were filed, deputy
district attorney Dale A. Davidson said new witnesses had come
forward but declined to identify them or discuss the evidence.
   On Thursday, he refused to say whether Thorson will be called to
testify against Nash. Thorson's attorney in the robbery case,
deputy public defender Cathy Dreyfuss, also declined to comment.
   The Times quoted sources as saying that Thorson, who lived with
Liberace and served as the pianist's chauffeur, secretary and, by
his own account, his lover from 1977 until 1982, also maintained a
close relationship with Nash during much of that period.
   ``Eddie was Scott's cocaine connection,'' the newspaper quoted
one source as saying.
   According to testimony at Holmes' 1982 trial, the porn star once
told Los Angeles police that he had led killers to a home in Laurel
Canyon at the request of Nash, who prosecutors said wanted revenge
because he had been robbed two days earlier.
   Four people were bludgeoned to death. The fifth survived but was
unable to identify her attackers.
   Thorson filed a highly publicized lawsuit against Liberace in
1982, in which he contended that the entertainer, who never
acknowledged being a homosexual, had reneged on promises to support
him for the rest of his life. The suit was settled out of court
shortly before Liberace died of AIDS in 1987.
</TEXT>
