<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0490 09-16 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0490,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Dismisses Questions About His Fitness for High Office</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Quayle breakfast remarks; picks up pvs
5th graf bgng, Quayle has.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate
Dan Quayle said today his experience in Congress and understand of
national security issues qualify him for high office, and that his
youth should not be any barrier.
   Addressing the suburban Overland Park Chamber of Commerce before
campaigning in Nebraska and Iowa, the Indiana senator also joked
that his campaign managers sometimes try to hide him from the
public when things go wrong.
   ``Sometimes they tell you to go to your room,'' Quayle said.
``And with some of the comments that I've made, I've been told that
several times. It's no fun sitting alone in your room.''
   Dealing with the issue of his fitness to serve as vice
president, Quayle said:
   ``I have 12 years of experience in Congress. I understand
national security measures, which is a very important requirement.
A lot has been made about my age and that 41 is too young. Jack
Kennedy was about my age when he ran for president.''
   John F. Kennedy was 43 when he beat Republican Vice President
Richard Nixon for the presidency in 1960.
   At Oklahoma City on Thursday, at his first news conference in
two weeks, Quayle said that the voters eventually ``will see the
real Dan Quayle, what he stands for,'' and make up their own minds.
   He dismissed as ``irrelevant'' questions about his past, such as
his college performance and why he did not make public his academic
records.
   Quayle has said he did not want reporters scrutinizing his less
than stellar grades.
   ``Winston Churchill was not a great student,'' Quayle said. ``He
was a great leader. FDR (Franklin D. Roosevelt) failed the bar
examination a number of times. He turned out to be a great
president.''
   According to biographies, Roosevelt entered Columbia University
Law School in 1904, a year after graduating from Harvard. He took
and passed the bar examination in 1907 and left Columbia that year
before receiving a degree.
   Referring to controversies over his military service during the
Vietnam War, his academic performance and his personal life, Quayle
said he was ``not going to focus on what I have done in the past''
but on ``what I stand for, what I articulate to the American
people.''
   ``The American people will judge me on what I am saying and what
I have done in the last 12 years in the Congress,'' he said.
   Quayle said he was not worried about a poll this week indicating
that a substantial portion of likely voters have reservations about
his credentials to serve in high office.
   A CBS-New York Times poll found that one-third of those
responding said Quayle was qualified to be president compared with
three-fifths who said the same of his Democratic counterpart, Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen of Texas.
   ``I think it's fair to say that in the last few weeks, the
American people have been told a different story about Dan Quayle
than what Dan Quayle has tried to communicate to the American
people,'' he said.
   Quayle was asked to explain his comment last week that Mikhail
S. Gorbachev was no different from other Soviet leaders and that
his perestroika policy of economic restructuring was ``nothing more
than refined Stalinism.''
   ``I have a hunch that restructuring in fact is to make sure that
Gorbachev gets his people into the political system and the people
who are not supporting him, out,'' Quayle said. ``That is classic
Stalinism. That's the way Stalin ran the country.''
   Quayle was asked how he would finance such costly proposals as
modernizing U.S. strategic nuclear missiles and President Reagan's
Star Wars plan for a space-based missile defense system at a time
of steep budget deficits.
   ``There will be some tough choices,'' Quayle replied.
   He said defense budget increases would have to be limited to 1
percent to 2 percent above inflation over the next two to five
years.
</TEXT>
