<HEAD>GOP Congressmen Say Three Dukakis Backers Are Anti-Israeli</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of House Republicans charged today
that Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis appointed
three ``anti-Israeli, pro-Palestinian'' members to the party's
ruling body and challenged him to dismiss them.
   The challenge was a clear effort to counter problems in the
campaign of GOP nominee George Bush, who has dumped eight campaign
advisers in the past week following charges of anti-Semitism
against them.
   Rep. Norman Lent, R-N.Y., said the three objectionable members
were appointed to the 400-member Democratic National Committee
following the party's July convention in Atlanta as a gesture of
conciliation to defeated presidential contender Jesse Jackson.
   He identified the three as the Rev. Willie Barrow, executive
director of Jackson's Chicago-based Operation PUSH; Robert Farrell,
a Los Angeles city councilman and close Jackson associate; and Ruth
Ann Skaff of Houston, whom he said is a spokeswoman for the
pro-Palestinian Ad Hoc Committtee on Lebanon.
   Lent said Barrow and Farrell are supporters of radical Muslim
leader Louis Farrakhan, who has made anti-Semitic statements. He
said Skaff has led anti-Israel demonstrations.
   ``The presence of (the three) on the Democratic team raises
questions about Michael Dukakis' judgment and his submission to
Jesse Jackson,'' Lent said at a news conference. ``Obviously,
Governor Dukakis has failed to grasp the message his appointments
send.''
   Lent said Bush had acted quickly to clean house when similar
allegations were raised about members of an ethnic coaliton
supporting his campaign and when it was reported that Bush adviser
Frederic V. Malek made a count of Jews in key jobs at the Bureau of
Labor Statistics in 1971.
   ``It's time for Michael Dukakis to show that he truly is in
charge,'' Lent said. ``He is the nominee of his party and should
have control over the party structure.''
   Appearing with Lent were Reps. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y., John
Miller, R-Wash., Guy Molinari, R-N.Y. and Vin Weber, R-Minn.
   Another Republican member of Congress, Sen. Rudy Boschwitz of
Minnesota, told reporters he had turned down a request from Bush
campaign aides take part in the attack.
   ``I don't want to do it,'' Boschwitz, a prominent Jewish
politican. ``I don't think there's any political future in these
charges and countercharges.''
   Two of the three DNC members under attack, Skaff and Farrell,
defended their stance on Israel. Barrow could not be reached
immediately for comment.
   ``Attacking individuals such as myself and Rev. Willie Barrow
and Councilman Farrell is a desperate and dangerous move by the
Bush campaign,'' said Skaff, the Texas coordinator for the Arab
American Institute.
   ``Targeting me as an Arab-American, and targeting my views on
this issue truly endangers the political security of Americans of
Arab heritage. Am I guilty of crime because my grandparents came
from Lebanon?'' she said.
   Skaff said she favors an independent Palestinian state, but only
``premised upon the security of Israel.'' And she said that she has
always condemned terrorism, but recognizes the Palestine Liberation
Organization because Palestinians have themselves chosen the group
as their representative.
   Farrell was criticized in 1985 when he refused to sign a
newspaper ad condemning anti-Semitic remarks attributed to Louis
Farrakhan, leader of the Nation of Islam.
   Farrell said Thursday he was unaware of the Farrakhan remarks at
the time and that he would gladly sign any letter opposing
anti-Semitic remarks.
   ``I'm very disappointed in someone in the Republican camp who
would take something as serious as relationships between blacks and
Jews and exacerbate them for political gain,'' he said.
   Barrow was quoted in a 1985 article in the Washington Post as
saying, ``I love my brother, Minister Louis Farrakhan. The devil
don't like it, Chicago don't like it, the world don't like it, but
we love it.''
   She said Thursday she was praising Farrakhan's role in
encouraging economic development in black communities at a meeting
held to discuss that development.
   She said she supports a Palestinian homeland, along with Israeli
security.
   Bush's campaign could not immediately be reached for comment.
   A spokeswoman for the Democratic National Committee, Robin
Diamond, said that body had no immediate comment.
</TEXT>
