<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--ArmyHotLine     09-16 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Army Hot Line,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dutch Army Offers Hot Line For Soldiers To Complain</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ Dutch soldiers who say their drill
sergeants beat or bullied them now can call a toll-free telephone
number to complain, the Defense Ministry said Friday.
   The 24-hour-a-day hot line is the government's latest move to
protect its 50,000 conscripts and 56,000 professional military,
whose rights already encompass labor unions, a 40-hour work week
and the right to adopt any hair style that doesn't interfere with
their duties.
   The line opened Thursday and is manned round the clock by a team
of social workers.
   ``We're definitely not looking for calls from people who say `I
want to go visit my granny this weekend but they won't let me,''' a
ministry spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   He said the ministry will investigate complaints ranging from
violent behavior and sexual abuse to bullying by superiors and
other soldiers.
</TEXT>
