<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Nicaraguan 1stLd-Writethru   09-16 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaraguan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0463,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Accept Sandinista Offer for Talks, Plan Congressional
Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lede graf and 6th graf new with congressional meeting.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan Contras have accepted a
Sandinista offer to hold preliminary talks in Guatemala City on
Monday to end the conflict in the Central American country and have
set up meetings today with U.S. Congressional leaders.
   ``We hope we can achieve a breakthrough and create momentum,''
Bosco Matamoros, a spokesman for the Contra rebels who oppose
Nicaragua's Marxist government, said Thursday.
   He said the resistance had urged the Sandinistas to then proceed
to high-level talks Sept. 26-28 in Guatemala, Costa Rica or the
Dominican Republic.
   But Matamoros said the Nicaraguan government would have to free
all remaining political prisoners and permit ``freedom of
expression'' for negotiations to succeed.
   It was not clear whether this amounted to the Contras setting
conditions and whether they would be acceptable to the Sandinistas.
   In the meantime, Contra leaders planned separate meetings on
Capitol Hill with Speaker Jim Wight, D-Texas, and House Republican
Leader Bob Michael of Illinois.
   ``We are concerned there be an adequate climate, and we ask the
government of Nicaragua to remove these obstacles,'' Matamoros said.
   He said Victor Tinoco, Nicaragua's vice minister of foreign
affairs, had been notified in Managua of the Contras' acceptance of
the preliminary meeting.
   At the same time, Matamoros stressed it was up to the
Sandinistas ``to create a favorable climate for a round of
negotiations at the high level'' to work out a peaceful settlement.
   Negotiations between the two sides broke down in Managua in June
after 11 weeks in a dispute over whether the steps demanded by the
Contras were part of a Central American peace plan.
   The Sandinistas say the negotiations collapsed because of
last-minute Contra demands over what were essentially domestic
political issues.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz met Wednesday with
resistance leaders. Matamoros and a U.S. official said the decision
to accept the Sandinista offer for a preliminary meeting was made
independently by the resistance group.
   Asked if the preliminary talks would lead to high-level
negotiations and a settlement, the official said, ``It depends on
the Sandinistas'' and whether they were willing to release arrested
demonstrators and lift restrictions on La Prensa and a Roman
Catholic radio station.
   The Reagan administration repeatedly has called on Nicaragua for
political reforms while urging Congress to finance arms and other
support for the Contras who are fighting to bring down the leftist
government.
</TEXT>
