<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0486,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Pledges to Boost Federal Spending on War Against Drugs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with pledge to boost federal drug
enforcement, picks up 4th graf pvs, Standing across ...; deletes
grafs 14-15, 17-19 pvs for length</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, saying the Reagan
administation has short-changed the war on drugs, promised today he
would double the number of federal drug agents and hire more
federal prosecutors.
   ``We are going to give state and local law enforcement officers
the money to fight the war,'' Dukakis said in remarks prepared for
delivery at the Los Angeles Police Academy.
   ``We're not going to try to nickel and dime you to death, as
this administation has done,'' he said.
   Dukakis said that as president he would double the number of
federal Drug Enforcement Administation officials over five years.
   Aides to Dukakis said he was prepared to spend $50 million to
hire 600 new agents next year toward the goal of 2,800 new agents.
   He said he would put 100 of those new agents in southern
California, where he was campaigning today.
   The Dukakis campaign said the candidate was committed to hiring
800 more federal prosecutors to help handle drug cases and other
crimes.
   Dukakis ridiculed remarks by Vice President George Bush two days
ago in San Francisco, quoting Bush as saying he is ``almost
haunted'' by severe drug problems in inner cities.
   Dukakis said, ``American children do not need our pity. They
need strong leaders and first rate law enforcement officers ...
They don't need a change of heart in Washington. They need a change
of leadership.''
   On Thursday, Dukakis traveled to the charred forests of
Yellowstone National Park to show support for firefighters.
   Standing across a river gorge from a blackened hillside, Dukakis
refused to be drawn into the debate in the West over whether the
Reagan administration should have acted sooner. Following National
Park Service policy, the government allowed those fires that were
ignited naturally to burn themselves out until late July.
   ``This isn't the time to discuss what might have been or should
be,'' Dukakis said. ``Everybody agrees that once the fires are out,
it'll be a good time to sit down and think through exactly how we
deal with this problem in the future.''
   The Democratic nominee, putting aside his newly aggressive
demeanor for a moment, sounded nearly as cautious when asked about
Bush's assault on his economic record as governor of Massachusetts
_ an area Dukakis made the centerpiece of his candidacy.
   ``I'll be responding to that sometime next week,'' Dukakis said
at first. ``... Good luck to Mr. Bush.''
   Bush, the Republican nominee, said Dukakis' state led in
spending increases and was second in tax increases under his
administrations and called him ``the gold medal winner in he
tax-and-spend competition.''
   Several minutes later, appearing to reconsider the notion of
allowing Bush's charges to go unanswered, Dukakis delivered a
response without prompting. Arriving in Los Angeles later, he again
volunteered a reaction.
   ``We've balanced 10 budgets in a row, we have a 3 percent
unemployment rate, we have more jobs than people to fill them,
personal income is rising at the second fastest rate in the nation,
and we've cut taxes five times in the last five yearrs,'' he said.
   ``What Mr. Bush has given us is a mountain of debt, record
deficits, and record trade deficts, and an economic future which
does not bode well for the American people.''
   The issue of when to battle forest fires has produced divisions
in the Rocky Mountain states and poses political pitfalls. Interior
Secretary Donald Hodel has suggested the policy may be changed. But
the policy of letting fires burn themselves out unless they
threaten lives or structures has won support from some
environmentalists, who argue that fire is a natural process that
makes way for new growth.
   Dukakis said he wanted to hear more about the issue, but he
recognized that argument.
   Dukakis has campaigned in the Rocky Mountain states and, at the
height of his midsummer popularity, aides were speaking hopefully
of the nominee's chances in those states _ especially Montana. But
as the race has tightened everywhere, the Rocky Mountain states _
which have been reliably Republican in presidential races even
though they elect Democratic state officials _ are looking
increasingly difficult for Dukakis.
</TEXT>
