<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Greenhouse-Hurricanes     09-16 0770</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greenhouse-Hurricanes,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greenhouse Effect May Worsen Hurricanes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricanes of the future may be even more
powerful than any that have come before, as a result of the
so-called greenhouse effect warming of the Earth, a scientist is
warning.
   Kerry A. Emanuel, of the meteorology department at Massachusetts
Institute of Technology, expressed his concern even as Hurricane
Gilbert, perhaps the most powerful tropical storm of the century,
was churning a path of destruction through the Gulf of Mexico.
   Because hurricanes gain their energy from the warm ocean waters
in tropical areas, rising temperatures could increase the strength
of these storms in the future, he explained in a telephone
interview.
   ``Over the warmest parts of the oceans, a change in sea-surface
temperature of 1 degree Celsius (1.6 degrees Fahrenheit) will
change the minimum sustainable pressure in a hurricane by 15 to
20'' millibars, Emanuel reported.
   The pressure in the center of a hurricane is generally
considered a good indication of its strength, with lower pressures
indicating a more powerful storm. Normal sea level pressure is
1,013 millibars, while in a powerful storms like Gilbert readings
can drop into the high 800s.
   Emanuel commented, however, that it's too soon to tell whether
Hurricane Gilbert is a product of the greenhouse warming.
   ``This is kind of an extraordinary hurricane, but I don't think
we can take it as an indication we are seeing any kind of trend,''
he said. ``If the predictions of some climate models come true, and
that's a pretty big if, we can expect to see some more intense
hurricanes in 50 years or so.''
   That means the strong storms of the future would be more
powerful than the strong ones of today, he explained, although
there wouldn't necessarily be more storms.
   There generally seems to be a limit to how low the pressure can
fall in even the strongest storms, explained Emanuel, but warmer
ocean waters could lower that limit. And that, he said, is what
could result in the stronger storms.
   The greenhouse effect has been widely reported in recent years.
Climate experts explain it as the result of increasing carbon
dioxide and other polluting gases in the atmosphere.
   Those gases allow the incoming sunlight to continue to warm the
Earth, but block some outgoing radiation, leading to a gradual
increase in the planet's temperature. It is a situation similar to
that of a greenhouse where heat from the sun is captured to warm
plants.
   Studies by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
concluded that carbon dioxide in the atmosphere has increased by 25
percent since the mid-1800s and continues to grow. Scientists have
estimated that the overall temperature of the Earth has risen by
more than 1 degree Fahrenheit over the same time, and could rise by
another 2 degrees over the next few decades.
   Computerized models, using complex mathematical formulas to
predict the result of such a warming, have warned of a variety of
dire consequences ranging from drought over croplands to melting of
the polar ice caps, raising sea levels and inundating coastal
communities.
   Emanuel is the author of a study, ``Toward a General Theory of
Hurricanes,'' which appears in the July-August edition of American
Scientist.
   In it he noted that while many things about the giant tropical
storms remain a mystery, in recent years scientists have come to a
better understanding of the storms.
   The power for hurricanes, he explained, comes from the transfer
of moisture and energy from the oceans into the overlying air. This
air rises, forming a low pressure area, and wind from surrounding
area begins blowing in a spiral toward that center, bringing in
more moisture from the warm ocean.
   Since the rate of evaporation increases with wind speed, the
faster the wind the more water and energy it can pick up in the
storm.
   The inward-flowing air cannot get to the actual center of the
storm because the laws of physics would cause it to increase its
spin to an infinite velocity, Emanuel explains. Thus, at some
point, the wind stops moving inward and begins to ascend, forming
the well-known cloudy eye-wall of a hurricane.
   Because ocean heat drives these big storms, scientists have
found that among the conditions necessary before a hurricane can
form is an ocean temperature of 26 degrees Celsius _ about 82
degrees Fahrenheit _ and that warm water needs to extend down about
60 meters, or 165 feet.
   In addition, the storms will not form if there are strong cross
winds, which disrupt the rising motion that helps form the center
of the storms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1255EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 4thLd-Writethru a0580 09-16 1077</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0580,1020</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls Dukakis A Campaign Convert on Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 new grafs after pvs 8th graf bgng, Bush said, with
speech at Findlay on patriotism; SUBS pvs 9th graf bgng, Bush told,
to reword for transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush said today that
Democratic rival Michael Dukakis is a campaign convert on defense
issues who is trying to fool American voters _ and Soviet leaders _
by ``riding around in a tank for 10 minutes.''
   Bush said photographs of Dukakis wearing a military helmet and
riding in an M-1 tank at a defense contractor's plant in Michigan
earlier this week were at odds with his record on national defense.
   ``All I can do is cite his position,'' Bush said, declaring that
Dukakis has opposed the railroad-based MX missile, the Midgetman
missile and the B-1 bomber.
   ``Now suddenly he rides around in a tank, jumps out of the tank,
takes off the helmet and comes on with different positions,'' the
GOP nominee said as he toured the Buckeye Steel Co. plant in
Columbus under the silent gaze of steelworkers, some wearing
Dukakis T-shirts.
   Dukakis opposes the MX and Midgetman missile programs and
initially expressed opposition to the B-1 bomber, although he said
later that production of the aircraft should be allowed to proceed.
   Bush said he was encouraged by the reception he received from
the steelworkers at the plant where his grandfather, Samuel
Prescott Bush, was once president. About 150 employees stood
quietly throughout the speech, neither jeering nor applauding.
   ``Admittedly, the applause meter didn't go off the chart,'' Bush
said, ``nor did the boo meter go off the chart. These days we
measure things by both meters.''
   Bush said Dukakis was ``way over in left field'' on some issues
of concern to blue-collar workers. ``These people don't want gun
control. They do favor the death penalty,'' the vice president said.
   In Findlay, Ohio, a city that calls itself ``Flag City U.S.A.,''
Bush declared that ``the flag is back'' and then seemed to stumble
into the Pledge of Allegiance.
   At a flag-draped rally, Bush said, ``What is it all about? It's
the symbol of these United States of America, and to the liberty
for which it stands, one nation under God with freedom and justice
for all. And let's never forget it.''
   Bush told reporters in Columbus that Dukakis is tailoring his
message in an effort gain the support of Democrats voters who
previously had voted for President Reagan.
   ``He's gone to states like this, found that his message of ...
cutting unilaterally on these weapons systems is not popular, and
so now he's been made over,'' Bush said. ``He's coming out with
policies quite different, but which ones do you believe? You
believe this 30-day conversion as you climb out of a tank?''
   The vice president added:
   ``The tanks did not fit. It's time to take another message to
Michael. It's very straightforward. You cannot fool the Soviet
leadership by knocking America's defense for 10 years and riding
around in a tank for 10 minutes. ... You can't fool the American
people.''
   Bush also made an apparent misstatement, saying he stands for
anti-Semitism, when asked about the resignation of six pro-Bush
campaign aides on ethnic groups who allegedly had pro-Nazi or
anti-Semitic ties. He said the aides left voluntarily to avoid
diverting attention from campaign issues.
   ``I hope I stand for anti-bigotry, anti-Semitism, anti-racism,''
Bush said. ``That is what drives me. It's one of the things that I
feel very strongly about.''
   The GOP nominee said in California on Thursday that he hoped
former White House aide Oliver North would be exonerated of all
charges stemming from his role in the Iran-Contra affair.
   But Bush refused to rule out a presidential pardon if North is
found guilty. And today, he ducked a question whether he would
offer North a job in any Bush administration.
   Bush stopped in Columbus on his return to Washington after a
two-day campaign swing through California highlighted by a
statistical assault on Dukakis as an Olympic-class
``tax-and-spend'' governor of Massachusetts.
   Trying to project a disastrous U.S. economy under a Dukakis
administration, Bush said the Massachusetts governor had presided
over a state that lost 26,000 jobs since 1983. The text of the
speech said ``manufacturing jobs,'' but Bush skipped over the word.
   Press Secretary Sheila Tate said the omission was inadvertent.
   Official figures also show that under Dukakis, the state's job
market as a whole has seen a five-year increase of 230,000 jobs to
more than offset the loss of manufacturing jobs.
   On another point, Bush said Massachusetts in the last two years
``has turned a surplus into a growing budget deficit that according
to Massachussetts legislators appears to be approaching $500 to
$700 million for fiscal 1989.''
   In fact, the state has no deficit now, and Tate said the vice
president was only referring to the future projected deficit.
   Massachusetts in fiscal 1988 had a $67 million surplus after
cutting $450 million in spending and dipping into some reserve
accounts. Critics questioned the surplus and said it could only be
the result of tax and fee increases, government borrowing and a
``raid'' on the state pension fund.
   Bush also noted that Dukakis has borrowed about $200 million a
month since June for operations, and Bush called it ``last-ditch
borrowing.''
   But Dukakis says the short-term loans are needed to cover
municipal aid that is now dispensed in a lump sum annually instead
of in periodic installments as was the case before 1986, and that
helps the local municipalities avoid heavy borrowing while waiting
for state aid.
   On taxes, Bush listed Massachusetts as second in the nation in
growth in per capita taxes since 1963.
   That means taxes are higher per person than in any state but
Connecticut. But it is not due to a tax hike by Dukakis, Bush
economics adviser Michael Boskin acknowledged.
   In fact there have been no broad-based tax increases in Dukakis'
two terms that began in 1983.
   Tax revenues went way up due to growth in income and other
economic factors, Boskin said, adding that the Bush criticism is
that Dukakis let the taxes rise without instituting any relief for
taxpayers.
   ``He's allowed them to rise without returning them,'' to
taxpayers or seeking tax limitation measures as other states have
done, said Boskin.
   There have been numerous tax cuts during Dukakis' last two terms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
