<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-Navy Launch,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy To Launch New Ship in New Orleans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy will launch a new amphibious landing
ship during ceremonies in New Orleans this weekend, weather
permitting, the service announced Friday.
   The ceremony for the Tortuga, an LSD-class dock landing ship, is
set to begin at 10 a.m. EDT Saturday at the Avondale Industries'
shipyard in New Orleans. Sen. J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., is
scheduled to deliver the principal speech.
   The Navy said Friday the ceremony might be canceled at the last
moment, however, depending upon the effects of Hurricane Gilbert.
The hurricane was in the Gulf of Mexico and closing on Texas Friday
afternoon.
   The Tortuga is 609 feet long, 84 feet wide and displaces about
15,726 tons when fully loaded. It is capable of carrying four
air-cushion landing craft in its well deck and has a flight deck
for helicopter operations.
   The vessel is the second U.S. Navy ship to be named after a
group of coral islets located off the coast of Key West, Fla.
