<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HollywoodUSO     09-16 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hollywood USO,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hollywood USO to Close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first USO club is moving due to fewer
customers and a less than ``wholesome environment'' for the
military, officials said.
   The Bob Hope USO club, which opened in 1940 and became a spot
where soldiers rubbed elbows with stars, is moving to Long Beach in
December, with a satellite club in Barstow.
   ``That's where the military is,'' Anne Milkes, the
organization's executive director, said Thursday ``We decided to
take Mohammed to the mountain.''
   The Hollywood USO club was a model for the chain of USO clubs
chartered by Congress in 1941 to serve the military overseas.
   At its height, the Hollywood center attracted up to 25,000
servicemen a year, Ms. Milkes said.
   But now most service people in the area are unwilling to make
the trek to Hollywood, where the USO shares a street with a club
featuring nude dancers.
   ``We wanted to provide a wholesome environment for young people
and Hollywood had a lot of problems,'' Ms. Milkes said.
   Its two new locations are accessible to 60,000 military
personnel, she said.
   Not everyone in Long Beach is pleased with the move.
   ``It's going to kill the rest of the businesses downtown,''
complained Marcia Lamb, co-owner of Overreact Gallery, an art
gallery across the street from the new USO site. ``We're trying to
develop a community feeling and a reputation for a certain
consistent type of nighttime entertainment.''
   But Ms. Milkes said such fears are based on outdated perceptions.
   ``Those who object are carrying around an image of drunken
sailors from the past,'' she said.
</TEXT>
