<HEAD>`Friendly' Punch Kills Youth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EUGENE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death of a 16-year-old boy who was
trading punches with a friend has been declared an accident,
authorities said.
   An investigation by the Lane County medical examiner's office
determined that Joseph A. Kight of Creswell died from an injury
after he was struck in the upper abdomen by a teen-age friend.
Police are not releasing the name of the friend because he is a
juvenile.
   Police said the boys were trading punches in a friendly manner
on Aug. 9 when Kight collapsed.
   A blow may have struck nerves and caused a ``lethal'' arrhythmia
of the heart, said medical examiner Dr. Samuel Vickers. He said it
is also possible a blow was struck during a critical time of the
heart's rhythmic cycle.
   Lab samples uncovered no evidence of drugs in the boy's system
and he had no other injuries, officials said.
