<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JarvisOverturned     09-16 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jarvis Overturned,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Appellate Court Overturns Tax-Limiting Proposition 62</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tax-reform group said it will appeal
a court ruling that overturned Proposition 62, the 1986 initiative
that requires local governments to seek voter approval for local
taxes.
   Proposition 62, a fine-tuning of the landmark tax-capping
Proposition 13 that was championed by the late tax reformer Howard
Jarvis, was overturned Thursday by the state's 4th District Court
of Appeal.
   The unanimous decision said requiring voter approval constitutes
a ``gross interference with the fiscal responsiblity of local
governments.''
   ``It's a sad day for the California taxpayer,'' said Joel Fox, a
spokesman for the California Tax Reduction Movement in Los Angeles.
The anti-tax group campaigned for Proposition 62 after Jarvis died
in 1986.
   Fox said his organization would appeal the ruling to the state
Supreme Court. If the high court refuses to hear the case, Fox said
his group would consider another initiative campaign.
   The appellate court reversed a decision in January by a Superior
Court judge, who upheld Proposition 62 against a challenge brought
by the city of Westminster.
   The appellate court ruling said Westminster has authority to
impose a tax on utility users without a citywide vote.
   A similar case is before the state's 1st District Court of
Appeal in San Francisco.
</TEXT>
