<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gilbert-KillerHurricanes     09-16 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gilbert-Killer Hurricanes,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survivors Recall Worse Giants Than Gilbert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane Gilbert Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN PLATERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Bernard Russell followed the destructive path
of Hurricane Gilbert this week, he recalled the 1935 hurricane that
claimed 50 relatives when it blasted the Florida Keys with 200 mph
wind and a 15-foot wall of water.
   ``I've been following this thing and I know the 1935 hurricane
was tougher _ no maybe about that,'' said Russell, who lost his
mother, three sisters, grandparents, aunts, uncles, nephews and
cousins in the Labor Day hurricane, one of only two Category 5
hurricanes to make U.S. landfall since record-keeping began.
   ``When I see the pictures from Jamaica, you can see tall coconut
palm trees still standing. There wasn't one left on my island _
only stumps,'' Russell, 69, said by telephone Thursday from his
daughter's home in Frostproof, Fla.
   Gilbert was a Category 4 storm when it devastated Jamaica this
week, then strengthened to Category 5, which signifies sustained
wind speed greater than 155 mph and interior barometric pressure
less than 27.17 inches and other factors.
   After crossing Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula, Gilbert had declined
to Category 3 on its way to landfall near the Texas-Mexican border
Friday. It had killed more than 50 people.
   Russell, then 17, was in the center of the 1935 hurricane's
14-mile-wide swath that destroyed a railroad, peeled the Matecumbe
Keys down to bare rock and killed 600, 408 in the Keys. The retired
carpenter still lives at Islamorada in Upper Matecumbe.
   Bob Sheets, director of the National Hurricane Center, said
Gilbert at its peak was bigger in size and stronger in barometric
pressure than the one that struck Sept. 2, 1935, although the
earlier one was more powerful when it struck land.
   The other Category 5 hurricane to make U.S. landfall was
Camille, which killed 256 in the Mississippi coastal area in 1969.
   In an interview at the time of the 50-year anniversary of the
Keys hurricane, Russell relived the giant storm that was forecast
to move into the Florida Straits between Key West and Cuba. But
after a morning of sunshine, winds became ferocious and heavy rain
fell.
   What was known then as the U.S. Weather Bureau was unaware the
hurricane had changed course.
   ``At 8 p.m., it got so black you couldn't see your hand in front
of your face,'' Russell said. He and his family sought refuge in a
nearby building.
   ``The building began to shake and muddy water came in under the
door. My father said we'd have to leave the building. He told us to
grab hold of each other and try to hang together.
   ``We opened the back door and became separated. I was holding
onto my sisters and nephews, but we were pulled apart,'' he said.
   Russell grabbed the door frame as the building toppled.
   ``There was debris everywhere. It was a boiling pot. The water
rose quickly and my leg got caught. I stretched my neck and cupped
my hands over my mouth as the water got higher.
   ``I heard a voice in the distance and I kept yelling at the
person to keep yelling. Later, I worked down the pile of trash and
my face pushed into something. It was my father; the voice I heard
in the distance, he had been only an arm's length away.''
   ``One of my cousins was found 40 miles from here,'' recalled
Russell. ``She was still holding her baby in her arms.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
