<HEAD>Former AP Reporter Dies of Heart Failure</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT Kerr's state to Oklahoma</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles C. Haslet, 85, a regional reporter for
The Associated Press in Washington from 1937 to 1967, died Thursday
of heart failure.
   Haslet, who covered stories of interest to the states of
Oklahoma, Kansas and Missouri, died at the Hermitage Methodist
Retirement Home in nearby Alexandria, Va., where he had lived for
the past five years.
   A native of Wellington, Kan., Haslet began his journalism career
on the Wellington Daily News in 1922. He joined the AP in Chicago
in 1924 and later served in the Tulsa and Kansas City bureaus
before moving to Washington.
   During his years as a regional reporter Haslet became close to
the political leaders of the time, including former House speaker
Carl Albert of Oklahoma, Oklahoma governor and senator Robert Kerr,
and current Senate minority leader Robert Dole.
   A memorial service will be held at the Hermitage Methodist
Retirement Home at 1:30 p.m. Monday, followed by private burial
services.
   Haslet is survived by a son Charles C. Haslet Jr. of Herndon,
Va., four grandchildren, and three sisters, Mrs Louise Newberry of
Wellington, Kan., Mrs. Lola McGuire of Wichita, Kas., and Mrs.
Edith Fisher of Santa Rosa, Calif.
</TEXT>
