<HEAD>NBC Executive's Death Was Possible Drug Overdose, Police Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocaine and paraphernalia used to sniff
the drug were found near the corpse of an NBC executive, leading
detectives to suspect the drug contributed to his death, police say.
   Jay Michelis, 50, was found dead Sept. 10 in his bedroom by a
servant. Nearby was a mirror covered with white powder and a $1
bill rolled up in the manner commonly used to snort cocaine, police
Lt. Greg Henderson said Thursday.
   A packet of the drug also was found in a wooden box in the room,
he said.
   A preliminary coroner's report attributed the death to heart
attack, said coroner's spokeswoman Pat Smith, adding that test
results wouldn't be available for at least a week.
   ``The reason for the decision is that he had bad coronary artery
disease with a fresh blood clot,'' Ms. Smith said. ``This is what
killed him.''
   The 30-year NBC veteran was West Coast vice president for
corporate and media relations.
