<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1457EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeachWaste     09-16 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Waste,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Needles Wash Up on Florida Beach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARINELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two thousand unused hypodermic needles
have been found along a 10-mile stretch of beach in northern
Florida, the latest case of medical debris washing up on the
state's shoreline.
   For the last two months, wastes such as specimen tubes, drug
vials and microscope slides have turned up on beaches between
Pompano Beach and Fort Lauderdale, in southern Florida, and in the
Panhandle area.
   On Thursday, the needles, still in their plastic cases, were
discovered on beaches around Marineland, 20 miles south of St.
Augustine. The needles were the sort used for drawing blood samples
for laboratory tests.
   Flagler County officials collected the needles to keep
beachcombers or bathers from stepping on them.
   ``I don't think there's any possibility of anyone having to
worry about contamination,'' said Nick Chapman, Flagler County
Health Department administrator. ``It's no different than stepping
on a piece of glass.''
   No one knows where the needles came from. Chapman said they
might have been dumped from a ship.
   Many of the needles were on Marineland beaches, but some also
were found up to 10 miles south in Beverly Beach, said Sgt. Steve
Drenning of the Flagler County Sheriff's Department.
   The medical waste problem this summer has not been limited to
Florida. Beaches in the New York area were temporarily closed after
medical refuse, mostly syringes and vials, began coming ashore
shortly after July 4.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1458EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Brown     09-16 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Brown,0156</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ellington Trombonist Dead At 81</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trombonist Lawrence Brown, who played for
decades with the Duke Ellington Orchestra after a stint with Louis
Armstrong, has died at home, his brother said. He was 81.
   Brown died Sept. 5 after suffering a stroke, said his brother,
Harold Brown.
   Brown was raised in Pasadena and studied piano, violin, tuba and
alto saxophone in addition to the trombone.
   He joined Armstrong in 1931 and Ellington the following year. He
left Ellington's orchestra in 1951 to tour with fellow Ellington
alumnus Johnny Hodges, then moved on to free-lance in New York
before rejoining Ellington in 1960.
   He recorded with Ellington, Hodges, Jimmy Rushing, Ruby Braff,
the Metronome All Stars, Lionel Hampton, Buck Clayton and others.
Brown returned to California in 1972 to to work for the Hollywood
local of the American Federation of Musicians and retired a few
years later.
</TEXT>
