<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Condom Law,0145</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City Law Says Only Pharmacists, Doctors Can Dispense Condoms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone who wants to buy a condom in the
city limits had better see a doctor, a pharmacist or a patent
medicine store, according to a municipal ordinance that just about
everyone agrees can't be enforced.
   The 1953 law limits the places that can sell contraceptives. It
also prohibits the display or advertising of contraceptives or
``sex-inciting devices,'' apparently meaning that Marshall
University officials became lawbreakers when they began selling
condoms from vending machines three weeks ago.
   ``Obviously, if we had known about it, we would have checked it
out and confronted the issue,'' said Ray Welty, the Marshall
administrator in charge of vending.
   City attorney Charles F. Dodrill said Thursday the law can't be
enforced because the U.S. Supreme Court voided similar laws as
unconstitutional.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
