<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ethiopia-Crash     09-16 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethiopia-Crash,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Down In Ethiopia, 31 Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state-owned jetliner carrying 104
people ran into a flock of birds, crashed and burst into flames
shortly after takeoff, killing at least 31 people, the airline and
sources said Friday.
   Thirty more people were injured and two people were missing in
the accident Thursday near Bahar Dar, close to the source of the
Blue Nile on Lake Tana's southern shore in Gojam province in the
northwest.
   The Ethiopian Airlines Boeing 737, which originated in Addis
Ababa, was on a scheduled domestic flight when a flock of birds was
sucked into both engines after it took off from Bahar Dar airport,
the airline said in a statement.
   The pilot tried to turn the plane back to Bahar Dar, but failed
and crashed into marshy ground 14 miles south of the airport. The
plane skidded on its belly for about 500 yards before the fusilage
broke into two, the airline said. Sources said the craft
immediately burst into flames.
   Seventy-one people escaped from the burning wreckage, 12 of them
seriously injured and 18 with minor injuries, the airline and the
sources said.
   The seriously injured were rushed to a hospital in Bahar Dar
while those with minor injuries were flown to Addis Ababa for
treatment Friday, sources said.
   It was the first statement to confirm fatalities in the crash
and the only official word since the Marxist government announced
the accident Thursday evening and said ``the majority'' of the
people on board the plane were safe.
   The airline did not issue a list of passengers or their
nationalities, but it was believed most of the people on the plane
were Ethiopian.
   The flight was on a scheduled run from Addis Ababa to Bahar Dar
to Asmara, the capital of northern Eritrea province. A civil
aviation official said birds have long been a problem at the Bahar
Dar airport.
   Bahar Dar is 200 miles northwest of Addis Ababa and 280 miles
southwest of Asmara. It sits on the southern shores of Lake Tana,
the source of the Blue Nile. The Blue Nile courses west out of the
Ethiopian highlands into Sudan, where it joins the White Nile at
Khartoum and continues on to the Mediterranean as the Nile River.
</TEXT>
