<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Deaver     09-16 0739</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaver,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Says Deaver Suffered Memory Impairment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A doctor who treated Michael K. Deaver for
alcoholism testified Friday that the former presidential aide
suffered memory impairment when he took tranquilizers during
hospital treatment for the disease.
   Dr. William E. Flynn said the combination of alcohol withdrawal
and heavy doses of the tranqilizer Valium impaired Deaver's
judgment and memory during a 1985 hospital stay.
   ``He wasn't really processing or dealing with things in an
appropriate manner,'' said Flynn, head of the alcoholism clinic at
Georgetown University Hospital. Flynn testified at a court hearing
on Deaver's medical condition.
   Defense lawyers are trying to convince U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson that Deaver's alcoholism is a mitigating
factor that should be taken into consideration when Deaver is
sentenced next week for three perjury convictions.
   The former White House deputy chief of staff was convicted last
December of three counts of lying to a federal grand jury and a
House subcommittee by saying he couldn't recall contacting
government officials on behalf of high-paying lobbying clients.
   Deaver, 50, faces a possible five-year prison term and a $6,800
fine for each of the three convictions. Sentencing is scheduled for
Sept. 23.
   The defense contends Deaver wasn't lying in 1986 when he
testified he couldn't recall telephoning then-Transportation
Secretary Elizabeth Dole from his hospital bed on June 3, 1985, on
behalf of Trans World Airlines.
   Flynn, who also treated Deaver for alcoholism in October 1986,
testified that the former presidential aide had reduced mental
functions during the detoxification treatments.
   ``Do you believe under the circumstances that his judgment was
impaired in any way?'' defense lawyer Randall J. Turk asked Flynn.
   ``I would say definitely,'' Flynn said.
   ``And his memory?'' Turk continued.
   ``Definitely,'' the doctor replied.
   Later, Flynn said he noted impairment of Deaver's ``memory of
the kinds of things that were happening to him'' during the
three-day hospital stay.
   But the doctor also said that throughout the visit, Deaver
``remained quite alert and never showed any signs of depression or
any signs of heavy sedation'' while he took large doses of Valium.
   Deaver has remained sober since undergoing a month-long
treatment in 1986 at a clinic.
   The medical testimony was not offered during Deaver's trial
because the defense rested without calling any witnesses.
   The presentation during a two-day hearing that began Thursday
appeared to be as much an attempt to put Deaver's defense on the
record for an appellate court as it is to persuade Jackson to
impose a lenient sentence.
   The defense is expected to argue on appeal that rulings Jackson
made during the trial last year made it impossible for Deaver to
put on a defense.
   During the trial, Jackson refused to strike from the indictment
certain allegations of perjury left unproven at the close of the
prosecution's case.
   Jackson ruled that he would keep these elements of the case
intact until after the close of the defense case, giving the
prosecution an opportunity to prove those points when questioning
Deaver or other defense witnesses.
   The defense then rested without calling any witnesses, including
Deaver or medical experts who could testify about how alcohol
impaired his memory.
   Independent counsel Whitney North Seymour Jr. argued Thursday
that the medical records would show no evidence of a memory loss.
Seymour contended that Deaver chose to remember some things and
forget others when he testified under oath in 1986 during the
investigations of his lobbying for possible ethics-law violations.
   Flynn testified that Deaver insisted on checking out of the
hospital after his first visit sooner than doctors thought
advisable and refused to enter a treatment program.
   ``He was adamant he didn't need further treatment. He would
handle this himself,'' Flynn said. At this point Deaver had not
really faced up to the fact that he was an alcoholic, even though
Flynn said he thought the former presidential aide had been
drinking heavily for several years.
   ``He was the kind of alcoholic who had been very successful at
hiding from a large number of people his alcoholism,'' Flynn said.
Deaver's family was not told of his problem until shortly before
his first hospitalization.
   When he returned for treatment in October 1986, Deaver again
resisted going into a clinic, Flynn said.
   But after some encouragement by his family and advice from his
lawyers, Deaver agreed to enter an alcoholism rehabilitation center
in Havre de Grace, Md., Flynn said.
</TEXT>
