<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Bukharin     09-16 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Bukharin,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rehabilitated Bolshevik's Works To Be Published</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party has published a collection of
works by Nikolai I. Bukharin, a Bolshevik leader who was shot under
dictator Josef Stalin, in another step toward his rehabilitation,
Tass reported today.
   The book, prepared by the Institute of Marxism-Leninism of the
party's Central Committee, coincides with the centennial of
Bukharin's birth.
   The collection includes articles and comments on communist
theory and party politics, economic policy and culture, the
official news agency said.
   Bukharin was a ``distinguished social scientist whose name and
writings have for long been unfairly buried in oblivion,'' Tass
said.
   In February, Bukharin was cleared of spying charges for which he
was shot in 1938. The party readmitted him posthumously in July.
   The rehabilitation was part of a review launched by Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev of party officials killed or arrested
by Stalin.
   Bukharin, an economist, favored moderate economic policies that
are similar to those being implemented under Gorbachev's program of
perestroika, or restructuring.
   In recent months, the Soviet press has published several
articles on Bukharin. The newspaper Sovietskaya Kultura on Tuesday
reported a lecture he delivered in Paris two years before he was
shot.
