<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarkHofmann     09-16 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mark Hofmann,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hofmann's Condition Upgraded; Investigators Wait To Ask Questions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MIMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of admitted pipe bomb killer
and forger Mark Hofmann was upgraded Friday from critical to
serious and stable following a prison drug overdose, but police
still could not interview him.
   ``He has improved considerably overnight. His pulse, blood
pressure and heart rate are all stable,'' said University of Utah
Health Sciences Center spokesman John Dwan. ``He's waking up,
coming out of the coma. He is only able to whisper at this time,
but he appears to be oriented, and he's following medical
instructions.''
   Officers were called to Hofmann's cell Thursday by his cellmate,
who could not wake him up for lunch. Hofmann initially was reported
in critical and unstable condition following what Dwan said was an
overdose of an undetermined anti-depressant drug.
   Hofmann was sentenced to five years to life after pleading
guilty in January 1987 to having planted pipe bombs that killed
Steven Christensen, a documents collector, and Kathleen Sheets,
wife of Christensen associate Gary Sheets, on Oct. 15, 1985. At a
January hearing, the state Board of Pardons told him he would spend
the rest of his life in prison.
   Hofmann, 33, confessed that he killed Christensen and Sheets to
cover up his career as a forger of historical documents, many of
which he sold to the Mormon Church.
   Dwan said Hofmann was gradually regaining consciousness Friday
and was taken off a respirator, but was in no condition to be
interrogated.
   ``He's still not lucid,'' Dwan said. ``Our medical personnel
have had to sedate him twice for medical purposes.''
   Armed corrections officers, supplemented by hospital security
and university police, guarded the door to Hofmann's room and
entrances to the intensive-care unit.
   Corrections spokesman Juan Benavidez said prison officials were
concerned the overdose might have been a prelude to an escape
attempt, although investigators had no hard evidence of that.
   Dwan said the security was for Hofmann's safety, too.
   ``We've received a couple calls here already from people saying
`Why don't you just let him die,' and so forth,'' he said.
``They're here to make sure he doesn't escape, but also that no one
bothers him.''
   Hofmann's wife, Doralee, recently filed for divorce and Hofmann
signed a consent form about five week ago. He spoke with her and
his children by telephone Wednesday but gave no indication anything
was amiss, prison officials said.
   He had been on administrative lockdown, confined to his cell 23
hours a day, since a purported Hofmann plot against Pardons Board
members was uncovered. His attorney, Ronald Yengich, has denied
such a plot existed.
</TEXT>
