<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSPolicies     09-16 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Policies,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Leaders Criticize Administration's Lack of AIDS
Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is to blame for a lack of
coordinated leadership in the nation's fight against the AIDS
epidemic, several business leaders said Friday at a conference on
the deadly disease.
   ``The simple truth is that the President has a moral and
probably constitutional imperative to trigger America's best
defense from this plague. He has failed,'' said Stephen E. Herbits,
executive vice president of corporate development for Joseph E.
Seagram & Sons Inc.
   Individual government agencies, such as the federal Centers for
Disease Control, have made great strides against AIDS, said Dr.
Theodore Cooper, chief executive officer of Upjohn Co., a
pharmaceutical manufacturer.
   But ``there is no leadership thrust in the government as a
whole'' to coordinate AIDS research developments and public policy
proposals, said Cooper, who chaired the national Institute of
Medicine AIDS Oversight Committee.
   Leslye Arsht, the White House public information officer
assigned to answer AIDS policy questions, was in a meeting Friday
afternoon and not immediately available for comment, a receptionist
said.
   Cooper called on the Reagan administration to recreate a central
presidential commission on AIDS to coordinate policy and research.
   Herbits and Cooper were among more than a dozen leaders from
business, labor and government who spoke at the conference
sponsored by the National Leadership Coalition on AIDS, based in
Washington.
   The conference was aimed at spurring greater corporate
leadership in the national war on AIDS, or acquired immune
deficiency syndrome, a fatal, incurable disease that destroys the
body's ability to fight sickness.
   ``The absence of our leadership will convince other community
leaders that this is not really an important problem,'' Cooper said.
   Herbits, who was a special assistant in the White House and
Defense Department before joining Seagrams in 1977, said Reagan
failed to make AIDS a top priority.
   ``In seven State of the Union speeches, Mr. Reagan stood before
our nation and never even mentioned that AIDS exists,'' Herbits
said in a speech prepared for the conference. ``Each year until
this, Congress doubled the Reagan administration's request for
funds dedicated to the fight on AIDS.
   ``Yet, the administration still underspent its appropriation,''
he said. ``The administration is still taking too long to approve
drugs for experimental therapies and still delays approval of
contracts to search for appropiate therapies for those who already
have the virus.''
   As of this week, 72,766 AIDS cases have been reported to the
CDC; 41,064 people, or 56 percent, are dead.
   While AIDS still primarily afflicts homosexuals and intravenous
drug users, a CDC official estimates that 5 percent of the cases
were spread by heterosexual contact.
</TEXT>
