<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike, Demonstration Reported in Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schools and factories closed Friday as thousands
of Armenians staged a strike to renew their call for annexation of
a disputed region in neighboring Azerbaijan, an activist said.
   Hovik Vassilyan said 150,000 people demonstrated on a main
square in the Armenian capital to support a work stoppage that
started Monday in Nagorno-Karabakh, the disputed region in
Azerbaijan.
   The strike in Nagorno-Karabakh, populated mostly by Armenians,
is scheduled to end Sunday, Vassilyan said.
   ``People are everywhere,'' said Vassilyan, a former political
prisoner and the editor of an unsanctioned Armenian nationalist
journal. He spoke by telephone from Yerevan.
   The Armenians are demanding that Nagorno-Karabakh be removed
from the control of Azerbaijan and become part of the Armenian
republic. The region has been part of Azerbaijan since 1923.
   Armenians, who are predominantly Christian, claim economic,
cultural and religious discrimination under the rule of
Azerbaijanis, most of whom are Moslem.
   In July, central authorities in Moscow rejected the demand to
turn Nagorno-Karabakh over to Armenia and instead mandated economic
and social improvements to the region.
   Armenians first started agitating for control over
Nagorno-Karabakh in February with street demonstrations and
strikes. At least 32 people were killed in rioting related to the
dispute in the Azerbaijani city of Sumgait.
