<2ND_LINE>AM-Pedestrians Struck,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>4 Pedestrians Struck By Police Cruiser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police cruiser responding to a call struck
four pedestrians on Friday, the second time this week that people
were hit by a police car.
   Jenny Romeo, 74, of Brooklyn, was in critical condition at Kings
County Hospital, with a fractured pelvis and a fracture to the
right side of her neck, hospital spokeswoman Leah Johnson said.
   Milton Ralichstien, 71, of Manhattan, was in stable condition
with bruises from his knees to his feet on both legs, Ms. Johnson
said. The others were treated and released, she said.
   The two police officers in the cruiser were treated for trauma
at Long Island College Hospital. They were identified by police as
Brian O'Malley, 27, the driver, and Roger Smith, 34.
   Friday's incident occurred shortly after 8:30 a.m., when the
cruiser, which had been parked in Brooklyn, received a call of a
man with a gun nearby.
   As the officers were driving to investigate, O'Malley's foot
slipped from the brake, onto the accelerator and then became wedged
between the pedals, according to police spokesman Officer Louis
Llanes.
   The car accelerated and struck the pedestrians as they crossed a
street, Llanes said. O'Malley stopped the car using his left foot
on the brake pedal, the spokesman said.
   On Sunday, a cruiser struck two girls during a 68-block chase
that began when the officers tried to stop car for a traffic
violation. One suffered a head injury, and the other suffered two
broken legs.
