<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Panama     09-16 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Says Cutback In Panama Will Not Hurt Anti-Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Friday reducing the U.S.
diplomatic presence in Panama would not harm efforts to stem the
flow of drugs into the United States.
   ``We're concerned right now about some of our people there and I
think that this is just a measure we're taking and probably
temporary,'' Reagan said.
   About half of the 160 diplomatic posts in Panama, including some
at the regional Drug Enforcement Administration, are to be vacated,
a State Department official said.
   The Reagan administration last May suspended virtually all
diplomatic contact with Panama. This has left many U.S. diplomats
in the country with little to do.
   Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said ``there
have been some threats against mission personnel'' and that the
administration wanted to reduce their ``vulnerabilities.''
   The cutback was recommended by Ambassador Arthur Davis and has
been under way since last spring. Redman said it would be completed
unless Secretary of State George P. Shultz received ``appeals''
from other agencies and decided in their favor.
   Other offices that may be closed or severely reduced are the
Justice Department and the U.S. Customs Service.
   Reagan was asked if the cutback would hamper anti-drug efforts
while he was having his photograph taken with NATO Secretary
General Manfred Woerner in the Oval Office.
   ``No, I don't think we're doing anything to reduce our ability
to interdict drugs,'' Reagan replied.
   Three State Department officials stressed, meanwhile, there
would be no reduction in the U.S. Southern Command or in the Panama
Canal Commission,
   ``We're doing it because the lessons of history have taught us
that when we are in a potentially confrontational situation, it
makes sense to reduce potential vulnerability,'' one of the
officials said Thursday night.
   After all, he said, the United States was trying to get rid of
the head of Panama's armed forces, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Noriega, the effective leader of Panama, has been indicted on
drug trafficking charges by federal grand juries in Florida. He has
successfully countered all U.S. efforts to drive him out.
   These included cancellation of all normal dealings with the
country. The prohibition is so extensive American diplomats are
even forbidden to apply for a renewal of their automobile license
plates.
   Despite persistent reports that Noriega was on the ropes, the
general has held on while Eric Arturo Delvalle, who had U.S.
backing to succeed Noriega, was ousted in February by the
pro-Noriega National Assembly.
   Administration sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said some of the extra U.S. security personnel sent to Panama last
spring by the Pentagon would be withdrawn gradually.
   According to an official of the Southern Command, 240 cases of
harassment of U.S. servicemen were reported between February and
August.
   The command has about 10,000 American servicemen stationed in
Panama permanently and a like number of military dependents.
   Referring to the diplomats, Redman said ``we are reducing the
vulnerabilities inherent in having a large number of United States
government personnel living and working in areas dominated by the
Noriega regime.''
</TEXT>
