<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-MailStrike     09-16 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Mail Strike,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service Returns To Near Normal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of Britain's postal workers were back on
their jobs Friday sorting a backlog of 150 million pieces of mail
that piled up during a two-week nationwide strike, officials said.
   All but 20,000 of the Post Office's 180,000 employees returned
to work after the strike, which was settled Monday, officials said.
   Most postal employees in Glasgow and in London _ the two cities
that process one-third of British mail _ returned to work late
Thursday.
   Mail was loaded on trains across the country, said Nigel Fitt, a
Post Office spokesman. But he said it will take two weeks to clear
the backlog.
   Fitt said 69 of the country's 82 major sorting offices were
operating Friday, and international mail service also was to resume.
   Members of the Union of Communication Workers staged a 24-hour
walkout on Aug. 31 to protest regional pay bonuses, then stayed off
the job to protest the hiring of temporary workers to handle the
one-day backlog.
   An agreement reached Monday night resolved the bonus issue, but
negotiations at local levels were set up to determine whether
temporary workers would be allowed to sort the mail built up.
   The regional pay dispute concerned bonuses the post office
wanted to pay to new workers in southeast England and in London,
where a high cost of living makes recruitment difficult. The union
said it wanted the bonuses paid nationally or not at all.
</TEXT>
