<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-WarGame 2ndLd-Writethru   09-16 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-War Game, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0654,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sharon Calls For War Game To Test Labor's Peace Theories</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 14th graf, `Uri Dan...' to CORRECT that Dan is aide, not
spokesman.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ariel Sharon of the right-wing Likud bloc has
proposed a ``war game'' to test the rival Labor Party's claim that
Israel could surrender some of the occupied West Bank without
undermining its security.
   The former defense minister issued the challenge in a letter
Thursday to the pro-Labor Council for Peace and Security. His
office released the letter Friday.
   The council, a group of retired military officers, contends
Israel's defense would be enhanced, not compromised, if it
surrendered occupied land in exchange for peace with the Arabs.
   As defense minister, Sharon was the architect of Israel's
much-criticized 1982 invasion of Lebanon, aimed at ending
cross-border attacks from the Arab state.
   In the letter, Sharon proposed a public debate followed by ``a
war game in which we will test, again in public, the different
military strategic concepts concerning the defense of Israel.''
   Sharon, now Israel's commerce minister and a high-ranking member
of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc, called for the
confrontations before the national elections Nov. 1. ``The public
should see for itself and make its own judgment,'' he said.
   National security and the future of the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip have become central issues in the election campaign.
   The executive committee of the Council for Peace and Security
met Friday to consider Sharon's proposal and will respond in the
next several days, said Moshe Amirav, secretary of the group.
   A Sharon aide said that before the war game, research institutes
would be asked to define Arab positions and strengths. Sharon's
team then would ``defend'' Israel from within current boundaries,
including the occupied territories, while the council would have to
``defend'' from a more limited land area.
   The Likud has consistently opposed any land-for-peace plans and
has stressed keeping the territories to strengthen security against
invasion from neighboring Arab states. The leftist Labor Party, led
by Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, has favored compromise.
   Israel has occupied the West Bank and Gaza Strip since the 1967
Middle East war. Palestinians launched an uprising in the
territories Dec. 8 to try to end Israeli rule. Since then more than
260 Palestinians have died, mostly in clashes with Israeli security
forces. Six Israelis also have died.
   Israel Gat, international secretary of the Labor Party, accused
Sharon of preposing ``a David and Goliath show for media purposes.''
   He said if the debate and war game were held, ``Mr. Sharon would
come out empty because his solutions are not well based.''
   Uri Dan, a Sharon aide, said the minister would probably lead
his own team in any debate and mock battles. Dan said Sharon, a
retired major general, sees such activities as a way to take
politics out of the issues.
   Another possible contender in the proposed games would be the
Officers and Academics for Security and Peace, a group of pro-Likud
retired officers organized to counter the activities of the Council
for Peace and Security.
   But Yehoshua Saguy, a founding member of the pro-Likud group,
was cool to the idea of a war game.
   ``A game is a game is a game,'' Saguy said. ``Other elements are
important, such as how to measure the possibilities of coming to
compromise with Jordan or the Palestinians and strategic
questions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
