<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabySwap     09-16 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Swap,0587</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says It Has Located Girl Who May Be Natural Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper has located a girl who
may be the daughter of a couple suing a hospital for $100 million
because, they claim, their healthy newborn was swapped for a sickly
infant 9{ years ago.
   Reporters, using public records, found the blue-eyed girl in the
southwest Florida city where she lives with her father, the St.
Petersburg Times said Friday. She is the only other white girl
reported born at tiny Hardee Memorial Hospital at the time the
plaintiff gave birth, the Times said.
   To protect the child, the paper did not identify her.
   Regina and Ernest Twigg sued in federal court in Tampa last
week, accusing three doctors and a nurse at the Wauchula hospital
of keeping their biological child, a healthy baby born Dec. 2,
1978. The suit contends the Twiggs were instead given a sickly
infant.
   That child, Arlena, died Aug. 23 after a long battle with a
heart problem.
   The Twiggs say blood tests performed at Johns Hopkins Hospital
in Baltimore shortly before Arlena's death prove that the child
they raised was not their biological daughter. They claim personnel
at Hardee Memorial swapped infants in order to give away or sell
the real baby Twigg and then altered the hospital's records to hide
their actions.
   Marvin Ellin, attorney for the Twiggs, said he hopes to locate
the girl found by the newspaper and determine if her blood matches
the Twiggs' O-type blood.
   ``If she's O-positive and shows any family resemblance to the
Twiggs, it's going to be incredible,'' he said.
   ``We would like for the child to know that we in fact did not
give her away,'' Twigg said. ``We would want her to know that we
would like to have her. But if she is happy ... we may feel
differently about it.''
   The girl's family dismisses the idea that she could be the
Twiggs' biological daughter.
   ``My sympathy goes out to those people,'' the girl's father told
the Times. ``They have every right to pursue their real child. (My
daughter) is not their child ... she will never be their child.''
   The Times did not indicate whether the girl was adopted or if
the man's late wife had given birth at Hardee Memorial.
   The man told the newspaper he knew nothing of any baby swap. He
would not disclose his daughter's blood type and said he would
resist attempts to draw the girl into the Twiggs' battle. The girl
knows nothing of the search.
   ``Until they get an indictment or a conviction ... I have
nothing to say,'' he said. ``I'm an innocent bystander.''
   Besides Mrs. Twigg, records show only one other white woman gave
birth to a girl during the two weeks before Mrs. Twigg's discharge
from Hardee Memorial, according to Oliver Boorde, state registrar
for vital statistics.
   The legal mother of that girl died in March 1981 when the child
was 2. Two months after the woman's death, her husband married a
worker he met in the hospital where his wife had been treated. That
marriage ended in divorce last December.
   The girl was immature for her age and had troubles in school,
but was loving, the ex-wife told the Times. ``She lost a mother and
she knew me as a mother for seven years and then lost me. What's
next?'' the woman said.
</TEXT>
