<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Reporters     09-16 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Reporters,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Foreign Reporters Kicked From Chinese Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two British reporters said Friday that Chinese
police in a northwestern province punched them and struck them with
electric cattle prods before they expelled them from the region.
   Timothy Luard of the British Broadcasting Corp. and Andrew
Higgins of The Independent, both based in Beijing, said police
detained them Monday when they arrived at the airport in Kashgar.
   The city is in far northwestern China's Xinjiang province.
Rumors have been circulating in recent weeks in Beijing about
ethnic unrest in the region, home to a Turkish minority.
   Police accused the journalists of failing to get permission to
visit the region, Luard said after arriving in Beijing Friday. He
and Higgins denied the charge.
   Police confiscated their passports and film and struck them on
two occasions before putting them on a plane out of Kashar on
Thursday morning, Luard said.
   He said the chief of the Kashgar police Foreign Affairs Section
threw him against a wall and punched him in the chest when the two
reporters objected to efforts by police to mount a 24-hour watch
inside the room where they were held.
   He said another police officer dragged Higgins into the room,
ripping his trousers.
   On Tuesday, police struck the pair with electric cattle prods
when they tried to walk down a street away from the building where
they were kept, Luard said. Police also hit several foreign
tourists who tried to intervene, he said.
   The government did not immediately comment on the journalists'
charges.
   Luard said he and Higgins had applied to Xinjiang authorities
the required 10 days in advance for permission to visit the region.
   He said authorities in Xinjiang's capital of Urumchi, where they
conducted interviews, knew of their plans to go on to Kashgar and
did not object.
   China's domestic media is state-run and the government maintains
tight control over the movements of foreign journalists. In June,
police in a village near Beijing threw out two reporters working
for the British news agency Reuters who tried to cover a peasant
protest against water pollution in their area.
   In the past two years, China has expelled three foreign
reporters from the country.
</TEXT>
