<1ST_LINE>r w AM-POW-MIARecognition 1stLd-Writethru a0660d. 09-16 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-POW-MIA Recognition, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Government Agrees To Joint Search Effort</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Top 9 grafs new to UPDATE with further information on
investigation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vietnamese government has agreed to a
joint effort to find the remains of U.S. servicemen missing in
action during the Vietnam War, the administration announced Friday.
   U.S. officials said the investigation will focus on seven cases
in which there is evidence that the victims were alive at the time
they came under Vietnamese custody.
   At the State Department, spokesman Charles Redman said the seven
are part of the 70 ``most compelling cases'' which U.S. officials
raised with Vietnamese authorities last year.
   Other officials said that that although the 70 were presumed to
be alive when captured, all have long since been presumed dead
because there is no evidence to prove otherwise.
   A 90-day period, beginning Sept. 1, was set aside for carrying
out the investigations, Redman said, with each one limited to 10
days.
   About 2,400 U.S. servicemen have been listed as missing in
action in Southeast Asia.
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci announced the agreement with
Vietnam during a POW-MIA Recognition Day ceremony on Capitol Hill.
   House Republican Leader Robert Michel of Illinois urged the
families of the missing Americans to ignore the rumors that will be
inevitable during the pending search.
   ``We have to continue to press for an accounting of each and
every one, even though the prospects of finding anyone alive
diminish with the passing of time,'' Michel told the crowd of
several hundred.
   ``We must continue to seek the truth,'' he said. ``But the two
greatest enemies of truth are rumors and false hopes. Nothing could
be more cruel to the families of MIAs and POWs than to lend
credence to false rumors, to raise hopes without the facts to
support them, to muddy the waters and confuse the issue.''
   Carlucci said he was encouraged by recent agreements between
Vietnamese Vice Premier Nguyen Co Thach and President Reagan's
special POW-MIA emissary to Hanoi, Gen. John W. Vessey Jr.
   ``Although last month Vietnam temporarily suspended its offer to
conduct joint operations, it recently agreed to resume cooperation,
and I am pleased to announce that joint activity will begin on
Sept. 25,'' the secretary said.
   Laos has agreed to similar efforts, ``but we still await the
results that we know are possible from those who hold the
answers,'' he said.
   Carlucci called on Cambodia to repatriate remains it claims to
hold and criticized the government of North Korea for failure to
return those of United Nations forces missing in the Korean War.
   ``The North Koreans have a golden opportunity this year to
display their willingness to rejoin the real world by dealing in
good faith through the proper channels on this vital human issue,''
said Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, who joined
Carlucci and Michel in addressing the crowd.
   ``Let's hope that when we meet again next year, we can report
real progress and real results,'' Dole said. ``The bottom line is:
We'll never forget, and we'll never give up.''
   As part of the day of remembrance, wreath-laying ceremonies were
being held at the Arlington National Cemetery in honor of POWs and
MIAs from the Korean War.
   An organization dedicated to remembering the families of missing
soldiers, No Greater Love, estimates that there are 8,100 MIAs and
389 POWs still unaccounted for in Korea.
   An estimated 79,000 U.S. servicemen were missing in action in
World War II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
