<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 2100EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WyethTour     09-16 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wyeth Tour,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Generations Of Wyeth Family Art Comes Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE RULE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHADDS FORD, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exhibit of three generations of Wyeth
family art was staged in palaces and ultramodern museums during its
world tour, but James Wyeth says the works look best hanging in his
hometown.
   The exhibition of 115 works by N.C. Wyeth, his son Andrew and
his grandson James opens Sunday in Brandywine River Museum in
Chadds Ford. It is the final stop of a 1{-year tour that also
included stops in the Soviet Union, Italy, Japan and England.
   James until recently has answered to the family nickname of
Jamie. But he now wants to be known as James.
   Speaking at a press preview Friday, he said, ``I've seen the
paintings hanging in a czarist building in Moscow ... in a
ultramodern museum in Tokyo ... in an old-style building in
Cambridge (England), but it still looks a hell of a lot better here
at home.''
   Chadds Ford, southwest of Philadelphia, is where N.C. Wyeth
settled after traveling through the Old West during the late 1800s
and early 1900s. Andrew and James were raised here, and many of
their works explore the people and surroundings.
   Other works examine the people and atmosphere of Maine, where
the family has a second home.
   The most celebrated Wyeth, 71-year-old Andrew, was scheduled to
attend the press preview, but a touch of the flu and a ``drained''
feeling he gets when he completes a work caused him to stay away
Friday, his son said.
   Through the worldwide tour, people flocked to the exhibit in
record-breaking numbers to get a glimpse of art that explores such
American traditions and lifestyles as farming and Halloween.
   But the collection also shows the enduring tradition of an
artistic family, and James Wyeth said that is what appealed most to
the exhibit's audiences abroad.
   ``It was the continuity that really struck them,'' he said.
   The exhibit opened in Leningrad in March 1987 and was the first
exhibit under the newest cultural exchange program between the
United States and the Soviet Union.
   ``The people were really dying to see the art,'' he said. ``At
some openings, people just stand around with their backs to the
paintings, but there they were almost pushing me aside to see the
paintings.''
   Included in the exhibit are three of Andrew Wyeth famous
``Helga'' paintings, a series of nudes and other figure studies of
the same woman that caused a sensation when its existence was
disclosed two years ago.
   When asked if he had any secret paintings, James Wyeth laughed.
``Yes, of a lot of pigs,'' he said.
   He posed for photographs before one of his more famous works,
Portrait of a Pig, a 4-by-7-foot painting done in 1970. The pig is
one of his favorite subjects and the exhibit displays several
paintings of other farm animals as well.
   The first portion of the exhibit displays N.C. Wyeth's art.
Although there are several paintings of Western scenes and a small
self-portrait from 1913, the majority of the 38 works on display
are book illustrations.
   N.C. Wyeth, who died in 1945, illustrated such classics as
Robert Louis Stevenson's ``Treasure Island'' and ``Kidnapped,'' and
Mark Twain's ``The Mysterious Stranger'' in the 1910s and 1920s.
   The exhibit runs through Nov. 20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 2111EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DetroitNewspapers     09-16 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Detroit Newspapers,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit Newspapers Deal Stalled For Second Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Detroit newspaper urged a federal appeals
court Friday to lift an order that for a second time stalled its
plans to combine business and production departments with a larger
rival.
   Attorneys for the Detroit Free Press asked the U.S. Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia Circuit to allow the agreement
to go forward, saying ``entry into a (joint operating agreement) is
by its nature an emergency remedy.''
   The court late Thursday barred the joint operations from
beginning after the expiration at 7:15 p.m. Saturday of a
lower-court stay. The superseding order carried no expiration date.
   The appeals court ordered the delay to gain time to study the
complex case, the court clerk's office said. The court gave no
indication when a ruling might come.
   Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press, a group of
advertisers and readers opposed to the newspapers' joint operating
agreement, had asked for a delay in implementing the joint
operating agreement. The court declined to grant the group's
request, but on its own authority issued a stay.
   The general manager of the Free Press, Bob Hall, said the stay
``just gives the judges a couple of days to look at the filings''
and has no bearing on the merits of the case.
   The partial merger under the Newspaper Preservation Act,
requested by the newspapers in 1986, was approved last month by
then-Attorney General Edwin Meese III.
   Michigan Citizens succeeded in blocking immediate implementation
of the agreement through a challenge in U.S. District Court in
Washington.
   The lower court on Wednesday rejected the challenge, and
Michigan Citizens the next day asked the appeals court to consider
the case.
   Free Press attorneys said Michigan Citizens' had failed to show
they were likely to succeed in an appeal or that denial of the stay
would cause permanent damage.
   Michigan Citizens contends the joint operating agreement would
set a precedent because it would allow a merger in a case where the
newspapers' financial losses were due to management decisions
rather than the normal competition in the marketplace.
   The group said such a precedent could end newspaper competition
in 20 cities served by multiple newspapers.
   The organization argued that the lower court, in granting a
stay, had accepted the premise that allowing the partial merger to
proceed while under challenge would be contrary to the public
interest.
   The Free Press, owned by Knight-Ridder Inc., had a daily
circulation last year of 638,720; the News, owned by Gannett Co.
Inc., had circulation of 678,720, according to the Audit Bureau of
Circulation.
   Knight-Ridder has said it will close the Free Press if the joint
operating agreement does not go through, at a cost of 2,000 jobs.
The merger of the newspapers' business, advertising, circulation
and production departments would result in the loss at both
newspapers of 600 to 800 jobs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
