<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Fire-Drifter     09-16 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire-Drifter,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drifter Charged In Fire That Destroyed Homes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEVADA CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transient suspected of accidentally
igniting a fire that destroyed 102 homes has been charged in the
blaze.
   Gary Wayne Parris, 39, appeared in Nevada County court Thursday
on a charge of felony count of reckless burning. He is also charged
with public drunkenness. He was being held Friday on $50,000 bail.
   Parris was at first charged with a misdemeanor count, but the
charge was upgraded because of evidence of ``willful and wanton''
disregard of the fire danger, according to District Attorney John
Darlington.
   Parris apparently lived in an abandoned home in a remote area
near Nevada City, about 50 miles northeast of Sacramento.
   The state Department of Forestry encouraged the district
attorney to file the more serious charges to get Parris off the
street for his own safety and so he can receive psychological help,
said chief ranger Robert Paulus.
   Some residents have expressed anger towards Parris, who police
say started the huge blaze Sunday by burning toilet paper outside a
makeshift outhouse.
   The fire destroyed 102 homes and 57 outbuildings, according to
state Department of Forestry spokeswoman Karen Terrill. So far, the
economic toll has risen beyond $15 million, including $11 million
in property damage and $4.2 million in suppression costs. The fire
was fully contained on Thursday.
