<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gilbert-Louisiana     09-16 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gilbert-Louisiana,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louisiana Coastal Residents Homeward Bound As Gilbert Heads For
Mexico</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Hurricane Gilbert Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Louisiana coastal
residents headed back to their deserted homes Friday after
Hurricane Gilbert barreled away from the Bayou State and toward
northeastern Mexico.
   ``It feels good to go home,'' said evacuee Fred Racca, a Cameron
Parish resident who spent Thursday night at an evacuation center in
a Lake Charles high school gym. He balanced a mattress on his head
while he walked out with his wife and three children.
   Cameron Parish civil defense director Hayes Picou gave
permission for his area's 10,000 residents to return home after
deciding that the danger for Louisiana was almost over.
   ``We're still monitoring the situation, but we think it's clear
enough for everyone to come home,'' Picou said.
   Other parishes followed Cameron's lead as the day progressed.
   But Andy Valence, mayor of the barrier island community of Grand
Isle, on a remote spit of land exposed to the Gulf of Mexico,
warned the 2,000 residents under his jurisdiction to stay away.
   Tides churned by Gilbert threatened to swamp the only road to
the mainland by Saturday morning, Valence said. And anyone who
returned to the island would be trapped if the storm headed back to
the Gulf and turned toward Louisiana.
   Scattered thunderstorms, wind gusts of up to 25 mph and tides
three to four feet above normal buffeted Louisiana's coast Friday
afternoon, but Bill Crouch of the National Weather Service said
that would be the extent of the bad weather if the storm's path
held.
   ``I think they are getting right now the worst they can
expect,'' said Crouch.
   Still, Gilbert exacted a toll on Louisiana and its people.
   Oil production in the Gulf was shut down for days because
offshore workers had to abandon rigs _ first for last week's
Hurricane Florence, then for Gilbert.
   Also, commercial shrimpers and fishermen had to abandon the Gulf
and inland waterways.
   At Grand Isle, Valence worried about severe coastal erosion that
began with Florence and continued with Gilbert. As much as 60 feet
of beach had washed away by Friday in some areas, he said.
   In Lafayette, Gilbert postponed the lucrative Festival Acadiens,
a world renowned celebration of Cajun culture and music that draws
thousands each year. The festival was moved to the first weekend in
October.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
