<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NYPrimary     09-16 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NY Primary,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Hope Primary Victories Mean Elections in November</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two of the state's leading Democrats won
renomination even though they were brushed by scandal, but voters
took the advice of a third Democrat who resigned his post after a
criminal conviction and said he did not want to be nominated.
   Among the winners in Thursday's primaries were every Democratic
incumbent in Congress and in the state Legislature who had sought
re-election.
   Five-term Bronx Congressman Robert Garcia, who was tied to the
Wedtech influence peddling scandal but has not been charged with
criminal wrongdoing; and state Senate Minority Leader Manfred
Ohrenstein of Manhattan, who has been charged in a criminal
indictment with doling out public money for private campaigns, both
survived primary challenges.
   A former incumbent, Rep. Mario Biaggi, did lose to state
Assemblyman Eliot Engel in a three-way race for the Democratic
nomination for Biaggi's old congressional seat.
   Biaggi had resigned from Congress in August after his conviction
in the Wedtech scandal and said he didn't want to be designated as
his party's nominee. Ironically, though, he will still be on the
November ballot, because the once-popular politician received the
GOP nomination with no primary opposition.
   There were no primary races in the only major statewide office
up this year _ the U.S. Senate seat held by Democrat Daniel Patrick
Moynihan. His GOP challenger in November will be lawyer Robert
McMillan.
   All of Thursday's Democratic incumbent winners in New York City
are virtually assured of victory in the general election in the
heavily Democratic city.
   John Marino, executive director of the state Democratic
Committee, said state party leaders are now focusing on suburban
and upstate congressional races where Democratic winners Thursday
face tough contests for seats now held by Republicans.
   ``What they have to do now is build upon the momentum that they
created for themselves and let that take them into Nov. 8,'' he
said.
   The seats include the one held by Rep. Jack Kemp, who opted not
to seek re-election in order to made a bid for the GOP presidential
nomination.
   The Wedtech scandal, in which Biaggi was convicted and Garcia
was implicated, involves a now-bankrupt Bronx defense contractor
whose officials allegedly bribed a number of local and federal
officials.
   Ohrenstein, who's been in the state Senate since 1960, faces
nearly a 400-count indictment in Manhattan charging that he misused
public funds to finance the private campaigns of Senate Democratic
candidates in 1986.
   Ohrenstein narrowly repulsed a primary challenge from Joseph
Rose, 29, the son of a wealthy developer who outspent Ohrenstein by
a 3-to-1 margin.
   The drawing power of one famous political name fell short in
suburban Westchester County, as former state official Nita Lowey
defeated Hamilton Fish III and a third candidate for the right to
oppose Republican Rep. Joseph DioGuardi in November.
   Fish's father, Hamilton Fish Jr., a Republican, represents a
neighboring district in Congress that had previously been
represented by his father, also named Hamilton Fish.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
