<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Cattle-Feedlots     09-16 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cattle-Feedlots,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agency Says 6.67 Million Head Being Fed For Slaughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle being fed for the slaughter market as
of Sept. 1 in the seven major beef states totaled 6.67 million
head, down 2 percent from a year ago but 4 percent more than
inventories of two years ago, the Agriculture Department said
Friday.
   The placement of new cattle and calves in fattening pens last
month was reported at 1.62 million head, down 16 percent from a
year ago and down 10 percent from two years ago.
   Marketings of ``fed'' cattle in August totaled 1.72 million
head, the same as a year ago but up 4 percent from two years ago.
   As of Sept. 1, feedlot inventories were larger than a year
earlier in California, Colorado, Kansas and Nebraska but were less
in Arizona, Iowa and Texas. The seven states produce about
three-fourths of the nation's beef.
   State feedlot cattle inventories are listed here for the seven
states. The first number is the number of cattle, in thousands, as
of Sept. 1, and the second number is the percentage of a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Arizona          199   74
California       485  107
Colorado         660  106
Iowa             475   97
Kansas         1,440  103
Nebraska       1,520  103
Texas          1,895   90
</TEXT>
