<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Jet-HotelSettlement     09-16 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jet-Hotel Settlement,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurance Company, Hotel Reach Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of a hotel extensively damaged
when an Air Force jet crashed into it last October, killing 10
people, have reached a $4 million settlement with their insurance
company, it was announced Friday.
   Shelby Insurance Co. of Shelby, Ohio, agreed to the payment of
the Airport Ramada Inn's claim. Representatives of both the
insurance company and the hotel said they plan to sue the Air Force.
   Sam Saini, principal owner of the hotel near Indianapolis
International Airport, has estimated damages, including the loss of
business income, at $9.5 million.
   The hotel, its north side still showing the smoke stains and
damage from the Oct. 20 crash, has not reopened.
   Officials of the insurance company said Shelby likely will file
suit against the Air Force to recover money paid to the hotel
owners in the settlement.
   The A-7D Corsair, returning to Nellis Air Force Base, Nev.,
crashed after its engine flamed out and it overshot the nearby
airport during an emergency landing attempt. The pilot, Maj. Bruce
Teagarden, ejected safely just before the plane hit the building.
   Teagarden was about 800 feet above the ground when he broke out
of clouds and began searching for an area to eject, according to an
Air Force report in January.
   He saw a pie-shaped field, aimed the plane at it and ejected
while about 300 feet above the ground.
   The jet then veered to the right and hit a bank building before
bouncing into the street and slamming into the Ramada Inn, causing
a deadly fireball.
</TEXT>
