<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Bible     09-16 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Bible,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former U.S. Senator Remembered Preserving the Nation's Natural
Resources</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Sen. Alan Bible was remembered
Friday as a giant in Congress whose quiet work helped preserve the
nation's natural resources.
   ``There is not an area in this country that has not benefited
from Alan Bible,'' former Gov. Mike O'Callaghan said in a eulogy to
350 people that included Nevada's top government and business
leaders.
   ``There is hardly a state in the union that does not owe a debt
of gratitude to this quiet Senator. Our friend Alan Bible was a
quiet man who left a record that has seldom been matched.''
   Bible, a Democrat, sponsored legislation in the Senate that set
up the nation's first protection acts for parks, water, air,
wildlife and historical sites, including the Grand Canyon.
   A major force in Nevada politics for more than 40 years, Bible
died Monday at a hospital in Auburn, Calif., of complications from
a respiratory illness. He was 78.
   Born in the rural northern Nevada community of Lovelock, Bible
was a member of the Senate for 20 years after serving in several
state public service positions. He retired from the Senate in 1974.
   ``I got the greatest pleasure out of trying to help people,''
Bible once said. ``There can be no greater reward in life.''
   Bible graduated from the University of Nevada-Reno in 1930 and
he received a law degree from Georgetown University in 1934.
   He was elected Storey County district attorney in 1938 and state
attorney general in 1942. After he retired from the Senate, he
returned to the University of Nevada-Reno to teach political
science for eight years.
   While in Congress, Bible cast the deciding Senate vote to
override President Nixon's veto of the Clear Water Act.
   Bible was also well known for his efforts to secure Nevada's
share of Colorado River water and to build pumping stations to
bring it into Las Vegas. Bible is survived by his wife, Loucile;
daughter, Debra; sons Paul, William and David; and seven
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
