<DOCNO> AP880916-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Contras-US     09-16 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras-US,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cesar Hoping For Agreement Soon On Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political director of the Nicaraguan Contras
said Friday he hoped the rebels will reach agreement within the
next three weeks on a long-term peace accord with the leftist
Managua government.
   But even if the talks do not succeed, said directorate member
Alfredo Cesar, the militarily weakened rebels will have captured
the moral high ground by demonstrating their willingness to seek
peace.
   ``There is the perception that the negotiation process is
stalled and that the resistance has not done everything possible''
to keep it on track, Cesar told reporters after meeting with
congressional leaders. The Contras have been blamed for the breakup
of peace talks June 9.
   The new rebel initiative means both Congress and the new
administration taking office in January ``will definitely have
found that we went the extra mile,'' he said.
   ``Taking the decision to go back (into talks with the Sandinista
government) without military aid is a very extraordinary gesture of
good faith on the part of the resistance,'' Cesar said.
   The Contras, formally known as the Nicaraguan Resistance,
announced on Thursday that they would send a delegation to
preliminary talks in Guatemala City on Monday aimed at a resumption
of the peace talks.
   Cesar said they will offer to begin formal, high-level peace
talks Sept. 26-28 in Guatemala, Costa Rica or the Dominican
Republic.
   The rebels say they will place no preconditions on the talks,
but will ask that the Sandinistas release 39 people jailed July 10
after an anti-government demonstration in Nandaime, a town near
Managua.
   Col. Enrique Bermudez, the rebels' military commander and a
newly elected directorate member, said the prisoner release would
``create a good climate for the negotiations.''
   In separate meetings with House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and
Minority Leader Robert Michel, R-Ill., members of the rebel
directorate said they hoped to reach an agreement that would let
their troops, most of which have been withdrawn from Nicaragua into
camps along the Honduran border, relocate in previously designated
cease-fire zones inside Nicaragua.
   They also said they wanted to establish goals for democratic
reforms to be implemented in Nicaragua and promised that, ``with
these reforms undertaken,'' they would lay down their arms.
   In a letter to congressional leaders, the rebels asked that a
$27 million humanitarian aid package now pending as part of a
disputed Pentagon money bill be modified to permit training for
Contra soldiers in ``human rights, hygiene, leadership skills and
political education;'' civic action to aid civilians affected by
the war, including medical supplies and ``basic work tools;''
communications gear to maintain contact with troops in the field;
and unspecified ``equipment needed to preserve ... physical
safety'' for troops en route to cease-fire zones.
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., a leading Contra opponent, said it
was unlikely the aid package would be modified. ``It's a delicate
compromise'' reached after three weeks of negotiations among Senate
Democrats, he said, adding, ``I'm very skeptical of people's
motives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
