<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 2125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AutoDefects     09-16 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Defects,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NHTSA Probes Allegations of Chrysler, Nissan Seat Defects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators opened an investigation
into reports that defective seats on more than 3 million Chrysler
and Nissan vehicles can cause drivers to lose control, the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration said Friday.
   The agency also opened 10 other preliminary evaluations, the
lowest level of investigation, into alleged automotive defects.
   Seat backs on 1.5 million Nissan cars and 1.7 million Chrysler
Caravan and Voyager vehicles allegedly are prone to collapse
suddenly, jarring the driver and causing him or her to steer out of
control, according to unconfirmed reports received by NHTSA.
   The agency ordered preliminary evaluations of all Nissan
passenger vehicles made from 1982 through 1984 and all 1984-1987
Chrysler Caravan and Voyager models.
   NHTSA said it has received 17 complaints of seat-back failure in
the Nissan vehicles, allegedly resulting in four accidents in which
five people were injured.
   Nine complaints received by the agency involved the Caravan and
Voyager. There was allegedly one accident in which three people
were injured, NHTSA said.
   ``We are aware of the NHTSA investigation and have received the
inquiry,'' said Chrysler Corp. spokesman Tony Cervone. ``We are
investigating the claim ourselves and will cooperate fully with
NHTSA's investigation.''
   Nissan Motor Corp. in U.S.A. said it would have no immediate
comment.
   Four new investigations involved other major U.S. automakers.
   The agency was studying allegations of door-hinge pin failure on
General Motors Corp.'s 1987-88 Beretta and Corsica models, and a GM
service bulletin reporting erratic cruise-control response on the
company's 1988 G vans with 6.2-liter diesel engines.
   NHTSA also opened probes of alleged failure of a seat-belt clip
in Ford Motor Co.'s 1984 Mustang and floormat interference with the
accelerator in the company's 1987-1988 Thunderbird and Cougar cars.
   Other new investigations ordered by NHTSA involved:
   _Steering shaft separation in the 1986 Hyundai Excel, in
reaction to a Canadian recall.
   _Ruptured fuel hoses in Hyundai Excels, in reaction to an
Australian recall.
   _Brake light switch failure in the 1985 BMW 325, 524, 528, 535,
635 and 735 models.
   _Heater core ruptures in the 1987 Volkswagen Golf.
   _Failure of some truck tires made by Danubian.
   _Brake shoe and caliper failure in some Midas products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
