<HEAD>US Says Chilean Police Overreacted In Quelling Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Friday Chilean
security agents used ``excessive and unnecessary'' forces in
breaking up a protest demonstration in which two American labor
leaders were participating.
   The incident, which occurred Thursday, involved some 300 persons
who gathered at the Chilean Supreme Court to protest a decision to
condemn a labor leader to a sentence of internal exile.
   The protest included Jack Joyce, president of the International
Bricklayer's Union, and William Doherty, of the AFL-CIO's American
Institute for Free Labor Development.
   Speaking from Santiago, Joyce said he and Doherty were knocked
down and tear-gassed by police during the demonstration.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said that according to
incomplete information, the group had been attempting to comply
with the directions of the authorities when they were dispersed
violently by Chilean security forces using water cannons, tear gas
and billy clubs.
   The U.S. Embassy in Santiago has protested the incident, which
occurred three weeks before a national plebiscite in which
President Augusto Pincochet will be the lone candidate.
   ``The Department of State regrets this overreaction by the
government of Chile to a peaceful protest,'' Redman said.
   ``We again stress that it behooves Chilean authorities,
especially during the final stage of the plebiscite campaign, to
show great care as they fulfill their commitment to create an
electoral climate free of intimidation.''
