<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 2128EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SoilProgram     09-16 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soil Program,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Offer To Take Additional 3.4 Million Acres From Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers have offered to take an additional 3.4
million acres of highly erodible cropland from production under the
10-year Conservation Reserve Program, or CRP, the Agriculture
Department said Friday.
   Milton Hertz, administrator of the department's Agricultural
Stabilization and Conservation Service, said the offers, or bids,
were made in the seventh signup for the program held July 18
through Aug. 31.
   Under the program, farmers agree to take land from production
for 10 years. In return, based on bids they submit, farmers get
annual rental payments from the government and one-time assistance
pay for half the cost of planting grass, trees and shrubs to guard
against erosion.
   The annual rental payments have been averaging around $50 per
acre.
   Acceptance of the bids will be announced around Dec. 15, Hertz
said. Congress in the 1985 farm law set a goal of 40 million to 45
million acres for the program by 1990.
   ``New CRP contracts may not be entered into which provide for an
annual rental rate in excess of the prevailing local rental rate
for comparable land,'' he said. ``Making this determination on each
bid will require extra time.''
   Including more than 25.5 million acres signed up earlier, the
latest offers would boost the program to almost 29 million acres if
all of the new bids are accepted.
   Hertz said he was encouraged by the continued interest in the
CRP, particularly in view of the 1988 drought.
   Kenneth A. Cook, senior associate of The Conservation
Foundation, a private, non-profit research organization based in
Washington, D.C., said the latest offerings were ``really a pretty
amazing signup when it started at the worst of the drought.''
   Cook said the signup could have turned out to be light, since
crop prices were going up rapidly because of the drought and it
would have been tempting for many farmers to think about growing
crops instead.
   ``But a lot of them may have thought these high (commodity)
prices aren't here to stay,'' Cook said. ``Also, the department
raised the bid levels the Corn Belt, and that helped.''
</TEXT>
