<HEAD>Bentsen Says Bush Is Silent on Deficits, Iran-Contra, Noriega</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB 3rd graf to CORRECT date of Pearl Harbor to Dec. 7 sted
1
bgng ``Well, it...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen said Friday that
Republican George Bush has wrongly criticized the Democrats but had
``a bad case of laryngitis'' about budget deficits, arms sales to
Iran and dealings with Panamanian leader Manuel Noriega.
   Stumping for votes on the steps of the Pitt County Courthouse,
the Democratic vice presidential nominee rejected Bush's charge
Thursday that with Michael Dukakis as governor, Massachusetts had
become a ``fiscal fiasco'' of high taxes and lost jobs.
   ``Well, it was Pearl Harbor Day all over again. As usual, George
got all of his facts wrong,'' Bentsen said, reminding his
snickering audience of 1,000 people about Bush's remark last week
that Sept. 7 rather than Dec. 7 was the anniversary of the Japanese
attack on Pearl Harbor.
   Standing in the shadow of a statue of a Confederate soldier, the
Texas senator praised the Democratic presidential candidate's
gubernatorial record.
   ``Under Mike Dukakis, Massachusetts unemployment is the lowest
rate of any major industrial state in this union,'' Bentsen said.
``Wages are growing twice as fast as the national average, personal
income growing faster than any other state, and he submitted 10
balanced budgets in a row.''
   ``When George Bush speaks out against Mike Dukakis,'' he said,
``we should all remember that when it came to speaking out against
arms to Iran, when it came to speaking out against cozy deals with
Gen. Noriega of Panama, when it came to speaking out against
economic policies that have almost tripled the national debt,
George Bush didn't speak, he just voted present.
   ``I'll tell you, when it comes to strong leadership, George Bush
has got himself a bad case of laryngitis,'' said Bentsen, who will
complete a four-day Southern campaign tour in Florida.
   ``I'm looking for old friends who wandered away in recent
years,'' he told the Greenville crowd, his biggest of the week.
``I'm talking to the Reagan Democrats. I'm urging them to come
home, and they're responding.''
   Earlier in the day at Memphis, Tenn., Bentsen told a breakfast
crowd of party loyalists that Dukakis' positions on trade, the
economy, education and defense were ones that Southerners could
support.
   He said Bush's attacks grew out of ``panic'' over the Democratic
ticket's early lead in public opinion polls.
   ``Mike Dukakis and Lloyd Bentsen are prepared to pay the price
to defend freedom. And you have my word on it,'' Bentsen said.
   Introduced by Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., and former Mississippi
Gov. William Winter, Bentsen said the Republicans were trying to
hide such policy failures of the past eight years as a
near-tripling of the national debt.
   ``George Bush talking about balanced budgets,'' he said in
Greenville. ``It's like Dan Quayle talking about his resume.
There's really not much to say.''
   Democratic gubernatorial candidate Bob Jordan of North Carolina
compared Quayle with Bentsen and said, ``God help us if Bush is
elected.''
   ``Did George Bush choose the most qualified person he could
find?'' Gore asked.
   ``We don't have to apologize to anybody, anywhere, for the
ticket we are putting before the American people this year,''
Winter said in Memphis.
