<HEAD>Four Bodies Found in Plane Wreckage on Maine Mountain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers on Friday found the bodies of
four people amid the wreckage of a single-engine plane that crashed
and burned a week ago en route to a fly-in at this northern Maine
town, authorities said.
   Authorities were unaware of the missing plane until they were
notified late Wednesday by relatives who failed to hear from the
travelers, said Ronald Roy, director of the Aeronautics Division of
the state Department of Transportation. No flight plan was filed,
he said.
   A search was launched Thursday, and on Friday, one of six Civil
Air Patrol planes spotted the wreckage in trees along the northwest
side of Lily Bay Mountain, about 10 miles north of Greenville, said
Steve McCausland, spokesman for the Maine State Police.
   A medic who was ferried to the scene in a National Guard
helicopter confirmed that there were no survivors among the two men
and two women, McCausland said.
   The Cessna 182 had taken off from Lawrence, Mass., on Sept. 9 to
participate in a weekend fly-in in Greenville, Roy said.
   The search was concentrated within 10 miles of Greenville after
investigators determined the pilot had made radio contact with the
control tower at Bangor International Airport and that radar tapes
from the Federal Aviation Administration in Boston indicated the
plane had reached the Greenville area.
