<2ND_LINE>AM-Mutilation Deaths,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators After Links Between Three Unidentified, Mutilated
Bodies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criminal investigators are looking for a
connection among three decapitated bodies of young men found since
May in widely separated areas of Georgia.
   The only current ties in the three deaths are that none of the
bodies showed signs of a struggle and that they shared similar
physical characteristics, officials said.
   The first was found in May near Cartersville in northwestern
Georgia, the second Sept. 6 near Warwick in southern Georgia and
the third Wednesday near Bogart in the northeastern part of the
state.
   All three were missing hands and head, with one also missing his
feet.
   None of the three has been identified, and officials have
released no cause of death in any of the cases.
   ``There's no question, to find bodies like this in Georgia is
very, very unusual,'' said John Bankhead, spokesman for the Georgia
Bureau of Investigation.
   ``We're trying to see how they might be linked, but there's no
way we can be sure if they are right now,'' he said. The bureau is
checking with other states to see if there are similar cases.
   Local sheriffs said each man appeared be of average height,
between 5-feet-6 and 6-feet, and of average build. Officials
believe each man was killed elsewhere and then left where the
bodies were found.
   Investigators hope they can find leads from the clothing found
on the Bogart and Bartow bodies. The Warwick body was clad only in
underwear.
