<2ND_LINE>AM-Guatemala-Protest,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says US Citizens Demonstrating at Embassy Have Right to Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALFONSO ANZUETO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GUATEMALA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four American citizens who chained
themselves to a gate of the U.S. Embassy three days ago to protest
Washington's policies in Central America are within their rights,
an embassy spokesman said Friday.
   ``This is an example of the right to protest in a country where
the right of free expression is respected,'' embassy spokesman John
Tracy said. It was the embassy's first official response.
   The protesters who began the demonstration Wednesday by throwing
a liquid resembling blood on the embassy steps and then chained
themselves to the main entrance were identified as Dale
Ashara-Davis, 34, of Baltimore, Md.; John Schuchardt, 49, of New
Haven, Conn., and Sara Story, 26, and Charlie Litery, 57, both of
Washington, D.C..
   The four, along with 16 other U.S. citizens jailed in Honduras,
belong to a group called Project Independence,
   Tracy said the protesters in Guatemala have not caused any major
problems or blocked people from entering and leaving the embassy.
   The protesters said they have asked to talk to U.S. Ambassador
James Michel, but Tracy said that ``up to now, they have not made
that request through the normal channels.''
   In Honduras, police Maj. Manuel Urbina said Thursday that 16
U.S. citizens were jailed after demonstrating at the U.S. Embassy
in Tegucigalpa and at the Palmerola air base 40 miles northwest of
the capital.
   Urbina, spokesman for the Public Security Forces, said the
detainees probably would be expelled.
   A declaration issued by the Project Independence group said,
``At this time of remembering Central American independence from
Spain (in 1821) we've come to join with Central Americans in
declaring its independence from U.S. domination.''
</TEXT>
