<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-16 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 350-pound sow decided she wasn't ready for hog
heaven and tried to make a break for it on the way to the
slaughterhouse.
   Or maybe she just wanted new duds for the occasion.
   The daring hog leaped from a truck onto the six-lane U.S. 70 in
front of a shopping mall Thursday.
   ``That's the first time I've ever come along to find a pig in
the road,'' said trucker Richard Belk of Salisbury.
   A witness told police the hog lifted the truck's tailgate with
its snout. Once out of the truck, the stunned sow stood in the road
for at least 15 minutes, refusing to budge as amazed motorists
stopped, stared and honked.
   ``The pig wasn't afraid at all,'' said Charlene Evans. ``A
trucker blew his horn at her and she wouldn't budge.''
   About eight police officers and motorists helped the truck's
driver reload the hog, which wasn't hurt except for a few scrapes.
   ``Did they say she was going to slaughter?'' asked police
officer R.B. Brown. ``I would've jumped out, too.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EL CAJON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If anyone is entitled to a little peace
and quiet, it's Bob and Dorothy DeBolt.
   The DeBolts, once the subject of an Academy Award-winning
documentary, raised six of their own children and 14 adopted ones,
many of whom have physical and mental handicaps.
   Now the couple, who moved to San Diego County about a year ago
from northern California, are savoring their accomplishments and
their empty nest.
   ``We always intended for our children to grow up and leave
home,'' said Mrs. DeBolt, 65. ``When each of the children flew the
nest, it was a wonderful kind of achievement. We don't pay for
anything anymore; they are all fiercely, fully independent.''
   The brood is scattered throughout California and as far as
Hawaii. Many live in Oakland or Berkeley, near the family's former
home in Piedmont, Calif.
   The DeBolts married in 1970, when Dorothy was a widow with nine
children, four of them adopted.
   Three years later, DeBolt, 57, quit his job as president of a
construction company, when the couple founded their own adoption
agency to help people adopt children with handicaps.
   The DeBolts said they now support themselves by giving seminars
and making public appearances.
</TEXT>
