<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TextileBill     09-16 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Textile Bill,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Textile Lawmakers Keep Bill Out of Conference Committee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile-state lawmakers won a key tactical
victory Friday in the House, persuading a committee chairman to
change course and push for approval of Senate-passed import
legislation without any changes.
   ``In my opinion this will insure passage of the textile bill by
Congress this year,'' Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said after
receiving word of the decision. ``The biggest danger we face now is
a presidential veto.''
   The bill, designed to protect American manufacturers from
foreign competition, would freeze current textile and apparel
imports at 1987 levels and hold growth to one percent annually
starting next year.
   Advancing amid a flurry of Reagan administration veto threats,
the measure would also cap nonrubber footwear imports at 1987
levels with no provision for increases.
   House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., met for 45 minutes with 20 textile-state lawmakers and then
consulted with senior committee members before deciding on an
about-face that will avoid sending the bill to a House-Senate
conference committee.
   At Rostenkowski's urging, the committee had approved Wednesday a
plan to send the bill to a conference committee with the Senate to
resolve differences. Textile lawmakers said the measure could
become snagged in the conference committee.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, told reporters Thursday that
it was ``not certain'' that the measure would go to a conference
committee. He indicated that there was still time to change course.
   The bill's supporters say it is needed to save American jobs
that will inevitably dwindle as the U.S. market becomes flooded
with textile and apparel imports. Critics say the measure
represents protectionism that would narrow consumer choices and
actually cost more jobs than it would save when Asian
textile-exporting nations retaliate.
   Congressional supporters of the textile industry expect Reagan
to veto the legislation. He vetoed an earlier version in 1985.
   Thus far, industry supporters have been unable to muster the
two-thirds support in either house needed to override a veto and
pass the measure into law over the president's objections.
   At all costs, however, they hope to deny Reagan the opportunity
to exercise a so-called pocket veto. The president may prevent a
bill from becoming law when Congress is out of session merely by
refusing to sign it.
   Congress had set a target date for adjournment of Oct. 5,
although that easily could be extended an extra week.
   Textile industry supporters say forcing Reagan to use his veto
pen and not merely kill the bill with a pocket veto would exact a
much higher political price from the Republican ticket in
textile-producing states.
   Differences between the Senate bill and the year-old House
version are few. The House bill would freeze imports at 1986
levels. It would set up a one-year pilot program under which the
government would auction off import licenses.
   It would guarantee better quotas to countries that increased
their purchases of U.S. farm goods. And it would set up a special
quota for imported silk neckties. Other than that, the two measures
are the same.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880916-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 2227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Derailment-Sinkhole     09-16 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Derailment-Sinkhole,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sinkhole Believed To Be Cause Of Derailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sinkhole that opened up beneath a
stretch of railroad track caused 27 cars of a freight train to
derail, CSX Transportation officials said Friday.
   ``The hole is the cause of the accident, there is no doubt about
that. It's as if a bridge fell or a tunnel collapsed. It's obvious
the whole track dropped fix to six feet. But we don't know why,''
CSX spokesman Lloyd Lewis said.
   ``The whole crossing where that track is contained is gone,'' he
said.
   Another CSX spokesman, Lindsay Leckie, said a depression, about
100 feet long, 10 feet wide and 5 feet deep, formed under the
tracks as the train rolled along early Thursday.
   ``There was apparently some water intrusion under the roadbed
which caused the track structure to collapse. The key question is
what caused this intrusion,'' Leckie said.
   He said the appearance of the hole was ``sudden, unobservable
and undetectable,'' adding that four locomotives and eight cars
passed over it before the derailment and other trains had used the
tracks an hour earlier.
   Tanker cars damaged in the derailment spewed noxious fumes into
the air. Two Florida Highway Patrol troopers were hospitalized for
respiratory problems after inhaling potassium hydroxide, and
several other officers and railroad workers were treated for
respiratory problems.
   The derailment forced the closing of five major intersections
and 45 nearby businesses. Four intersections and the businesses
reopened Friday.
</TEXT>
