<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 2138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Harper 2ndLd-Writethru a0745 09-16 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Harper, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0745,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Rules For Valerie Harper In Dispute Over `Valerie' Series</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-7, `Miss Harper ..., with 7 grafs to UPDATE with
comment from jury foreman, Lorimar spokeswoman, new quotes from
Miss Harper.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury decided Friday that Valerie Harper was
right and Lorimar Telepictures Corp. was wrong in the dispute that
ended her role in the ``Valerie'' television series, awarding her
nearly $2 million in damages and a share of the profits.
   The jurors gave Miss Harper and her husband, Tony Cacciotti, who
worked as a supervising producer for the show, $1.85 million in
general damages.
   The jury found that Miss Harper also is entitled to 12.5 percent
of the adjusted gross profits of the series for the 1987-88 season
_ even though she was no longer on the show for most of the season.
The contract wold have run through 1991.
   Her lawyer estimated that her share of last season's profits
could eventually amount to as much as $15 million if the show is
syndicated.
   Jurors found that Lorimar had acted with ``oppression and
malice'' in firing her. But the jury declined to grant her and her
husband any punitive damages.
   ``The television business is just like any other business,''
said jury foreman Archie McDaniels, a postal worker. ``You have
good and bad. This verdict doesn't condemn the TV industry. You
just have to treat people fairly.''
   Some of the jurors lined up in the hallway after delivering
their verdict to get Miss Harper's autograph. The actress, engulfed
by well-wishers and reporters as she left the courtroom, said she
felt ``vindicated.''
   She said she hoped the decision will be ``a landmark in terms of
how actors are dealt with.''
   ``People have to be accountable for what they do,'' she said.
``That's the real victory in this case.''
   Lorimar attorney Donald Engel called the verdict ``a mixed bag''
and said that from Lorimar's standpoint, ``it could have been
worse.'' He said he was pleased that no punitive damages were
awarded, and added that in a case that pitted an an individual
against a big corporation, ``we didn't do so bad.''
   He said an appeal was unlikely because ``the verdict is so
small,'' but Lorimar spokeswoman Barbara Brogliatti said: ``We're
disappointed in the verdict. And our attorney has advised us there
are grounds for an appeal and we are considering it.''
   Lorimar sued Miss Harper, claiming she breached her contract by
quitting the NBC show ``Valerie.'' A countersuit by Miss Harper and
her husband contended she was wrongfully fired from the show.
   Lorimar offered extensive testimony depicting Miss Harper as a
temperamental star who wanted complete creative control. Miss
Harper testified she wanted input on creative decisions but was not
trying to wrest complete control.
   She had stressed that she brought the concept of the ``Valerie''
series to NBC and expected to help shape the episodes. She claimed
the writers and producers changed the show to minimize her role and
focus on the teen-age boys in the series.
   Sandy Duncan replaced Miss Harper on the show, which was
retitled ``The Hogan Family.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
