<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Air Show,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll From Ramstein Air Show Disaster Rises To 64</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 34-year-old West German man died
Friday from injuries suffered at last month's Ramstein air show
disaster, bringing the death toll to 64, a state official said.
   Rhineland-Palatinate state spokesman Juergen Dietzen said the
man died in a hospital in Homburg early Friday from severe burns
suffered in the Aug. 28 catastrophe during an air show at the
Ramstein U.S. Air Force base.
   Dietzen said 152 people remained hospitalized in 46 facilities
and at least 25 of the victims are in very serious or critical
condition.
   The accident occurred when three jets in a 10-plane Italian air
force stunt team collided during a performance. One of the jets
plunged into the crowd below and exploded in flames.
   Officials gave the following breakdown by nationalities of the
people who perished: 57 West Germans, a U.S. soldier and her
9-year-old son, one French citizen, a Dutch citizen and the three
Italian pilots.
</TEXT>
