<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Superfund     09-16 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Superfund,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressmen Ask EPA to Hold Off on Superfund Study</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen congressional committee chairmen,
subcommittee chairman and ranking Republicans asked the
Environmental Protection Agency on Friday not to begin a major
study of the ``Superfund'' toxic waste cleanup program so late in
the administration.
   ``The agency should concentrate its full energy and resources on
implementing'' amendments to the cleanup law passed in 1986
``rather than on reopening many policy questions which were hotly
contested during enactment and during reauthorization less than two
years ago,'' the leaders wrote to EPA.
   ``Second, it is inappropriate to spend Superfund money to
undertake a costly Superfund reauthorization study during the final
days of this administration,'' the group said.
   The agency had planned to give the Conservation Foundation $2.5
million for a study to define issues that should be dealt with in
the Superfund program. Environmentalists had objected that such a
study really should be done as part of the congressional work
leading to renewal of the law in 1991.
   ``Any long-term Superfund study going beyond data gathering
should be developed by the next administration,'' the chairmen said.
   Craig DeRemer, an aide to Thomas, said the agency had to study
the letter before replying but it appeared that ``they have
misunderstood some of the purposes of the study.'' He said Thomas
wanted an examination of all hazardous waste issues, not just
Superfund.
   He noted that Thomas, in a Thursday conversation with reporters,
had said most Superfund issues could be characterized as both
``policy'' and ``implementation'' issues, such as the question of
``how clean is clean'' standards.
   In that conversation, Thomas noted, ``I haven't had anybody yet
come to me and say, `Lee, this is a dumb idea.''' However, he said
``we probably won't'' proceed if environmental groups decline to
serve on the study steering committee.
   ``The issues are going to be the same in any administration,''
DeRemer said. ``There is no reason to wait. Changes can always be
made in the new administration.''
</TEXT>
