<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 2104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Homeless-Housing     09-16 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless-Housing,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homeless Advocates Seek Court's Help to Obtain Federal Property
for Housing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for the homeless told a federal
judge Friday that the Department of Housing and Urban Development
violated the law by selling foreclosed homes to the highest bidder
without determining whether they could be used by the homeless and
low-income people.
   William Bradford, representing the coalition of advocates for
the homeless, told U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch that HUD
receives 70,000 single-family houses each year _ about 7,000 a
month _ but the agency ``cannot proceed as if it is simply in the
real estate business. They must consider the homeless.''
   In a related case, the National Coalition for the Homeless also
argued that the Reagan administration has defied a congressional
mandate to release underutilized federal property as housing for
the nation's homeless.
   Ms. Maria Foscarinis, a coalition attorney, said, ``There are
thousands of properties underutilized which could be used for the
homeless.'' She said that of the 12 facilities have been identified
as underutilized by the Veterans Administration, the Defense
Department and the General Services Administration, only two have
been made available to the homeless.
   Government attorney W. Robert Irwin argued that the 1987 Stuart
B. McKinney Homeless Assistance Act _ named after the late
Connecticut congressman who was a leading promoter of the measure _
does not apply to single-family dwellings.
   ``They want to shut down a program that has been going on for 50
years,'' Irwin said. ``They want to tie up the program.''
   Arthur Goldberg, another government lawyer, said all the
agencies have complied with the provisions of the Homeless Act.
   ``Congress was trying to match up the needs of the homeless with
the properties available,'' he said. ``It is not a perfect match.''
   Gasch, who heard three separate cases brought by homeless
advocates against the government, took them under advisement,
saying he would decide as soon as he can whether to issue
preliminary injunctions.
   Bradford told the judge that two temporary restraining orders
issued last month preventing HUD from auctioning off its foreclosed
single-family homes were to expire at the end of business Friday.
   Gasch merely said, ``I would hope they would maintain the status
quo.''
   HUD general counsel J. Michael Dorsey said the federal agency
would follow the restraining order voluntarily until the end of
business next Wednesday. It was anticipated that Gasch would decide
the case by then.
   HUD has said that it generally sells the homes to the highest
bidders _ frequently investors _ but insists that it has several
programs designed to help homeless people find places to live.
   Recently, HUD has been selling an average of 7,100 properties
each month _ houses that had Federal Housing Administration
mortgage insurance and that went into foreclosure when their owners
could no longer keep up the mortgage payments. The program has
produced some $2.4 billion in proceeds since Oct. 1, 1987, the
start of the current fiscal year.
   HUD officials have argued that the court decisions, if upheld,
could cost the agency $3 billion a year and bankrupt its
single-family mortgage insurance fund.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America, in a
friend-of-the-court brief, said if Gasch issued an injunction, it
would interfere with the orderly and efficient way HUD replenishes
and restores the actuarial soundness of the FHA program.
   The association said it would reduce future refunds of premiums
paid by current FHA-insured home owners, increase premiums of
future FHA homeowners, ``make single-family programs unavailable or
less attractive to prospective home buyers,'' and reduce the
opportunities of home ownership for individuals and families in the
future.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
