<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-16 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rains Drench Gulf States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert pushed clouds and thunderstorms across the
Gulf of Mexico coast on Friday, pelting the area with rain and
causing local flooding.
   Violent weather surrounding the hurricane spun off more than a
half-dozen tornadoes in the Brownsville, Texas, area Friday,
blowing over at least two homes and slightly injuring one person.
   Thunderstorms related to Gilbert also spawned tornadoes Friday
afternoon at Fort Rucker and Daleville in Alabama. Strong
thunderstorm wind gusts caused damage to trees and house roofs at
Houma, La.
   The calm eye at the heart of the hurricane made landfall about
120 miles south of Brownsville, at 4:35 p.m. CDT, in Mexico's
Tamaulipas state.
   The National Weather Service said tides near the hurricane
center will be as much as 11 feet higher than normal. Gilbert was
expected to bring 10 to 15 inches of rainfall.
   By noon on Friday, showers and thunderstorms reached from
eastern Texas across northern Florida and southern Georgia,
Alabama, Mississippi, Tennessee, Kentucky, Illinois, western
Indiana, Wisconsin, northern Minnesota and North Dakota. Rain also
continued over the northern Pacific Coast.
   Rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT included 2{
inches at Baton Rouge, La., almost 2 inches at Mobile, Ala., 1{
inches at Brownsville, Texas, and 1 and one-third inches at
Pensacola, Fla.
   The nation's low temperature Friday was 17 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Bremerton, Wash., to 104 degrees at Palm Springs, Calif.
   The forecast Saturday was for showers and thunderstorms in
central and eastern Texas, Arkansas, southeast Missouri, the Ohio
Valley, the Tennessee Valley, from Mississippi across Alabama, from
Florida to New York state, the Appalachians and the lower Great
Lakes. Rain was also predicted for northwest Montana.
   Predicted high temperatures were in the 60s over northern Maine,
Upper Michigan, and from the northern Rockies across the northern
Pacific Coast; near 90 degrees in Florida and Louisiana; in the 90s
from southwest Texas to the desert Southwest, and near 105 degrees
through the desert Southwest. High temperatures in the rest of the
nation were expected to reach seasonable 70s and 80s.
</TEXT>
