<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru a0625 09-16 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0625,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Supporters Begin New Political Party</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf `But some...' with 3 grafs to ADD background.
PICKUP 9th pvs `Mrs. Aquino, who...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of President Corazon
Aquino launched a new pro-administration political party Friday,
but she said the move must not be allowed to divide democratic
forces.
   Mrs. Aquino hailed the formation of Struggle of the Democratic
Filipino, the latest step in the realignment of forces that toppled
President Ferdinand Marcos' 20-year regime and propelled her to
power in February 1986.
   Mrs. Aquino made the remarks in a speech to the first national
convention of the party.
   ``Perhaps it is time to have political parties,'' she said in a
speech opening its first convention. ``Perhaps indeed, the time for
realignment is now. Yet, I hope that these realignments do not
portend the permanent and total division of the forces of democracy
in our country. For should that happen, it will mean the end of all
of us.''
   She said divisions among pro-democracy Filipinos enabled Marcos,
now in exile in Hawaii, to impose eight years of martial law in
1972 and prolong his rule.
   ``It is good for the country and for democracy if people with
shared ideals and programs organize themselves into separate
parties,'' Mrs. Aquino said. ``But it would be disastrous if we
divided ourselves again into permanent hostile camps.''
   Rep. Ramon Mitra, speaker of the House of Representatives, was
elected president of the new party, which organizers hope will
bring together pro-government forces under a single banner and
serve as the president's party.
   In February 1986 Mrs. Aquino ran for president under the banner
of the United Nationalist Democratic Organization, or UNIDO, the
party of her running mate, Salvador Laurel. Since then, Vice
President Laurel has criticized Mrs. Aquino's policies, UNIDO has
fared poorly at the ballot box and many of the party's legislators
have defected to pro-Aquino parties.
   Last month Laurel formed an opposition movement, the Union for
National Action. He accused Mrs. Aquino of incompetence and urged
her to resign to make way for new elections but he received little
popular support.
   Some pro-Aquino politicians say formation of the Struggle for
the Democratic Filipino is a bid by the president's relatives and
others to consolidate their own power before the 1992 presidential
election. Among the party's main organizers is Rep. Jose Cojuangco,
Mrs. Aquino's influential younger brother.
   Mrs. Aquino, who has vowed not to seek re-election, told more
than 5,000 delegates that she hoped the party was organized ``not
only for the 1992 elections but to help our people face and
overcome their problems.''
   She said Filipinos were disenchanted with traditional political
parties and the bickering and constant jockeying for positions.
Political parties in the Philippines traditionally revolved around
personalities rather than ideology.
   Mitra said Mrs. Aquino avoided giving the party a ringing
endorsement because she did not want to be accused of playing
politics. Mrs. Aquino said she was not favoring the party over
other parties in the government coalition and would keynote their
conventions if invited.
   Mitra said Thursday that the party was organized to consolidate
political support for the government and establish a grass-roots,
mass movement behind Mrs. Aquino.
   ``But there are others who do not believe in this thinking,''
Mitra said. He was referring to the refusal of 18 Liberal Party
members in the House to join the new party.
   The Liberals, led by Senate President Jovito Salonga, are among
six parties in the government coalition. But the Liberals have
disagreed with other pro-government parties and with some of the
president's influential relatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
