<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0622 09-16 0834</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0622,0857</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gaza Refugee Camps Under Curfew, Three Guerrillas Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 5 grafs SUB for 7th graf pvs, At least 266... UPDATING
casualties, newspaper banned. Picks up 8th graf pvs, Pro-PLO
leaders ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army imposed curfews Friday on 180,000
Arabs living in Gaza Strip refugee camps to prevent violence after
activists called a general strike to mark the 1982 massacre of
hundreds of Palestinians in Lebanon.
   In southern Lebanon, troops fatally shot three PLO guerrillas
who the army said planned to attack Israeli settlements.
   A Palestine Liberation Organization official told an Israeli
daily the PLO wants to negotiate peace but would not abandon
attacks against Israel.
   Police questioned Israeli peace crusader Abie Nathan, who met
this week with PLO chief Yasser Arafat in violation of Israeli law.
Nathan, 61, was released on $3,000 bail.
   ``I violated the law to promote peace and ... I'm ready to pay
the price,'' said Nathan, a former fighter pilot and owner of the
pirate radio station Voice of Peace.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, troops fired at Palestinian
stone-throwers, critically wounding a 14-year-old boy in the
stomach, hospital officials said. The army said it was checking the
report.
   The army denied another report by Arab hospital officials that
Israeli troop gunfire wounded a Palestinian in Jabaliya refugee
camp outside Gaza City.
   A 25-year-old Jewish woman was hit by a rock and suffered a
skull fracture while driving past Dahariyeh south of Hebron in the
West Bank on her way home to a settlement near Jerusalem, said
Tammy Lunenfeld, spokeswoman for Beersheba's Soroka hospital.
   Also Friday, the army banned distribution of the pro-PLO Al Fajr
newspaper in the occupied territories for 45 days, the military
government announced.
   It said the paper, based in Arab east Jerusalem, violated the
law by publishing ``a very anti-Semitic cartoon depicting a Jew as
a Nazi'' without submitting the cartoon to military censors.
   At least 266 Palestinians and six Israelis have been killed
since the Palestinian uprising began Dec. 8 in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Pro-PL0 leaders of the uprising called a general strike for
Saturday to mark the sixth anniversary of the slayings of hundreds
of Palestinians by Israeli-allied Christian militiamen in the
Beirut refugee camps Sabra and Chatilla.
   The army imposed indefinite curfews on the Gaza Strip refugee
camps Bureij, Jabaliya, Nuseirat, Khan Yunis and Shati to prevent
clashes during the anniversary, confining 180,000 Palestinians to
their homes. Four West Bank villages also were under curfew.
   In Gaza City, Islamic militants belonging to the underground
group Hamas, or Zeal, painted graffiti calling on merchants to
observe the strike. One slogan, written in Hebrew and Arabic, read
``Death to the Jews,'' Arab witnesses said.
   The three guerrillas killed in southern Lebanon belonged to
Arafat's Fatah faction, the largest in the PLO, Israel radio said.
   The squad carried Soviet-made Kalashnikov rifles equipped with
silencers and apparently was planning to attack border settlements
in northern Israel, the report said.
   An army patrol spotted the guerrillas on the northern slopes of
Mount Dov on the Israeli-Lebanese border and opened fire, the army
said. The Israeli troops did not suffer casualties.
   The clash was inside Israel's self-proclaimed security zone, a
six- to-10-mile-wide strip north of the border. It is patrolled by
about 1,000 Israeli troops and an equal number of Israeli-backed
Lebanese militiamen.
   In an interview published Friday in the Jerusalem Post daily,
PLO spokesman Bassam Abu Sharif said the organization would not
cease acts of violence against Israel or call a halt to the
uprising.
   ``Military operations that have been carried out against Israel,
the Israeli army, will definitely continue as an act of
resistance,'' Abu Sharif said.
   But he also said the PLO was ready to ``deal with any
representatives of the Israelis who are courageous enough to sit
and talk and negotiate peace.''
   Nathan was interrogated for 90 minutes by police in the Tel Aviv
suburb of Petah Tikva. Police officials said that once the
investigation is completed, it is up to the state attorney to
determine whether Nathan should stand trial.
   Nathan could face up to three years in prison for violating a
1986 law that bars Israelis from meeting with members of terror
groups. Israel considers the PLO a terror group.
   Nathan, who made millions selling hamburgers in Tel Aviv before
becoming a peace activist, said he didn't think he broke the law
because he met with Arafat to promote peace.
   As Nathan arrived at the police station, about 20 members of the
anti-Arab Kach movement waved an Israeli flag and shouted: ``A rope
for the traitor.'' Nathan turned to the demonstrators and tapped
his index finger against his temple to show he thought they were
stupid.
   Nathan said he requested a meeting with Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir to brief him on what Arafat said.
   Shamir said he would not see the activist, but told reporters
one of his assistants might receive Nathan.
</TEXT>
