<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Flag, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0682,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Some Backlash at Ohio's Flag City Festival</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: to clarify that Bush paraphrased the Pledge, SUB 2nd graf:
The GOP...half-hour speech.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FINDLAY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush took his patriotic road show to
this northwest Ohio community Friday, where some sponsors of the
local ``Flag City Festival'' complained that he turned the
non-partisan event into a Republican photo opportunity.
   The GOP presidential nominee told about 1,000 people waving
flags outside the Elks Lodge that ``the flag is back'' and rambled
into a paraphrase of the Pledge of Allegiance during his half-hour
speech.
   ``I wish the cynics around our country on the East Coast and
West Coast could be in Findlay today to see the outpouring of
patriotism,'' Bush said.
   ``I thrill to the site of the flag. I've seen it burned by
enemies abroad and scorned by the misguided in our country. And
I've seen it wrapped around the coffins of young men,'' he said.
   ``What is it all about? It's the symbol of these United States
of America, and to the liberty for which it stands, one nation
under God with freedom and justice for all. And let's never forget
it.''
   Neil Scott, a local businessman, protested in an interview that
``what was intended to be a non-partisan promotion of fun and
patriotism has turned into a partisan use of the flag for private
gain by a candidate.''
   Dean Fout, president of the North End Merchants Association,
also expressed annoyance that Bush would ``come charging in with `I
pledge allegience' and all that stuff, and take a lot of credit
away from us.''
   The event was conceived by local merchants to celebrate
patriotism and town spirit. Fout said Findlay officially calls
itself Flag City.
   Local Democrats planned to hold a ``pro-flag rally'' after
Bush's visit to ``promote the flag as a non-partisan symbol that
belongs to all of us,'' Scott said.
</TEXT>
