<HEAD>Police Won't Comment on Death of Bus Hijacker While in Custody</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASERU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police declined to comment Friday on the
death of a man captured after he and three other hijackers seized a
bus carrying 70 pilgrims to see Pope John Paul II.
   Three hijackers and a passenger were killed outright when police
stormed the bus Wednesday night and a second passenger died later
of his wounds.
   Several rescued hostages said the surviving gunman tried to
mingle with the passengers but was pointed out to police who seized
him. The witnesses said he did not appear to be seriously hurt.
   The government announced on Thursday that the man had died but
gave no details about the death, nor did it indicate why he died in
police custody a day after the gunfight.
   Several foreign journalists said they saw the man's body in a
hospital morgue and it appeared his throat had been cut and his jaw
smashed.
   The two slain passengers were a 14-year-old girl, killed
instantly, and a man, 55, who died Thursday. Officials said 21
other people were wounded by bullets and by shrapnel from the
hijackers' grenades.
   The hijackers had identified themselves as members of the
Lesotho Liberation Army and demanded a meeting with the pope and
King Moshoeshoe II. They said they were fighting to end military
rule in Lesotho.
   John Paul, touring southern Africa, left Lesotho Friday after a
36-hour stay marred by the hijacking and bad weather.
   Lesotho is surrounded by South Africa, and a special South
African police unit was asked to help deal with the hijackers.
Witnesses said Lesotho security forces took away the hijacker who
died later.
