<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AdoptedHeir     09-16 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Adopted Heir,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heir To German Castle Finds There Is A Catch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FERRYSBURG, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A businessman recently adopted by a
German baron has a kingsize worry: a $3 million mortgage that he
must repay by next month to keep a bank from seizing the family
castle.
   Richard Hemmelsbach, however, is confident that his plans to
turn the 1,428-year-old, 100-bedroom castle into a hotel will go
forward before the bank acts.
   ``We need to keep the castle in the family; that's where it
belongs,'' said Hemmelsbach, the owner of two small marketing
companies here.
   Hemmelsbach was adopted last month by the Baron Freiherr
Theodore von Liebieg after the heirless baron conducted a
nationwide search for an heir on the syndicated television show ``A
Current Affair.''
   The Hemmelsbach family and the baron's family had known each
other 40 years ago, after World War II, and the baron recognized
Hemmelsbach's name from among about 10,000 people who wrote asking
to inherit the castle.
   The new Baron Richard James von Liebieg Hemmelsbach said Friday
he is negotiating with a major U.S. hotel chain interested in
renovating a portion of the castle and turning it into a
first-class hotel, and he is confident a deal with the company
would secure the $3 million.
   If Hemmelsbach does not pay off the $3 million by Oct. 15, the
bank holding the mortgage will offer the estate to other parties
who have already expressed interest in buying it.
   ``We need to keep the castle in the family; that's where it
belongs,'' Hemmelsbach said.
   Von Liebieg, who lives about 15 miles from the castle, began his
search for an heir to maintain the deteriorating estate after the
bank recently repossessed it from a German businessman to whom von
Liebieg sold the castle 15 years ago.
   The businessman also had planned to turn the castle into a
hotel, but financial troubles forced him to abandon his plans,
Hemmelsbach said.
   The castle, reportedly the oldest in Germany, is located on the
banks of the Mosel River at the base of the Eifel mountains.
   Hemmelsbach would not name the company interested in developing
the property, but said several others and a group of investors were
waiting in the wings if the deal falls through. He said he believed
it would cost between $9 million and $12 million to renovate the
castle, which sits on 100 acres. He said the castle, accompanying
estate and vineyards are worth $10 million.
   Meanwhile, he is selling one of his marketing companies so he
can devote his time to raising funds and expect to make his third
trip to the castle within three weeks.
   ``It was love at first sight,'' Hemmelsbach said of the estate.
</TEXT>
