<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomelessEducation     09-16 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Education,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Says Communities Must Educate Homeless Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Education Department says communities
are responsible for the education of children living within their
boundaries, even if they live in temporary shelters, state parks or
other temporary situations.
   The policy was issued Thursday after the Hingham School
Department refused to allow four children in a family living
temporarily in tents in Wompatuck State Park to attend Hingham
schools.
   Hingham School Superintendent Lewis J. Ernst had said the park
was considered to be under state jurisdiction and that town
taxpayers support school districts. Hingham is about 10 miles of
Boston on Hingham Bay.
   The children have been going to school this month in nearby
Norwell, where the school committee voted unanimously to let them
attend school without paying out-of-town tuition.
   State Education Commissioner Harold Raynolds Jr. said in a
statement that the law entitles all children to attend the public
schools in the towns in which they live.
   ``That law applies to children irrespective of their living
situation, whether they live with parents or other relatives in
foster homes or in temporary shelters or motels because they have
been displaced from their homes,'' he said.
   Edward Melikian, spokesman for the Education Department, said it
is up to John and Kitty Montgomery, who are living with five
children, four of school age, in three tents in the state park, to
decide whether to transfer the children from Norwell to Hingham
schools.
   The parents said they would like to keep the children in Norwell
schools.
   ``Norwell has been so incredibly gracious with our kids,'' said
Montgomery. The Montgomerys moved from Tucson, Ariz., in late
August to be near Mrs. Montgomery's father. While Montgomery has
found a job, and his wife also hopes to work, they have not found
affordable housing.
</TEXT>
