<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NRC-SeabrookReax     09-16 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NRC-Seabrook Reax,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seabrook Officials Start Low-Power Preparations</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Seabrook License</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MOKRZYCKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seabrook nuclear power plant officials
said Friday that preparations for low-power testing will begin
immediately following a Nuclear Regulatory Commission vote to clear
a major obstacle toward a license.
   But opponents declared the fight to stop Seabrook from operating
is far from over.
   At a news conference, Edward Brown, president of New Hampshire
Yankee, hailed Friday's NRC action as ``another major step forward
for Seabrook.''
   He said Seabrook will require about five weeks of preparation
before the plant would be ready to begin testing at 5 percent
power. Actual issuance of the license could take another four
weeks, and atomic tests could begin two weeks after that, he
estimated.
   The NRC, by a 4-0 vote, approved a rule change that emergency
sirens do not have to be in place before low-power testing begins,
but the commission left open the question of whether Seabrook's
owners are financially qualified to conduct the tests.
   ``I'll say without absolutely no qualification whatsoever there
is no hazard to public safety from low-power testing _ absolutely
none,'' Brown said in regard to the NRC decision to allow the
testing without sirens.
   Opponents, however, denounced the NRC vote as weakening
protections to the public.
   ``The decision again shows the Reagan-Bush administration is so
blindly committed to getting Seabrook on line that public
protection doesn't matter,'' said Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass.
   ``The administration has placed the short-term economic
interests of one utility ahead of the long-term health and safety
of citizens living around the plant. Its goal is to get this plant
plugged in and turned on before Nov. 8 so that no one can turn it
off later.''
   Brown denied there was a connection between Seabrook's plans and
the November election, saying the timing is ``pure coincidence.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, the Democratic
presidential nominee, has been a longtime opponent of Seabrook. He
denounced the latest decision in a prepared statement saying, ``The
NRC _ the Not Responsible Commission _ is experiencing a meltdown
in its thinking process.''
   Regarding Seabrook's finances, Brown predicted that a final
agreement will be in place within several weeks to cover payments
being skipped by the owner of the fourth largest Seabrook share,
Massachusetts Municipal Wholesale Electric Co.
   Brown also said he doubts that the bankruptcy judge overseeing
Public Service's reorganization would block low-power testing once
he ``hears the facts on low-power and not the myths.''
   However, Tom Moughan, of Citizens Within The 10-Mile Radius,
said NRC's decision to deal with financial questions later means
the fight isn't over.
   ``We think the public needs to understand that the full-power
(license) possibilities are distant still,'' he said.
</TEXT>
