<HEAD>Martin Sheen Calls Off Dukakis Protest After Hayden Intervenes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Sheen called off a protest Thursday
aimed at Michael Dukakis after state Assemblyman Tom Hayden
intervened and arranged a meeting between the actor-activist and
the candidate over his stand on a grape boycott.
   The Massachusetts governor was in town to attend a fund-raiser
and a celebrity summit at the home of television producer Norman
Lear.
   A spokeswoman for Sheen, who supports the United Farm Workers'
protest of allegedly dangerous pesticides on California grapes,
called local news agencies more than four hours ahead of time to
announce the protest outside Lear's house.
   Valerie Sklarevsky, the spokeswoman, said Sheen and UFW members
and supporters wanted Dukakis to clarify his stance on the grape
boycott and would be picketing.
   About an hour later, Ms. Sklarevsky called back and said the
protest was called off because Hayden talked to Sheen and arranged
a private meeting with the actor and Dukakis.
   ``He (Sheen) was told it wouldn't look good,'' Ms. Sklarevsky
said.
   Actress Morgan Fairchild said Thursday the celebrities attending
the political pow-wow would discuss strategies on getting their
candidate elected president and what they could do to help.
   Don Johnson, Gregory Peck, Chevy Chase, Goldie Hawn, Ally
Sheedy, Rob Lowe and Burgess Meredith were expected to attend, said
Dee Dee Myers, a Dukakis spokeswoman.
   ``These are people who want to get out and work for Mike
Dukakis; roll up their sleeves and get Michael Dukakis and Lloyd
Bentsen elected,'' Ms. Myers said.
