<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0676 09-16 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0676,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Vows `No Safe Haven' for Drug Traffickers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with demonstrators, INSERT two grafs after 8th pvs,
``You're the ... Dukakis said, picking up 9th pvs, Dukakis
said...Southern California; ADDS six grafs to UPDATE with
appearance at high school in East Los Angeles.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic candidate Michael Dukakis promised
Friday to double the number of drug enforcement agents and vowed
``there will be no safe haven for dope peddlers and drug profits
anywhere on this earth.''
   The Massachusetts governor delivered a tough anti-crime speech
during an appearance at the Los Angeles Police Academy, where he
observed a training exercise on a simulated city street called
Hogan's Alley.
   While Dukakis stood a few feet away, Officer Jerry Mulford
demonstrated ``cover and concealment'' tactics, ducking behind
wooden boxes and a brick wall and fired at various moving and
pop-up targets.
   Trainees usually use live ammunition in such exercises, but the
Secret Service vetoed the practice during Dukakis' visit.
   In his speech, Dukakis told police recruits that the Reagan
administration was trying to ``nickel and dime you to death'' by
cutting funds for drug enforcement.
   ``We're going to give the state and local law enforcement
officers the money they need to fight this war,'' he said.
   ``You're the ones who take the risks, you're the ones who make
the busts, you're the ones who bear the costs of this war and you
deserve the best equipment and the best communications and the best
training we can give you,'' Dukakis said.
   In a later appearance at a Chula Vista, Calif., police station,
Dukakis was greeted by demonstrators who needled the Massachusetts
governor for his since-modified prison furlough policy and for his
veto on constitutial grounds of a bill requiring teachers to lead
students in the Pledge of Allegiance.
   One group wore mock prison uniforms and chanted, ``Let me out,
I'll kill again,'' and another carried pro-George Bush signs and
recited the pledge.
   Dukakis said at the police academy he would double the number of
Drug Enforcement Administration efforts over the next five years
and added, ``We're going to send the first 100 of those new agents
here to South California.''
   He said the cost of the new agents would be more than covered by
the increased revenue in seized drug profits.
   Dukakis aides quoted DEA estimates that each agent seized an
average of $259,000 in drug profits in 1987, more than double what
it cost to keep them in the field.
   Dukakis also pledged to hire 800 more federal prosecutors and to
``wage an all-out effort to hunt down, to freeze and to seize drug
profits wherever we can find them.''
   ``We're going to send a message to drug kingpins,'' he said.
``As far as Mike Dukakis is concerned, there's nowhere you can run,
there's nowhere you can sail, there's nowhere you can hide. There
will be no safe haven for dope peddlers and drug profits anywhere
on this earth.''
   Republican presidential nominee George Bush has criticized
Dukakis for his refusal to endorse Bush's proposal for imposing the
death penalty on drug kingpins.
   Dukakis continued his drug war theme during a Mexican
Independence Day celebration at Roosevelt High School in East Los
Angeles, an area with a large Mexican-American population.
   There he told students that under the Reagan administration ``at
one point, it got so bad, that agents of the Drug Enforcement
Administration had to have a bake sale to raise money to finance
drug stakeout operations.''
   However, aides said afterword that the bake sale, described in a
book by Elaine Shannon entitled ``Desperado,'' was to raise money
for drug education programs.
   ``We need a president in this country who will make a difference
and not excuses,'' he told a cheering crowd composed mostly of
students.
   ``I hope many of you will become the future political leaders of
this country,'' he said.
   Hispanics make up 23 percent of the population of California,
but only 8 percent of the registered voters.
</TEXT>
