<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PoisonGas     09-16 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Poison Gas,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Rejects Bid To Investigate Alleged Use Of Poison Gas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Friday refused to receive a U.N.
team to investigate allegations that it used outlawed poison gas
against its Kurdish minority.
   Acting Ambassador Ali Mahmoud Sumaida delivered the Iraqi
government's formal rejection Friday night to U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar.
   ``The response was negative,'' Sumaida told reporters after his
meeting. ``We declined to receive such a mission because there is
no basis for evidence (for such a mission).''
   He said that reports by a Turkish team of experts and the
Turkish Red Crescent _ Turkey's equivalent of the Red Cross _ did
not provide sufficient evidence to warrant dispatching a team of
investigators.
   At least a dozen nations, including the United States, Britain
and Nordic countries had urged the secretary-general to send a team
to investigate the charges that Iraq was using chemical warfare
against Kurdish rebels.
   Iraq has said, however, that foreign journalists were welcome to
investigate although the United Nations was not welcome.
   No immediate response came from the secretary-general. The
United Nations is circumspect when the soveignty of a member is
involved, however, and it is unlikely the world organization would
consider sending an investigatory team lacking cooperation by the
host country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
