<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFiresRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0824 09-16 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0824,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Pick Up In Yellowstone; Continue In Other Western States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Friday weather, SUB 6th graf, `Forecasts for
..., and to UPDATE with arrival of Marines, SUB 10 graf, `And 700
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fires in Yellowstone
National Park picked up again Friday, but fire officials were
confident moisture from storms last weekend and work since then
would prevent the fires from growing.
   ``This week, I think they're fairly confident, with the measures
they've taken during the early part of this week, that they'll be
able to hold the fires,'' said fire information officer Linda
Miller. ``I think they're fairly confident that they won't have any
major problems.''
   The fires, which now form one huge blaze, have affected 1.1
million acres of the 2.2 million-acre park. But according to new
infrared scans, they have burned only about 50 percent to 60
percent of the land within fire perimeters.
   Park officials said the fires remained inside fire perimeters
Friday.
   ``I don't think anything slopped over any lines,'' said park
spokeswoman Sonya Capek.
   Temperatures in the park only reached the mid-60s and steady
winds approached 35 mph. The weather forecast offered some good
news for Saturday, with a chance of light snowshowers in the
afternoon and temperatures in the 50s. The storm also could bring
some heavy winds, but Capek said the high humidity and cold
temperatures will keep the fires down.
   Firefighters had taken advantage of the wet, cold weather
earlier in the week to strengthen existing lines around fires and
extend lines and by Friday had contained 50 percent of the
335,500-acre North Fork fire, the most troublesome of the blazes in
the park.
   Blazes also burned Friday in Montana, Idaho, Oregon and
Washington state as the worst fire season in 30 years continued.
More than 4 million acres, including 2.1 million acres in Alaska,
have gone up in smoke.
   Denny Bungarz, North Fork fire incident commander, said
officials believe it would take seven days of continued dry weather
before Yellowstone would return to the tinder-dry conditions that
allowed fires to grow by thousands of acres daily.
   And 700 Marines from Camp Pendleton in California reached the
park Friday to help with firefighting efforts, bringing the
military force in the country's first national park to 4,100.
   Thirty Canadian firefighters arrived Friday, the first Canadian
crew to arrive since the U.S. Forest Service accepted that
country's offer to help.
   Firefighters had contained 70 percent of the 413,380-acre Clover
Mist fire in the park's northeastern corner. That leaves the Wolf
Lake fire, on the northeast edge of the North Fork, as the only
fire where containment figures were below 50 percent. Firefighters
had contained 8 percent of that blaze.
   To the south, officials in the Bridger-Teton National Forest
declared the 225,500-acre Huck-Mink complex of fires fully
contained.
   Wildfires continued to burn in most of Idaho's national forests
Friday, and fire bosses welcomed a weekend forecast of cooler,
wetter weather.
   ``I don't know if we're over the hump as far as the fire season
goes, but we've been saying we're guardedly optimistic,'' said
Sandi Sacher, an information officer at the Boise Interagency Fire
Center.
   Fires that so far had consumed more than 190,000 acres remained
out of control and outside wilderness boundaries in the Nez Perce,
Challis, Panhandle and Salmon national forests, Ms. Sacher said.
   Restrictions on the use of several national forests in western
Montana were lifted Friday.
   ``We had enough moisture (so that) we dropped down to a
moderate'' fire danger, said Bob Krepps of the Forest Service.
   Meanwhile, a fire in Glacier National Park had grown about 2,000
acres by Friday, and in west-central Montana hundreds of soldiers
helped crews mop up the 247,000-acre Canyon Creek blaze.
</TEXT>
