<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Olympics 2ndLd-Writethru a0836 09-16 0910</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Olympics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0836,0934</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seoul Olympic Games Begin In Blaze of Pageantry</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 23 grafs SUB for grafs 8-26 pvs, On Friday ... UPDATING with
new material on parade, other doings. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 Summer Olympics, the largest
and most tightly guarded in history, began in a blaze of pageantry
Saturday as marchers in traditional Korean costumes entered the
main stadium to the beat of a ``dragon drum.''
   About 70,000 spectators in the Olympic Stadium and up to a
billion television viewers around the world watched the spectacular
show that began at 10:30 a.m. (8:30 p.m. EDT Friday) in sunny
weather.
   It was the first Olympic opening ceremony with a prelude outside
the main stadium. Before the performances in the Olylmpic Stadium,
a flotilla of 458 boats sailed by on the Han River adjacent to the
stadium.
   The theme of the three-hour extravaganza, with 13,000
performers, was ``Beyond All Barriers'' _ a phrase stressing the
Seoul Games as a stage for the first East-West competitions at the
Summer Olympics in 12 years.
   Political boycotts had marred the 1980 Moscow Games and the Los
Angeles competition four years ago.
   About 160 countries sent nearly 10,000 athletes to the Games to
compete for 237 gold medals, making these 16-day Games the
best-attended ever by competitors.
   South Korean security forces ringing the stadium and on alert
across the nation were on guard against terrorism. Officals called
the measures the most extensive ever to protect a sports event.
   Greece led the parade of teams, a tradition honoring the country
as the site of the ancient Olympics.
   Teams marched according to the Korean alphabet, with Ghana
second in the procession. As the host nation, South Korea was last.
   Most teams were garbed in matching jackets and pants or skirts,
but African delegations wore native garb of flowing robes with
colorful print patterns.
   The processions seemed less formal than at past Olympics opening
ceremonies. Some teams broke ranks to wave to the cheering crowd.
An American athlete carried a sign proclaiming, ``Hi, Mom, I'm
Here.''
   The teams gathered on the infield after circling the running
track. The march route took them past the seating area for
dignitaries, including South Korean President Roh Tae-woo and Juan
Antonio Samaranch, president of the International Olympic Committee.
   Before the teams marched in, a chorus sang an ancient seafaring
ballad, and thousands of blue and white balloons floated skyward. A
replica of the huge dragon drum used in ancient Korean ceremonies
was transfered from ship to shore then carried to the stadium.
   Huge balloons were released from a Shindan Tree, sacred in
Korean mythology, and then the Olympic flame was revealed on a
72-foot pedestal resembling a traditional Korean candleholder.
   Korean dancers in Greek tunics and flowing gowns danced and
whirled as silver-colored confetti rained down from the sky.
   ``I believe God is blessing my country for its years of hard
work and preparation,'' said Yuk Hee-Jin, 17, a spectator. ``I'm
really proud of my country. The whole world will now know more
about Korea.''
   The opening ceremonies, as conceived, planned, practiced and
practiced again, were designed by the Games' hosts to portray the
Eastern philosophies of harmony and balance _ factors long-wanting
in Korea's tumultuous history.
   Planners drew from the concept of Yin and Yang, the symbol on
the Korean flag that is also a major Oriental philosophy. Yin and
Yang represent opposing forces that come together in a bond of
harmony and friendship.
   So the script for the Olympic opener mixed the Yin of the old
and the Yang of the new.
   Music for the show came from ancient Korean drums and wind
instruments as well as a synthesizer that pumped out modern pieces
composed by contemporary Korean artists.
   The Koreans invited dancers from 60 nations to participate in
the program of native dances from Hungary, Peru, Senegal, Saudi
Arabia, the United States and other nations.
   Music to accompany the marchers was composed from folk music of
the various nations.
   The Koreans also sought to keep harmony among the nations
marching in the opening ceremony. Plans to limit the number in the
process were quickly scrapped after protests from several
countries, including the United States.
   And while the program called for women in flowing white robes to
march in front of the delegations carrying signs with each nation's
name, Iran was granted its wish that a man front their team because
of the Moslem nation's strict fundamentalist tenets that forbid
women from such public displays.
   On Friday, a runner carried the Olympic torch to City Hall in a
snowstorm of confetti, streamers and balloons.
   The torch relay began Aug. 23 in Olympia, Greece, site of the
ancient Olympics.
   Elsewhere in the capital, hundreds of radicals staged
anti-Olympic protests at three universities Friday. They burned the
U.S. flag and an effigy of President Reagan and yelled ``Down with
the dictators' Olympics!'' Onlookers shouted at them as riot police
watched from a distance.
   In the protests, radicals, some of them armed with firebombs and
clubs, demanded the Olympics be shared with communist North Korea
and charged the Games were being used to cement authoritarian rule
in South Korea.
   North Korea declared again Friday that the Seoul government is
using the Games to further divide the Korean peninsula.
   The two Koreas have been divided since the end of World War II
and fought the Korean War in 1950-53.
</TEXT>
