<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Friday he is ready to
study Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's proposal for a mutual
superpower base-closing in the Pacific, but said the United States
should proceed cautiously.
   Making clear that ``I haven't had an opportunity to go into it
in detail,'' Reagan told reporters he remains interested in doing
``anything we can'' to improve U.S.-Soviet relations.
   But in an allusion to how people sometimes get cheated at
card-playing, he said, ``As I have frequently said to him
(Gorbachev), `Trust everybody, but cut the cards.'''
