<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Norway-SealKillers ADV22   09-16 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Norway-Seal Killers, ADV 22,0760</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs Sept. 22 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Norwegians in Dispute over Report that Seals are Skinned Alive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHAN RAPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A report that some hunters are skinning
seals alive has touched off a bitter dispute in Norway, where
hunters and fishermen say seal killing is crucial to their way of
life.
   Odd F. Lindberg, an author and photographer who sailed as a
government-appointed inspector on a hunting boat east of Greenland
last spring, said in his report that seals were not only skinned
alive but killed in deliberately ``sadistical ways.''
   The report came as authorities sought to ease controls on seal
killing, because fisherman complain that thousands of the animals
have invaded Norway's northern coast, eating fish and damaging nets.
   ``Since my report I have received at least 100 telephone
threats, with some saying they are going to tear my limbs off,''
said Lindberg.
   The Ministry of Fisheries, which employed Lindberg to do the
inspection, refuses to accept his report.
   ``It may be that he (Lindberg) believes he has seen things that
he has not seen,'' said Trond S. Paulsen, a senior ministry
official. The ministry has no plans to take action on his report,
he said.
   But the report drew widespread sympathy for seals following a
summer of death for the animals further south. A distemper virus
killed 13,000 seals along the coasts of Denmark, Norway, Sweden,
the Netherlands and West Germany since April.
   Norway's leading newspaper, Aftenposten, devoted its front page
to a color picture it said was taken by Lindberg of a seal pup in
the water being clubbed with the blunt side of a long spiked pole.
   Killing pups in the water is prohibited, and it would appear
from the photo that the hunter had apparently missed a clean kill
on the head.
   In the 1970s, the French actress Birgitte Bardot, Greenpeace and
other environmental organizations successfully campaigned against
seal slaughter here and in Canada.
   Their campaign led to a 1983 ban by the European Economic
Community on imports of seal skins, a heavy blow to the seal
hunters whose main market was the European fur industry.
   After the EEC import ban, the Canadian government banned the
killing of seal pups, which are coveted for their white coats.
   Norway's seal hunting fleet dwindled from about 50 vessels to
five and the catch was cut from several hundred thousand seals a
year to a quota of less than 40,000.
   However, disgruntled seal hunters now see the chance for a
comeback.
   Later this year, the EEC will start talks on the possibilities
of either lifting the ban or making it permanent. A decision is
expected next year.
   Last year's seal invasion softened public opinion in Norway.
Fishermen complained they could lose their livelihoods if the seals
were allowed to continue to eat their catch and destroy their nets.
   ``We count on the import ban being changed,'' said spokesman Jan
Lauritson at the Ministry of Fisheries. ``There are no logical,
scientific grounds for it.''
   Norway hunts seals during the spring in waters east of Greenland
and in the Barents Sea, north of the Soviet Union.
   Lindberg was one of three inspectors assigned this year to make
sure the killings were carried out according to detailed rules,
intended to minimize the animals' suffering. He spent from
mid-March to mid-April aboard a seal hunt vessel off Greenland.
   Lindberg said he turned in his report to the Ministry of
Fisheries at the beginning of July and that it created ``panic.''
   ``The animals are rarely checked to see if they have been
fatally shot,'' the report said, ``and are often alive when they
are hoisted aboard. As a result it often happens that the animal is
skinned while growling, its eyes pleading and its mouth snapping at
you.''
   He said he had seen animals that appeared to be dead but ``woke
up'' while being skinned.
   Before releasing Lindberg's report Sept. 2, the ministry issued
a statement saying a committee of experts had found Lindberg ``not
trustworthy.''
   Other inspectors made no such complaints, said Paulsen.
   Officials said no formal qualifications are needed to be an
inspector, but that they usually employ biologists, students and
researchers. They said Lindberg had offered to do the job without
pay.
   Lindberg, 43, has specialized in conditions for marine mammals
in polar areas.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Sept. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
