<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Military, ADV 23,0820</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs Sept. 23 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Nationalist Chinese Military Assailed as Too Powerful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nationalist Chinese military, long the
backbone of the government, is under attack by critics who contend
it remains too powerful at a time of easing tensions with rival
communist China.
   Emboldened by the relaxed political atmosphere on Taiwan after
nearly four decades of authoritarian rule, some Taiwanese claim the
military abuses its power despite the lifting of martial law here a
year ago.
   Newspapers, which customarily hushed up any allegations of
military wrongdoing in the past, now give wide coverage to the
charges of abuses.
   The Nationalist government and armed forces led by Chiang
Kai-shek fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a civil war to the
communists on the mainland and remain technically at war with
Beijing.
   China still regards Taiwan as a renegade province but has not
launched a significant military action since 1958, when communist
forces fired hundreds of thousands of artillery shells at two tiny
Nationalist-held offshore islands, Quemoy and Matsu.
   ``Soldiers used to be admired for defending the country with
their lives,'' said legislator Chang Shih-liang of the governing
Nationalist Party. ``But with the absence of wars for so long,
people began to question what they have been doing.''
   A central figure in the controversy is Taiwan's only four-star
general, Hau Pei-tsun, head of the general chiefs of staff since
1981 and one of those who came to Taiwan after the communists won
the mainland in 1949.
   Hau, who commands Taiwan's half a million troops, was praised
for ensuring a peaceful transfer of power after the death in
January of President Chiang Ching-kuo, the son of Chiang Kai-shek,
who lifted martial law despite his strong ties to the military.
   But critics argue that Chiang Ching-Kuo's successor, Lee
Teng-hui, has little control over the armed forces, which are
allocated an estimated 46 percent of Taiwan's annual budget of
nearly $20 billion.
   ``No military officers dared to give an order without the prior
approval from Chiang Ching-kuo, but it appears no one can control
them now,'' said Chang Chung-tung, history professor at National
Taiwan University.
   Lee, a native Taiwanese, has yet to build up his own power base
in the Nationalist military that remains dominated by officers who
came from mainland China. That also has led to speculation that
Hau's influence is growing.
   Some liberal newspapers and magazines recently criticized Hau on
grounds that he promoted several of his own men, including two
generals demoted by Chiang Ching-kuo for dereliction of duty.
   Newspapers also have suggested that Hau played an influential
role in crafting the Nationalist party's new policy-making Central
Standing Committee that was named in July. The military retained
three of 31 committee seats, including one held by Hau.
   Opposition politicians have assailed the armed forces for their
role in trying to crack down on dissent, claiming military police
and intelligence agents have appeared at major anti-government
demonstrations where only a police presence was appropriate.
   In August, several dozen members of the opposition Democratic
Progressive Party staged a protest in Taipei to demand the
impeachment of Hau because a military jail burned the memoirs of a
renowned dissident prisoner.
   The liberal Independence Evening Post said in an editorial July
27 that with the lifting of martial law ``we thought military
personnel would reduce their role to that of defending the state
and civilians.''
   ``Rather, we saw the military openly intervening in political
factional disputes, continuing to have a hand in social and
economic affairs and having too much say in government personnel
changes,'' it said.
   A Defense Ministry spokesman, Maj. Gen. Chang Hui-yuan, called
the newspaper's accusations ``malicious slandering'' and ``an
insult to our troops.''
   To counter the intense criticism, the military has launched a
campaign to stress the importance of national defense in speeches
and through concerts, plays and television shows, including one
showing the 69-year-old Hau swimming, golfing and playing with his
grandson.
   In a speech marking Soldiers' Day on Sept. 3, Hau urged
Taiwanese ``not to reduce the sense of crisis while living in
comfort,'' claiming that communist China still could invade Taiwan
at any time.
   Professor Chang reflects widespread sentiment when he labels as
unlikely the possibility of a military coup or a military-led
campaign to reverse the recent liberalization trend that has
permitted political opposition and relaxed unofficial ties with
China.
   ``Military officers must have realized that the public would not
support them in case of a coup,'' he said. ``They must also ask
whether they could control the troops before moving to seize
power.''
   Most of the troops are native Taiwanese, who make up 85 percent
of the island's population.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Sept. 23</NOTE>
