<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Launch Decision, Adv19,1089</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Sept 19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Decision on Blast-off Will Come Down to One Man: Crippen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Discovery's countdown clock
reaches the 9-minute mark on launch day, it will stop automatically
and be held there for 10 minutes while one man decides whether to
give the final go-ahead for liftoff.
   He will look to many experts, analyzing every scrap of
information, for help. They will report on the condition of the
shuttle and its thousands of complex parts, the state of the
weather overhead and at prime and emergency landing sites around
the globe, the readiness of the launch and flight control teams to
support the mission.
   Before the 10 minutes is up, he will say go or no-go.
   It is a new and awesome responsibility, a product of the
Challenger disaster, and it lies with Robert L. Crippen, a
50-year-old Navy captain and an astronaut who has gone into space
more often on the shuttle than any other person. He piloted the
first launch in 1981 and has commanded three other flights.
   His fellow astronauts are delighted to have one of their own
calling that critical shot.
   Rick Hauck, another Navy captain, who will command Discovery on
the first shuttle mission since Challenger, said, ``I flew my first
mission with him in 1983, and I can't think of anyone who is reverse transcriptase,
an enzyme the AIDS virus uses
to replicate itself and spread through the body.
   The experiment to grow crystals of the AIDS protein was
developed by researchers at Burroughs Wellcome in Research Triangle
Park, N.C., and NASA officials determined it was safe to fly on the
shuttle.
   Another experiment involves taking photographs and video of
lightning at night to study relationships between it and other
elements such as thunderstorms. Such research may one day lead to
better weather forecasting.
   ``The altitude we fly at gives you kind of a unique perspective.
We get a very broad view of thunderstorms. We can see a third of a
continent's worth of thunderstorms. It's spectacular,'' Nelson said.
   Astronauts also will photograph the sky immediately after sunset
and after sunrise to measure the brightness of Earth's atmosphere
at those times. The information can be used to build sensors for
future unmanned satellites, Nelson said.
   The five other experiments consist of two separation processes
and three basic research projects that include examining how metal
melts and resolidifies in zero gravity, mixing immiscible fluids
and watching them separate and studying how blood flows and
collects in weightlessness.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon Sept. 19</NOTE>
