<2ND_LINE>PM-Shuttle-Personnel Changes, Adv19,0789</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Sept 19 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Accident Led to Many Changes in Ranks at NASA; Astronauts Now in
Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Almost all the men who ignored the warnings
and gave the go-ahead for the Challenger launch are gone and new
ones are in place as the shuttle program returns to flight.
   One shuttle astronaut, Richard Truly, now is at the helm of
NASA's spaceflight program. Another, Robert Crippen _ who has been
on four shuttle missions _ will give the final nod to commit
Discovery and other future shuttles to flight.
   The top officials of Morton Thiokol, which built the booster
rocket that doomed the Challenger, are gone. Gone, too, is most of
the NASA hierarchy, and gone are the directors of NASA centers
investigated by the presidential Challenger commission.
   There are two notable exceptions: Arnold Aldrich, one of the
NASA bosses who gave final approval for the Jan. 28, 1986, flight,
and Allan J. McDonald, a Morton Thiokol engineer who argued against
the launch but was overruled. Aldrich is director of the shuttle
program at NASA headquarters and McDonald is in charge of Thiokol's
space operations.
   The Rogers commission presented its conclusion that Challenger
``was an accident rooted in history,'' but it did not recommend any
criminal indictment. Still, Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C.
demanded that ``every single person be identified and disciplined.''
   That seems to have been done without resorting to the courts.
   Lawrence B. Mulloy, former manager of the booster rocket program
at the Marshall Space Flight Center who had brushed off the Thiokol
concerns, and Stanley Reinartz, manager of shuttle projects who
decided not to tell top launch officials about those concerns, both
left NASA. So has George B. Hardy, the Marshall official who told
Thiokol he was ``appalled'' at the firm's original recommendation
that the launch should not take place.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration was working
without its chief on the day of the tragedy, and the man with the
title of acting administrator was new to the agency.
   Administrator James M. Beggs had stepped aside in early December
1985 when he was indicted on charges unrelated to NASA. Dr. William
R. Graham, who had been deputy administrator for only 10 days when
Beggs stepped out, had to take the heat for the worst tragedy in
America's space program.
   After Challenger, Beggs resigned and Graham remained as acting
administrator until Dr. James C. Fletcher returned in May 1986 from
private life and reassumed the job of administrator he had held for
eight years in the 1970s.
   ``Where management is weak, we will strengthen it,'' he
promised. ``Where engineering or design processes need improving,
we will improve it. Where our internal communications are poor, we
will see that they get better.''
   The purge had begun much earlier.
   The first to step down after Challenger was Jesse Moore,
assistant NASA administrator for spaceflight, who had already been
named to take over as director of the Johnson Space Center in
Houston. Truly was summoned from the U.S. Navy Space Command to
take charge; he proclaimed ``the NASA can-do spirit is intact'' and
quickly set out a conservative agenda to get back into the
spaceflight business.
   In the NASA structure, center directors wield considerable power
and those directly concerned with shuttle flight were quick to fall.
   Moore remained at Johnson only a few months and left to take an
ill-defined headquarters job that lasted six months. Richard Smith
left the Kennedy Space Center for a private space firm. Dr. William
Lucas retired from the Marshall Space Flight Center, which has
charge of NASA propulsion systems and received the most criticism
from the Rogers commission.
   NASA went to the Air Force for Lt. Gen. Forrest S. McCartney to
head the Kennedy Space Center. At Johnson, Aaron Cohen was moved up
and Marshall got J. R. Thompson, a veteran space engineer, who came
back to NASA from Princeton's Plasma Physics Laboratory.
   Three of the four Thiokol officials who overruled their
engineers and acceded to the Challenger launch still are with the
company but in non-shuttle positions. They are J.C. Kilminster, now
in the automotive products division, R.K. Lund, vice president of
advanced technology; and Calvin Wiggins, general manager of the
Huntsville division. Jerald E. Mason, boss of the booster division,
retired early.
   Roger Boisjoly, a Thiokol engineer, said the company harassed
him for his strong testimony before the Rogers commission and sued
Thiokol for billions of dollars. The case was dismissed and he has
left the company long ago.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon Sept. 1</NOTE>
