<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-16 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0574</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retail sales declined in August for only the
second time this year, the government has reported, indicating to
analysts that inflationary pressures are easing.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that sales fell by 0.2
percent last month to $133.5 billion.
   Economists have been worried since the spring that rising export
sales coupled with strong demand from U.S. consumers would put too
much strain on the economy and fuel inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. industrial operating rate rose for
the fifth consecutive month in August, the Federal Reserve Board
says.
   Economists played down the inflationary effect of the increase
announced Thursday because it stemmed entirely from a temporary
summer surge at utilities.
   The Fed said the nation's factories, mines and utilities
operated at 83.7 percent of capacity last month, a 0.1 percentage
point increase over July.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Management officials at Hospital Corp.
of America are trying to line up financing for a $3.3 billion
buyout of the company, one of the world's biggest hospital chains.
   The company said Thursday that a group of managers had advised
the board of directors about its intended proposal of $47 a share
in cash for HCA's 70.6 million shares outstanding.
   HCA said Chairman Thomas F. Frist Jr. plans to negotiate with
unidentified third parties to obtain financing for the proposal,
known as a leveraged buyout.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROCKY HILL, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ames Department Stores Inc. said it has
agreed to buy Zayre Corp.'s 388-unit discount store division in a
deal it valued at about $800 million.
   Peter Hollis, Ames' president and chief executive officer, said
Thursday that the deal would double the number of discount stores
that Ames operates, and lift Ames to third place from fifth among
the nation's largest discount retailers.
   Ames operates 348 discount stores, primarily in small towns in
18 states in the Northeast and mid-Atlantic regions. Zayre discount
stores are in 26 states and the District of Columbia.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British publisher Robert Maxwell has raised his
offer for Macmillan Inc. to $2.41 billion in cash, a surprise move
to counter a $2.36 billion deal for the U.S. publishing giant made
by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. earlier this
week.
   Maxwell, who previously offered $84 for each of the company's
27.76 million shares, said Thursday he now was willing to pay
$86.80. He also offered to pay the company's recently declared
20-cent quarterly dividend.
   As an alternative, Maxwell said, his Sept. 8 offer to purchase
11 Macmillan information businesses for $1.4 billion still was good.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Brands Inc. says it has
received and rebuffed a buyout proposal from an investor group led
by financier Bennett LeBow, who alternatively requested a chance to
buy the company's tobacco businesses.
   American Brands said late Thursday the group had filed for
federal antitrust clearance to acquire more than $15 million worth
of the company's stock, and might acquire more than 50 percent of
American Brands' outstanding shares.
   LeBow indicated he wanted to discuss a negotiated, cash buyout
of American Brands at a ``significant premium'' to the market price.
   American Brands closed at $48.37{ a share Thursday, down 37{
cents in New York Stock Exchange trading.
</TEXT>
