<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   09-16 0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0563</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The congressional watchdog agency added as
much as $14 billion to its estimate of the cost of bailing out the
savings industry and said regulators lack the money to do it.
   Frederick D. Wolf, director of the finance division of the
General Accounting Office, said Thursday he now estimates the cost
of eliminating insolvent S&Ls at $45 billion to $50 billion, up
from the $26 billion to $36 billion cost estimated by the agency in
May.
   Estimates of private analysts go to $80 billion and higher.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Credit-repair clinics that promise consumers
they will have derogatory information removed from an individual's
credit file for a fee are a ``sham,'' a congressional subcommittee
was told.
   Walter R. Kurth, president of Associated Credit Bureaus Inc.,
told the House Banking consumer affairs subcommittee Thursday that
the individual consumer can do anything the credit-repair clinics
can.
   Under the law, individuals who feel their credit records have
inaccuracies can go directly to a local credit bureau and ask that
they be corrected.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of the proposed partial merger of
two Detroit newspapers have asked an appeals court to delay the
business arrangement until the courts can hold a full hearing on
the issue.
   The appeal was filed Thursday in U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia Circuit by Michigan Citizens for an
Independent Press, said John Kelly, a Michigan state senator from
Detroit.
   Kelly has led the effort by newspaper readers and advertisers to
block a joint operating agreement between the Detroit Free Press
and the Detroit News under an exception to federal antitrust laws.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A playful bit of English tradition has gone on the
auction block, with the proposed sale of Hamleys of Regent Street,
one of the world's oldest, biggest and most famous toy stores.
   The store's owners on Thursday announced the proposed sale of
the flagship store and the Hamleys name, with hopes the new owner
would expand the business worldwide.
   Major U.S. retailers have expressed an interest in buying the
228-year-old store, which holds a royal warrant as a toy and sports
equipment merchant to Queen Elizabeth II.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fans who still buy Elvis Presley
souvenirs now can pay for them with a flashy black credit card
bearing the singer's image.
   Applications for the Presley MasterCard were sent to 200,000
people around the country this week, and Jack Soden, manager of
Presley's former residence in Memphis, said Thursday that more than
a million will be mailed over the next couple of months.
   The new MasterCard is being issued by Leader Federal Savings and
Loan of Memphis.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined in a drifting session Thursday. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials lost 8.36 points at 2,092.28.
   The dollar turned mixed against most key currencies. Gold prices
declined.
   Bond prices finished lower as a mild rally ran out of steam.
   Cotton futures prices plummeted the permitted daily limit of 2
cents a pound as fears of hurricane damage to the Texas cotton crop
receded. Futures prices of oil, precious metals, grains, soybeans,
livestock and stocks all declined.
</TEXT>
