<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     09-16 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Production Unlikely To Resume Until After Weekend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decreasing likelihood that Hurricane Gilbert
would seriously disrupt Gulf of Mexico energy production and
indications that Iraq was balking at coming under OPEC output
restrictions have helped curb the recent oil futures rally.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, wholesale unleaded gasoline
for October delivery closed down 1.39 cents at 45.63 cents a gallon
on Thursday after rising 3.21 cents in the previous session.
   The October wholesale heating oil contract fell 1.37 cents a
gallon to close at 42.70 cents after a 2.24-cent rise on Wednesday.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, settled 50 cents lower at $14.90 per barrel
following an 84-cent rise in volatile trading on Wednesday.
   Crude prices generally had been rising since plunging briefly to
two-year lows on Monday. But factors that strengthened the market
recently began to fade early in the trading day Thursday along with
reports that Hurricane Gilbert was headed for the U.S. Gulf of
Mexico coast, analysts said.
   Oil and gas companies operating in the Gulf had evacuated many
of their personnel from refineries and oil platforms, but observers
said the prospect of a major disruption in oil supplies due to the
approaching hurricane waned.
   ``Traders seem to feel that (Hurricane) Gilbert is not going to
do a lot of damage now,'' said John Hill of Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures.
   Companies reporting the evacuation of oil platforms and
refineries along the Gulf indicated they would not restart
operations until next week.
   But analysts said it was unlikely there would be any spot
shortages of oil products such as gasoline and heating oil and no
effect on contracts scheduled for October delivery.
   Approximately 870,000 barrels per day of oil and 8 million cubic
feet of natural gas are produced at Gulf facilities, according to
the Minerals Management Service.
   Also depressing prices Thursday was a statement from Iraq's oil
minister that his country would not lower its oil output if asked
to do so by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and
instead might raise production.
   The minister's statement punctured the upward momentum that
began Monday when Saudi Arabia's King Fahd made a rare public
statement calling for cooperation among OPEC and non-OPEC
oil-producing nations in restraining oil production.
   Iraq has refused to abide by its OPEC-assigned quota of 1.5
million barrels a day and is reported to be producing about 2.7
million barrels a day. Some observers hoped that after a recent
cease-fire in its 8-year-old war with Iran, Iraq would join with
other OPEC nations in setting production limits that would help
raise prices.
   Other OPEC nations also are exceeding quotas.
   The Iraqi statement also dampened hopes that a Sept. 25 meeting
of OPEC's price monitoring committee would produce substantive
results.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
