<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NewChevrolets     09-16 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Chevrolets,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Family of Chevrolets Introduced</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Prizm is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevrolet has announced two new car lines,
including a new line of four imports designed to give the auto
giant a larger share of the small car market.
   Chevrolet executives, on hand here to preview the new lines for
dealers on Thursday, said the new imports and a new mid-size
domestic series would boost its standing against cars made by rival
Ford Motor Co.
   One of the new lines, the Geo, will have four models and will be
offered only through Chevrolet dealers. Company officials said 80
percent of their 5,000 dealers had agreed to handle the line, using
separate signs and display areas.
   The second line, the Lumina, will replace the Celebrity series.
   Chevrolet Motor Division General Manager Robert D. Burger said
the Geo was created ``to significantly broaden our customer appeal
and to attract buyers who currently may not consider buying a
Chevrolet.''
   Mike Erdman, general marketing manager for Chevrolet, a division
of General Motors Corp., said 40 percent of car sales are small
cars, a market dominated by imports. Erdman said surveys indicate
28 percent of the people who buy imports never have been in a
domestic manufacturer's dealership.
   Promotion of the Geo will mark the ``most aggressive special
marketing effort ever undertaken at Chevrolet,'' Erdman said.
   ``There are 400 nameplates out there,'' he said of the growing
auto market. ``Competing for a share of the market is a real
challenge.''
   Asked about the cost of the imports, considering the current yen
rate, Erdman admitted ``it's going to be a very difficult challenge
to make money on them.'' The yen has risen sharply against the
dollar since 1985, making Japanese products more expensive in the
United States.
   Fred Schaafsma, chief engineer for Chevrolet division, said the
American auto manufacturer is ``actively working with all three of
our affiliates to get costs down.''
   Erdman said he expected the Lumina line to account for 17
percent of Chevrolet's sales by 1991. Lumina will replace all
Celebrity models except the station wagon by the 1990 model year.
The 1990 model of a Lumina sedan will be introduced next spring.
   Burger said Chevrolet expects to sell more than 3 million cars
and trucks in the 1989 model year, provided the U.S. economy
continues to support a forecast of 15 million car and truck sales
next year.
   Chevrolet officials attending a news conference to unveil the
new products vowed the automotive giant would top sales of Ford
cars next year.
   In the 1988 model year, which began Oct. 1, 1987, Ford has sold
1,450,010 cars from its Ford Division through Sept. 10, up 7
percent from the same period in the 1987 model year. Chevrolet has
sold 1,401,190 cars in the current model year, 3 percent fewer than
during the same period in the 1987 model year.
   The Geo line will include the Prizm, Metro and Spectrum cars and
the Tracker utility vehicle. Chevrolet said Geo car prices will
range from $5,999 for the Metro, which is advertised at getting 53
mpg, to $7,610 for the Spectrum, now made in Japan by Isuzu Motors
Ltd.
   The base price for the Tracker will be $10,195. Distribution of
the Tracker will be limited to a dozen states on the East and West
coasts.
   The Tracker and Metro will be made by Suzuki Motor Co. Ltd. in
Japan and the Prizm will be made in Fremont, Calif., by New United
Motor Manufacturing Co. Inc., a joint venture of GM and Toyota
Motor Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
