<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0852EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-AmericanBrands Bjt   09-16 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-American Brands, Bjt,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Brands Rejects Takeover Offer From LeBow Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman and chief executive officer
of American Brands Inc. has rejected the second takeover offer this
year, saying his company wants to remain independent.
   On Thursday, American Brands turned down a buyout proposal from
an investor group led by Bennett S. LeBow, who said he still wants
to buy American Brands' tobacco companies.
   ``The American Brands board of directors continues to believe
that the best long-term interest of American Brands and its
shareholders is that the company continue to operate as an
independent company,'' said William J. Alley. ``American Brands has
no interest in engaging in discussions with Mr. LeBow with respect
to an acquisition of American Brands.''
   American Brands said on Thursday that Brooke Partners L.P.,
which is controlled by LeBow, had filed for federal antitrust
clearance to acquire more than $15 million worth of the company's
stock, and might acquire more than 50 percent of American Brands'
outstanding shares.
   American Brands closed at $48.37{ a share Thursday, down 37{
cents in New York Stock Exchange trading. Based on Thursday's
closing price and the company's roughly 110 million common shares
outstanding, American Brands has a market value of about $5.32
billion.
   It was the second takeover overture this year for American
Brands, which in February acquired E-II Holdings Inc. for $1.1
billion after E-II launched an attempted hostile buyout of American
Brands.
   American Brands said LeBow had approached the company in July
about a possible acquisition of its American Tobacco Co. by Liggett
Group Inc., which LeBow also controls. American Tobacco brands
include Lucky Strike and Tareyton cigarettes and Half & Half pipe
tobacco, among others.
   Americans Brands officials rejected Liggett's proposed deal
saying it was not in the company's best interests.
   In a letter to American's chairman, LeBow said he continued to
believe the ``economic logic of combining Liggett and the tobacco
operations of American Brands compels us to effect such a
combination.''
   LeBow said in the letter that Brooke continued to be interested
in acquiring the Greenwich-based firm's tobacco business rather
than the entire company.
   Alley noted that American Brands was pursuing a restructuring
program aimed at sharpening the company's focus and increasing
shareholder value.
   In the past 16 months, Alley said American Brands has invested
$2 billion to acquire seven businesses designed to ``strengthen''
the company's ``core business strategy.''
   The company has also divested itself of businesses that do not
meet its goals and has purchased 17.1 million million shares of its
common stock, Alley said.
</TEXT>
