<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Inflation     09-16 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Inflation,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Annual Rate Rises to 5.7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's annual rate of inflation rose to 5.7
percent in August, the highest level in three years, the government
announced Friday.
   Nevertheless, the increase from 4.8 percent in July was not as
bad as some investors and economists had feared. Stocks showed
little reaction.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson warned on Wednesday
that there would be a significant increase in the rate because of
Britain's practice of including mortgage rates in the calculation.
   Britain's mortgage rates have climbed sharply, and are in
13-percent range, following the government's move in recent months
to push interest rates up to curb inflation by dampening the
country's strong consumer spending.
   Britain's annual inflation rate has climbed substantially so far
this year and is much higher than had been forecast.
   The rate stood at 3.3 percent in January.
</TEXT>
