<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0938EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-KrogerLawsuit     09-16 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kroger Lawsuit,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investors Sue Over Restructuring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Kroger Co. shareholders have sued to
block the company's proposed $3.8 billion restructuring aimed at
fending off hostile takeovers of the nation's largest supermarket
chain.
   In two class action lawsuits filed Thursday, the shareholders
asked the Hamilton County Court of Common Pleas to prevent Kroger
from adopting the plan.
   Kroger announced the plan Tuesday after the Maryland-based Haft
family, known for its takeover forays, had received government
clearance to buy at least $15 million worth of Kroger stock.
   The lawsuits charge that Kroger executives and directors are
trying to protect their own financial interests, not the interests
of shareholders, with the proposed restructuring.
   ``By proposing the restructuring plan, they have displayed their
predisposition and determination to reject and thwart tender and or
other offers and proposals by third parties for enhanced
shareholder value, so as to preserve and protect their emoluments
and positions with the company,'' one suit contends.
   The suits, both filed as class actions on behalf of all 52,000
Kroger shareholders, seek unspecified damages.
   Kroger declined comment on the suits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
