<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-ShoddyImports     09-16 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Shoddy Imports,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say Italians Worst For Shipping China Poor Quality Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy, followed by the United States, leads the
way in exporting substandard goods to China, the Chinese government
agency responsible for inspecting foreign shipments said Friday.
   An official of the State Administration for the Inspection of
Import and Export Commodities said 37.5 percent of 584 Italian
products inspected in the first half of this year failed to meet
contract standards either in quality or quantity.
   He said the United States was second-worst with 30.87 percent,
or 517 of 1,675 shipments checked, of poor quality.
   The official, who was not identified, was quoted by the official
news agency Xinhua. There was no elaboration on the type of shoddy
goods shipped or which foreign trading partner had the best record.
   The report said 26.25 percent of British commodities, 24.73
percent of French products and 22 percent of goods from Hong Kong
and Macao failed to meet contract standards.
   In total, the administration inspected 56,695 shipments of
imported goods in the first half of the year, and found quality
products in 15.7 percent.
   Serious problems also existed in motor vehicles imported from
the Soviet Union and Eastern European countries, the report said.
   In the past, foreign businessmen accused of selling defective
merchandise to China have complained that their goods were damaged
by mishandling or long delays in transport within China or that the
Chinese ordered equipment unsuitable to their needs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
