<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     09-16 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0319</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed today in trading
swollen by the so-called triple witching hour.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dipped 2.66 to 2,089.62
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers slightly outnumbered losers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 508 up, 472 down and 561
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 57.74 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The session began with an outburst of activity by professional
traders closing out positions linked to expiring stock index
futures and options.
   Some of those September contracts were settled as of the
opening, and others were due to be settled at the close.
   In the last month of each calendar quarter, the simultaneous
expiration of a set of index options, index futures and options on
individual stocks has become a familiar phenomenon, dubbed the
``triple witching hour.''
   Otherwise, analysts said the market was still drifting without
direction.
   The economy has obliged Wall Street lately by showing signs of
growing at a slower, and presumably more sustainable, pace, but the
markets' response hasn't been as enthusiastic as many observers
expected.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Exxon rose [ to 45[; General
Electric gained [ to 42]; Ford Motor dropped ] to 50~, and Merck
was unchanged at 58[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up .01 to 151.61. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index fell .65 to 297.05.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 8.36 to
2,092.28.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 6 on the
NYSE, with 643 up, 749 down and 534 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 161.20 million shares, against 177.22
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
