<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   09-16 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Inventories Up, Sales Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout with business inventories. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The government disclosed new evidence of a weakening economy
today, reporting a rise in business inventories last month that
coincided with a decline in sales.
   The Commerce Department said business inventories rose 0.3
percent in July while sales fell 0.2 percent. The July increase in
inventories was the 19th straight month without a decline. The drop
in sales was the first since January and followed a strong jump of
1.4 percent in June.
   Economists sometimes interpret rising inventories and slowing
sales as a signal of economic weakness. Too many goods in reserve
could lead to production cuts and layoffs at manufacturing plants.
   The report came a day after the Commerce Department said sales
of retail merchandise, a narrower category of sales, fell 0.2
percent in August, and the Federal Reserve said U.S. industry's
operating rate was unchanged in August, the first time in six
months the figure hasn't increased.
   These figures also suggested that the economy is beginning to
weaken after a period of strong growth, thereby easing some fears
of inflation that have dogged the nation's financial markets for
months.
   The Federal Reserve, in an effort to slow the economy by curbing
domestic demand, has been pushing interest rates higher since late
March and economists say the Fed tightening may be beginning to
take hold.
   ``I think things are looking just fine inflation-wise,'' said
Michael K. Evans, head of Evans Economics, a Washington consulting
firm. ``I think the Fed deserves an A. I think they tightened just
enough to slow down the economy without sending it into a
tailspin.''
   Financial markets today showed little reaction to the economic
news, however. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30
industrial stocks had moved less than a point higher by late
morning. In the bond market, prices were little changed, and the
dollar held steady against foreign currencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
