<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-16 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade in a continuation of the technically
based sell-off that began late in Thursday's session, analysts said.
   Prices dropped sharply in the closing minutes Thursday after
wheat traders pushed prices for December and March delivery to new
contract highs. December wheat peaked at $4.32\ a bushel and March
wheat hit $4.36 a bushel.
   Having made new those highs, wheat prices are likely to fall 15
to 20 cents a bushel to levels near recent lows, said Jerry Zusel,
manager of floor operations at the Chicago Board of Trade for
Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   ``I think we're just in a big trading range right now,'' he
said. ``We've been at the higher end of the range and now we're
going toward the lower end of range.''
   Other crop futures have tended to follow the wheat market in
recent weeks.
   Zusel said good prospects for rain this weekend in the Midwest
may spark some buying of corn and soybean futures on ideas that
showers will slow the harvest of those crops. But he said
harvesting was barely underway so a delay at this point probably
wouldn't have much impact on prices.
   In early trading, wheat was 3 cents to 4\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.19 a bushel; corn was 2\
cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.80{ a bushel;
oats were 3{ cents to 5{ cents lower with December at $2.70{ a
bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 8{ cents lower with September at
$8.65 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade in position-evening ahead of this
afternoon's seven-state cattle-on-feed report from the Agriculture
Department.
   Live cattle were .32 cent lower to .15 cent higher with October
at 70.05 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent lower to .05
cent higher with September at 79.80 cents a pound; hogs were .15
cent lower to .15 cent higher with October at 37.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .18 cent to 1.20 cents higher with
February at 48.90 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled mostly lower on Thursday while pork
bellies finished higher.
</TEXT>
