<1ST_LINE>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv16   09-16 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 16,0580</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Friday Sept. 16</NOTE>
<HEAD>Who's Right: The Consumers or the `Experts?'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Considering what they have to put up with, you
could hardly blame Americans if they got down on themselves and
their economy, since it is full of gaps and crunches.
   Week after week they are reminded of wage crunches, tax
crunches, savings crunches, interest rate crunches and home
mortgage crunches. According to a popular magazine, the ranks of
middle management also are being crunched.
   It is an economy that critics say is filled with gaps. Most
glaring, of course, are the trade gap and the budget gap, but there
are also age gaps in corporations and a widening gap between stock
and bond yields.
   Whenever the economy seems to gather strength it is whacked back
by its custodians with talk of higher taxes or interest rates, or
with warnings of bad things to come. Sometimes they act, too, as
when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates.
   Isn't a strong economy what everyone wants? Of course, but not
too strong, says the Fed, because that might bring inflation, a
position that recently provoked economist Howard Ruff into wishing
he were in another business.
   Said Ruff: ``If I were a political cartoonist, I would depict
(Fed Chairman Alan) Greenspan giving a smiling patient, the
economy, a small shot of arsenic while explaining, `You're too
healthy for your own good.'''
   Seldom is optimism offered by those sages who claim to see the
future. And even when it is, it comes wrapped in dull brown paper
and contains a warning that the contents should be considered
dangerous.
   Think about this from an economist-educator: ``Although the
outlook for the economy continues to erode, and there has been a
clear upward shift ... to raise prices, there is no sign that we
are poised to enter a recession.''
   Considering all this, it speaks for the resiliency of the U.S.
consumer that confidence snapped back in August after having been
depressed in June and July.
   That news comes from the Conference Board, a non-profit
organization that regularly measures attitudes of thousands of
households throughout the country, the goal being to ascertain
their buying intentions.
   The latest survey revealed that a rising number of Americans in
August were more optimistic about current and future business
conditions than they had been in the previous two months.
   A greater percentage said that the economy would improve and
that jobs would become more plentiful over the next six months. The
farm mood was found to be improving. And households in general were
impressed by the economy's vigor.
   The professional watchers of the economy, however, will not be
impressed by such things. Instead, they will view this more
confident mood as a danger to be watched, lest it explode into an
inflationary buying boom.
   There is little new in such interpretations; the negative theme
has been ``in'' for more than a year among those who think they
understand how modern economies work.
   But what the ``experts'' sometimes may tend to overlook is the
endurance, economic understanding and sense of responsibility of
the U.S. consumer.
   Could it be that those qualities have something to do with the
fact that the seers' worst fears failed to occur over the past year?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Fri Sept. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
