<HEAD>Ford Announces New Electronics Plant for Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. on Thursday announced
plans to build a $68 million plant near Cadiz, Spain, to make
electronic engine control devices.
   Production is to begin in 1990 at the 100,000-square-foot
factory. When full production is reached about a year later, the
plant will employ about 350 people, the company said.
   The engine control module is the only product scheduled for the
plant now, but it may be expanded to produce other electronic
devices, said Ford spokesman Al Chambers.
   Products from the plant will be sent mainly to other Ford plants
in Europe.
</TEXT>
