<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-16 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Stuck in Tight Range in Europe, Gold Falls Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mixed Friday after remaining
in a tight range during the European session, reflecting indecision
among market participants about the U.S. currency's direction.
   Gold prices tumbled as much as $6.50 an ounce in Europe, hurt by
what bullion brokers called investor disappointment with the
precious metal's declining value over the last few weeks.
   Traders said the dollar spent the day in a range of about 1.8700
West German marks to 1.8780 marks, roughly the same range it was
confined to Thursday. One trader said the market ``just doesn't
have an idea which way to push it.''
   Traders said fear of central bank intervention combined with
internal market resistance is preventing the dollar from rising,
but that the recent news of an improvement in the U.S. trade
deficit is supporting the currency.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6758 to buy one pound, vs. $1.6675 late Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Thursday
included: 1.8763 West German marks, down from 1.8775; 1.5835 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5820; 6.3795 French francs, up from 6.3790;
2.1151 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1160; 1,398.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,398.87; 1.2232 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2225.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.31 yen to a closing 133.76 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 134.25 yen.
   Gold fell in London to $412 a troy ounce, compared with $417.75
late Thursday. Brokers said that because of the metal's failure to
stay above the psychologically important level of $420, many gold
holders were selling.
   In Zurich, gold closed $411 compared with $417.50 late Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.61 to close at $419.84.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market $6.40 a troy
ounce, compared with $6.44 Thursday.
</TEXT>
