<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plunge; Grains Close Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged in late trading
Friday to close sharply lower on the Chicago Board as sellers
chased buyers and found none. Grain futures also closed lower.
   ``The market theoretically probes for the orders,'' said Steve
Freed, grain analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
``In general we ran out of bullish news this week and when the
market started looking for consumption buying and speculative
buying, all it found was sell stops.''
   Sell stops are price levels that trigger large numbers of sell
orders. Massive selling of contracts for November delivery of
soybeans occurred at $8.71 a bushel and $8.66 a bushel, Freed said.
   The November soybean contract closed at $8.58 a bushel, more
than 27 cents below Thursday's final price.
   The declines in corn and wheat prices were not as sharp. Wheat
was supported by indications that new export business was
developing, Freed said, and corn futures drew some support from the
wheat market.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 7 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.02 a bushel; corn was {
cent to 5{ cents lower with September at $2.79 a bushel; oats were
4} cents to 9 cents lower with September at $2.60\ a bushel;
soybeans were 16 cents to 27{ cents lower with September at $8.47 a
bushel.
  
</TEXT>
