<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Interco     09-16 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Interco,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interco Discusses Recapitalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc., target of a $2.6 billion hostile
takeover bid by Cardinal Acquisition Corp., said Friday it was
talking with commercial banks about a possible recapitalization of
the company.
   Cardinal, headed by brothers Steven and Mitchell Rales of
Washington, D.C., has offered to buy the St. Louis-based
manufacturer and retailer of woman's apparel, footwear and
furniture for $70 a share. Interco has rejected the bid as
inadequate.
   Interco said in a filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission that on Tuesday it had entered into an agreement with
certain commercial banks, which were not identified, about their
potential commitment to provide the financing for recapitalization.
Interco said the agreement involved the delivery of preliminary
documentation for the recapitalization proposal.
   Interco said it had not received any financing commitments.
   The company also said in its filing it was considering the sale
or restructuring of its Ethan Allen furniture unit as well as the
sale of its apparel manufacturing division and other assets.
   A recapitalization or sale of Interco's assets would be a
defensive step to thwart the Rales' bid.
</TEXT>
