<FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 1725EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-EasternPilots     09-16 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern Pilots,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines Pilots Take Case to Wall Street</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines pilots, locked in a battle with
management, told financial analysts Friday the ailing airline may
have to be sold or merged with sister carrier Continental Airlines.
   ``Anywhere you look you can see the systematic destruction of
Eastern Airlines,'' said Daniel Vician, vice chairman of the Master
Executive Council of the Eastern pilots' union. ``This airline
cannot be turned around by labor concessions alone.''
   Vician said the union sees three possible options at this point:
negotiation of an acceptable contract agreement between the pilots
and Eastern management, a merger between Eastern and Continental or
a buyout of Eastern by an outside entity.
   Miami-based Eastern and Houston-based Continental, a non-union
carrier, are both subsidiaries of giant Texas Air Corp.
   Eastern continues to sustain heavy losses, posting a net loss of
$89.8 million in the second quarter. Eastern employees have accused
Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo of siphoning off cash, in the form
of management fees, rents on planes and airport gates and
commissions on fuel purchases, from Eastern into its parent company,
   The pilots union and Eastern management are scheduled to meet in
contract negotiations by the end of the month. While Eastern
continues to seek cuts in labor costs, it has indicated it could
seek to freeze the pilots' wages and cut costs through attrition
and longer flying hours.
   The pilots may try to build ``fence agreements'' into the
contract, such as one allowing them to unionize Continental pilots,
according to union sources.
   The airline laid off 4,000 employees early this month. A federal
judge in Washington had ruled Eastern could not lay off unionized
personnel. But the U.S. Court of Appeals later dissolved the order,
saying the carrier would have to post a $4.7 million bond to cover
a month of paychecks should the unions win their case.
   Members of the Machinists union at Eastern began voting Friday
on a contract that would cut pay for mechanics by as much as 20
percent, with even sharper cuts for less-skilled workers.
   It is unusual for a union to advocate a merger. But Vician and
Farrell Kupersmith, an accountant at Touche Ross & Co. who is
working with the pilots, told the analysts a merger between Eastern
and Continental would remove the contentious issue of cash
transfers out of Eastern.
   ``There is no good merger in the (airline) industry with
responsibility to the employees,'' Vician told The Associated Press
after the meeting. ``It would not be our first choice.''
   As for another possible approach, a takeover of Eastern by the
pilots with outside financial backing, Vician said his union has
been advised that ``that is a futile effort.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
