<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Time     09-16 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Time,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Time Stock Soars on Unconfirmed Rumors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of Time Inc. common stock shot up
nearly 10 percent Friday as a flurry of rumors swirled through Wall
Street about the entertainment and media giant.
   Time stock climbed $9.37{ a share to close at $106.87{ in
trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The company said it knew of no reason for the price rise.
   Analysts said rumors circulated during the day that Time planned
to sell its book operations, might merge with another company, had
become the takeover target of a major European publishing company
and had hired a prominent firm specializing in leveraged buyouts.
   J. Kendrick Noble, a securities analyst for PaineWebber, said
that while there might be a ``grain of truth behind each of the
rumnors, I don't believe there is anything significant happening at
Time Inc. at the moment.''
   He said the market might ``be looking for the next target''
after Macmillan Inc., which is the subject of competing takeover
offers.
   Asked to comment on the sharp stock advance, Time spokesman Lou
Slovinsky said, ``We know of no reason why our stock has risen.''
   He added that the compoany did not comment on rumors or its
proprietary business relationships.
   Time, which has about 58 million shares of common stock
outstanding, is one of the world's largest magazine and book
publishers and has interests in pay television services as well as
in cable television.
   In the six months ended June 30, it reported a profit of $150
million, or $2.58 a share, up from $124 million, or $2.06 a share,
a year earlier. Revenue rose to $2.17 billion from $1.98 billion.
</TEXT>
