<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Gates-Dyneer     09-16 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gates-Dyneer,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gates Corp. to Acquire Dyneer Spun Steel Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gates Corp. has agreed to acquire Dyneer Corp.'s
Spun Steel Inc. subsidiary based in Bloomfield Hills, Mich., Gates
said Thursday.
   Details of the sale by Dyneer, which is based in Scottsdale,
Ariz., were not disclosed. The sale was expected to be closed by
the end of September.
   Spun Steel manufactures pulleys, tensioners and accessory drive
systems for the auto industry from plants at Dothan, Ala., and
Strathroy and Windsor, Ontario, Canada.
   Spun Steel president Robert D. Emrick said the firm's 1988 sales
were expected to be approximately $50 million.
   The company will become an independent subsidiary of Gates,
according to Donald E. Miller, Gates president and chief operating
officer.
   Miller said all Spun Steel employees and management are expected
to remain with the company, and that ``Gates intends to make major
investments in this business to expand it into the worldwide
automotive market.''
</TEXT>
