<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Sundstrand     09-16 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Sundstrand,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Sundstrand Agrees To Record Defense Fraud Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sundstrand Corp. has agreed to pay the
government close to $100 million in a record defense fraud
settlement involving alleged schemes to overbill the Defense
Department for airplane parts, according to Business Week magazine.
   A story in the magazine's Sept. 26 issue, released Thursday,
quoted unidentified sources it said were familiar with the case as
saying the company would enter a guilty plea in the next few weeks,
as part of a sealed agreement in federal court in Chicago.
   Business Week said its sources also indicated Sundstrand faces
possible suspension by the Pentagon, which accounts for 42 percent
of the company's $1.4 billion in annual sales.
   Furthermore, several senior Sundstrand executives could be
indicted as soon as next month for their alleged roles in the
scheme, the magazine stated.
   ``I have no idea what they're going to print so there would be
no way I could comment,'' Sundstrand spokesman Claude Vernam said
when contacted by The Associated Press.
   Even after company officials have read the Business Week
article, Vernam said he did not expect Sundstrand to comment beyond
what it has disclosed in its quarterly reports.
   The aerospace contractor revealed in a 1987 financial filing
with the government that it would face criminal charges resulting
from two federal grand jury investigations into alleged overcharges.
   Sundstrand reported that the government was seeking repayment of
$13.5 million plus interest and $102.9 million plus interest in two
separate disputes over contract pricing.
   Sundstrand is based in Rockford, Ill., and operates a subsidiary
in Redmond, Wash., near Seattle, that is part of its Advanced
Technology Group.
   In its annual report to the Securities and Exchange Commission
earlier this year, Sundstrand acknowledged the ``government has
advised that it intends to charge the company with criminal
violations'' in Rockford and Seattle.
   Sundstrand, which makes flight data equipment, engine start-up
systems and other electronic equipment for commercial and military
aircraft, said in its SEC filing that it was ``in the process of
entering a settlement in one or possibly both actions.''
   Such settlements, the company also noted in the filing, ``could
result in the imposition of materially adverse fines and
penalties.''
   Sundstrand began putting money in reserve two years ago to cover
settlement and legal expenses related to the dispute. The company
added $76 million in the second quarter to the reserve, which
already held $50.2 million, resulting in a $16.5 million net loss
for the period.
</TEXT>
