<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MarketMerger     09-16 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Market Merger,0304</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Declines to Take Quick Action on Grocery Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge, saying a quick ruling would
be ``almost shooting from the hip,'' declined to make a decision
Friday on whether to allow the $2.5 billion merger of Lucky and
Alpha Beta to proceed.
   After three hours of arguments by attorneys, U.S. District Judge
David Kenyon asked for more data on the ``relevant market area''
affected by the proposed merger.
   Attorneys said they could supply the information by Wednesday
and Kenyon said he would rule soon after that.
   Kenyon left in place a temporary restraining order which bars
completion of the acquisition of Lucky by American Stores, parent
company of Alpha Beta.
   California Attorney General John Van de Kamp has filed suit to
stop the merger. He claims that transaction coupled with the recent
merger of Safeway and Vons supermarkets will decrease competition
and mean higher prices for California consumers.
   Deputy Attorney General Chester Horne argued that the merger
violates the Clayton Antitrust Act and said that the U.S. Supreme
Court has never approved a merger between two such gigantic market
chains.
   He suggested the merger will virtually eliminate ``mom and pop
grocery stores,'' which will be unable to compete against the
giants.
   ``Without the entry of signficant competititors there will be no
competition in this state if this merger is allowed to go
through,'' Horne said.
   Attorney Frank Rothman, representing American Stores Cos., the
parent company of Alpha Beta, said the consumer will benefit
because Alpha Beta plans to adopt Lucky's low-price structure.
   When Kenyon expressed skepticism about whether low prices would
last, Rothman responded that if the chain raised prices, ``Everyone
else in the marketplace would cut our heart out.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
